    {
      "title": "CHC 110 - Medical Errors (2 hours)",
      "lessons": [
        {
          "title": "CHC 110: Medical Errors Overview",
          "durationMinutes": 17,
          "content": "CHC 110: Medical Errors Overview\nCHC 110: Medical Errors Overview\nPreventing Errors Starts With Attention\n\nMedical errors can happen when information is missed, misunderstood, done too quickly, or not reported. Home Health Aides help prevent errors by following the care plan, communicating clearly, and reporting changes promptly.\n\nLesson Objectives\n\nBy the end of this module, the learner should understand what medical errors are and how the HHA can help reduce risk in the home setting.\n\nDefine medical errors in simple terms.\nIdentify common error risks in home care.\nUse the care plan, assignment sheet, and agency policy to avoid unsafe actions.\nExplain why reporting, documentation, and communication reduce errors.\nRecognize that the HHA should never hide, ignore, or guess about a possible error.\nWhat Is a Medical Error?\n\nA medical error is a preventable mistake or missed action that could harm a client or lead to unsafe care. Some errors cause harm right away. Others are near misses, meaning harm almost happened but was prevented in time. Near misses still matter because they show where safety can improve.\n\nWhy HHAs Study Medical Errors\n\nA Home Health Aide is not responsible for diagnosing illness or making medical decisions. However, the aide is often the person who notices day-to-day changes first. Careful observation, accurate reporting, and following directions help the nurse and care team prevent harm.\n\nProfessional Boundary\n\nIf a client or family asks you to do something outside the care plan, stop and report. Good intentions do not make an unsafe task safe.\n\nQuick Learner Check\nWhat is a medical error?\nWhat is a near miss?\nWhy is the HHA important in preventing errors?\nSuggested Answers\nA medical error is a preventable mistake or missed action that could cause unsafe care or harm.\nA near miss is an event where harm almost happened but was caught or avoided before reaching the client.\nThe HHA spends time with the client, follows the care plan, observes changes, and reports concerns to the supervisor or nurse.\nRemember\n\nErrors are prevented by slowing down, following the care plan, asking questions, and reporting early.\n\nReference for instructor review: AHRQ Patient Safety\nLinks to an external site.\n | The Joint Commission Speak Up\nLinks to an external site.\n\nCanvas source: https://hic.instructure.com/courses/287/pages/chc-110-medical-errors-overview?module_item_id=3223"
        },
        {
          "title": "CHC 110 Topic 1: Common Medical Errors in Home Care",
          "durationMinutes": 17,
          "content": "CHC 110 Topic 1: Common Medical Errors in Home Care\nCHC 110 Topic 1: Common Medical Errors in Home Care\nKnowing Where Mistakes Can Happen\n\nHome care has unique risks because care happens in a private home with family routines, distractions, and changing conditions.\n\nCommon Error Areas\n\nMany errors in home care are connected to communication, timing, infection control, falls, medication assistance, diet instructions, and documentation. The HHA helps reduce these risks by following directions exactly and reporting anything that does not seem right.\n\nNot following the care plan or doing unassigned tasks.\nForgetting to report a change in condition.\nDocumenting late, vaguely, or inaccurately.\nAssisting with the wrong diet, fluid amount, or activity level.\nFailing to use infection control practices.\nLeaving fall hazards in the home.\nAssisting with self-administration of medications outside agency policy.\nMisunderstanding verbal instructions and not asking for clarification.\nExamples in Daily Care\n\nA client may be on thickened liquids, but a family member offers regular water. A client may be told to use a walker, but the walker is in another room. A client may complain of new chest discomfort, but the aide assumes it is indigestion and does not report it. These situations can become serious if they are ignored.\n\nRed Flags That Require Reporting\nNew or worsening pain, shortness of breath, dizziness, confusion, weakness, or fever.\nA fall, near fall, medication concern, missed visit, or wrong supply.\nA client refusing ordered care or asking for care outside the plan.\nUnsafe home conditions such as no food, spoiled food, broken equipment, or blocked exits.\nQuick Learner Check\nName two common error risks in home care.\nWhy can a near fall be important even if the client was not injured?\nWhat should an HHA do if a family member asks for care outside the plan?\nSuggested Answers\nExamples include poor documentation, missed reporting, infection control mistakes, fall hazards, diet mistakes, and medication assistance outside policy.\nA near fall shows that the client may be unsafe and the care plan or environment may need review.\nThe HHA should not perform unassigned care. The aide should explain that care must follow the plan and report the request to the supervisor.\nRemember\n\nSmall warning signs can prevent large problems when they are reported quickly.\n\nReference for instructor review: AHRQ Patient Safety\nLinks to an external site.\n | The Joint Commission Speak Up\nLinks to an external site.\n\nCanvas source: https://hic.instructure.com/courses/287/pages/chc-110-topic-1-common-medical-errors-in-home-care?module_item_id=3224"
        },
        {
          "title": "CHC 110 Topic 2: Preventing Errors With the Care Plan and Communication",
          "durationMinutes": 17,
          "content": "CHC 110 Topic 2: Preventing Errors With the Care Plan and Communication\nCHC 110 Topic 2: Preventing Errors With the Care Plan and Communication\nUse the Plan, Ask Questions, Confirm Understanding\n\nThe care plan is one of the main tools used to prevent medical errors. It tells the HHA what to do, what not to do, and when to report.\n\nUse the Care Plan Every Visit\n\nReview the assignment before starting care. The care plan may include mobility instructions, diet orders, bathing assistance, skin observation, infection control instructions, safety precautions, and reporting requirements. Do not rely only on memory.\n\nClear Communication\n\nErrors often happen when information is incomplete or misunderstood. Use clear, respectful communication with the client, family, supervisor, and care team. Repeat important instructions back to confirm understanding.\n\nAsk for clarification if directions are unclear.\nUse exact observations instead of opinions.\nReport changes promptly.\nDo not pass along private information to people who do not need to know.\nDocument care as soon as possible after completing it.\nThe Handoff\n\nA handoff happens when information is shared from one caregiver or team member to another. A good handoff includes what care was provided, what changed, what still needs attention, and any safety concerns. Missing information during handoff can lead to repeated care, missed care, or unsafe care.\n\nUse Exact Words When Needed\n\nIf a client says, “I feel like I cannot breathe,” report the client’s exact words. Exact words help the nurse understand urgency.\n\nQuick Learner Check\nWhy should the HHA review the care plan every visit?\nWhat should the aide do if instructions are unclear?\nWhat information belongs in a good handoff?\nSuggested Answers\nThe care plan may change and it tells the HHA what care is assigned, what precautions are needed, and what must be reported.\nThe aide should ask the supervisor or nurse for clarification before proceeding.\nA good handoff includes care provided, changes observed, remaining concerns, and safety issues.\nRemember\n\nWhen in doubt, ask before acting. Guessing creates risk.\n\nReference for instructor review: AHRQ Patient Safety\nLinks to an external site.\n | The Joint Commission Speak Up\nLinks to an external site.\n\nCanvas source: https://hic.instructure.com/courses/287/pages/chc-110-topic-2-preventing-errors-with-the-care-plan-and-communication?module_item_id=3225"
        },
        {
          "title": "CHC 110 Topic 3: Reporting, Documenting, and Responding to Errors",
          "durationMinutes": 17,
          "content": "CHC 110 Topic 3: Reporting, Documenting, and Responding to Errors\nCHC 110 Topic 3: Reporting, Documenting, and Responding to Errors\nReport Early and Honestly\n\nErrors and near misses must be reported promptly. Reporting is not about blame; it is about protecting the client and improving safety.\n\nIf an Error or Near Miss Happens\n\nStay calm and make sure the client is safe. Follow agency policy. Notify the supervisor or nurse immediately. If there is an emergency, call 911 first according to policy and then notify the agency.\n\nDo not hide the error.\nDo not change documentation to cover up what happened.\nDo not blame the client, family, or another worker.\nDo not give medical advice beyond your role.\nReport facts: what happened, when it happened, who was present, and the client’s condition.\nDocumenting Facts\n\nDocumentation should be timely, accurate, and objective. Write what you saw, heard, did, and reported. Avoid opinions such as “client was being difficult.” Instead, describe the behavior: “client refused shower and stated, ‘I am too tired today.’”\n\nLearning From Mistakes\n\nA safe care team uses errors and near misses to improve systems. For example, if the aide almost gives the client the wrong meal because the diet instructions are hard to find, the agency may improve how diet information is displayed. Reporting helps fix the problem before harm occurs.\n\nEmergency Reminder\n\nIf the client has signs of a medical emergency, such as severe shortness of breath, chest pain, sudden weakness, or loss of consciousness, follow emergency procedures immediately.\n\nQuick Learner Check\nWhat is the first priority if an error happens?\nWhy should errors and near misses be reported?\nWhat is an example of objective documentation?\nSuggested Answers\nThe first priority is client safety. Stay calm, get help, and follow agency policy.\nReporting helps protect the client, alert the care team, and prevent the same problem from happening again.\nObjective documentation states facts, such as “client refused shower and stated, ‘I am too tired today,’” instead of personal opinions.\nRemember\n\nHonest reporting protects the client, the aide, and the care team.\n\nReference for instructor review: AHRQ Patient Safety\nLinks to an external site.\n | The Joint Commission Speak Up\nLinks to an external site.\n\nCanvas source: https://hic.instructure.com/courses/287/pages/chc-110-topic-3-reporting-documenting-and-responding-to-errors?module_item_id=3226"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "CHC 111 - Domestic Violence (2 hours)",
      "lessons": [
        {
          "title": "CHC 111: Domestic Violence Overview",
          "durationMinutes": 17,
          "content": "CHC 111: Domestic Violence Overview\nCHC 111: Domestic Violence Overview\nUnderstanding Domestic Violence in Home Care\n\nDomestic violence is a pattern of harmful behavior used to control another person. The HHA may notice warning signs during home visits and must respond with safety, respect, and proper reporting.\n\nLesson Objectives\nDefine domestic violence in simple terms.\nIdentify common types of abuse and control.\nRecognize possible warning signs during home care visits.\nUse trauma-informed communication when a client may be unsafe.\nFollow agency policy for safety, reporting, and documentation.\nWhy This Module Matters\n\nHome care workers enter the client’s private space. This means an HHA may notice injuries, fear, controlling behavior, unsafe living conditions, or changes that other members of the care team do not see. Your role is not to investigate or prove abuse. Your role is to observe, support, protect privacy, report concerns, and get emergency help when someone is in immediate danger.\n\nDomestic violence can happen to people of any age, gender, culture, income level, sexual orientation, or disability status. It may involve a spouse, partner, family member, caregiver, or another person in the home.\n\nKey Ideas\nAbuse is about power and control, not just anger.\nA client may not be ready or able to leave an unsafe situation.\nPrivacy and safety are critical when speaking with a client.\nThe HHA should follow the care plan, chain of command, and agency policy.\nCall 911 immediately if there is immediate danger.\nQuick Learner Check\nWhat is the HHA’s role if domestic violence is suspected?\nCan domestic violence happen to older adults or people with disabilities?\nWhat should the aide do if someone is in immediate danger?\nSuggested Answers\nThe HHA observes, supports the client respectfully, protects privacy, documents facts, and reports concerns according to agency policy. The aide does not investigate or confront the suspected abuser.\nYes. Domestic violence and abuse can affect people of any age, ability, gender, culture, income level, or relationship type.\nCall 911 immediately and follow agency emergency policy.\nRemember\n\nYou do not need proof to report a concern through the proper chain of command. Safety comes first.\n\nSources for Instructor Review\nCDC: About Intimate Partner Violence\nLinks to an external site.\nNational Domestic Violence Hotline: Warning Signs\nLinks to an external site.\nSAMHSA: Trauma-Informed Approach\nLinks to an external site.\nNational Institute on Aging: Elder Abuse\nLinks to an external site.\n\nCanvas source: https://hic.instructure.com/courses/287/pages/chc-111-domestic-violence-overview?module_item_id=3136"
        },
        {
          "title": "CHC 111 Topic 1: What Domestic Violence Means",
          "durationMinutes": 17,
          "content": "CHC 111 Topic 1: What Domestic Violence Means\nCHC 111 Topic 1: What Domestic Violence Means\nWhat Domestic Violence Means\n\nDomestic violence is more than physical injury. It is a pattern of behaviors used to gain power and control over another person.\n\nDefinition for Home Care\n\nDomestic violence may include physical harm, threats, intimidation, emotional abuse, sexual abuse, financial control, isolation, stalking, or coercion. It can occur between intimate partners, family members, or caregivers. In home care, the word “client” may include an older adult, an adult with a disability, or another vulnerable person who depends on help at home.\n\nThe person causing harm may seem polite when the HHA is present. They may answer questions for the client, refuse privacy, watch the client closely, or try to control what the aide sees. This can make abuse hard to recognize.\n\nPower and Control\n\nAbuse often follows a pattern. The abusive person may use fear, dependence, money, medication, transportation, housing, immigration concerns, children, pets, or family pressure to keep control. The client may feel trapped, ashamed, afraid, loyal, financially dependent, or worried that no one will believe them.\n\nImportant HHA Boundaries\nDo not confront the suspected abuser.\nDo not promise secrecy if safety or reporting rules apply.\nDo not tell the client what they “must” do.\nDo not judge the client for staying or returning.\nDo report concerns promptly according to agency policy.\nQuick Learner Check\nWhy is domestic violence described as a pattern?\nWhy should the HHA avoid confronting the suspected abuser?\nName one reason a client may feel unable to leave.\nSuggested Answers\nBecause abuse often involves repeated behaviors used to control, frighten, isolate, or harm another person.\nConfronting the suspected abuser can increase danger for the client and the aide. The HHA should follow agency reporting and safety procedures.\nPossible reasons include fear, money, housing, transportation, medication dependence, family pressure, shame, threats, children, pets, or disability needs.\nRemember\n\nDomestic violence is about control. The aide’s response should increase safety, not increase danger.\n\nCanvas source: https://hic.instructure.com/courses/287/pages/chc-111-topic-1-what-domestic-violence-means?module_item_id=3137"
        },
        {
          "title": "CHC 111 Topic 2: Types of Abuse and Control",
          "durationMinutes": 17,
          "content": "CHC 111 Topic 2: Types of Abuse and Control\nCHC 111 Topic 2: Types of Abuse and Control\nTypes of Abuse and Control\n\nAbuse can be physical, emotional, sexual, financial, digital, spiritual, or neglectful. Some abuse leaves marks, and some does not.\n\nCommon Types of Abuse\nPhysical abuse: hitting, pushing, grabbing, burning, choking, restraining, or blocking movement.\nEmotional or verbal abuse: insults, humiliation, threats, blaming, intimidation, or making the client feel worthless.\nSexual abuse: unwanted sexual contact, pressure, threats, or sexual activity when the person cannot consent.\nFinancial abuse: taking money, controlling bank cards, stealing benefits, forcing signatures, or preventing access to resources.\nIsolation: keeping the client away from family, friends, phone calls, transportation, appointments, or private conversations.\nDigital abuse: tracking phone use, reading messages, using cameras, controlling passwords, or monitoring location.\nNeglect: failing to provide food, hygiene, medication help, safe shelter, or medical attention when the person depends on care.\nAbuse May Be Hidden\n\nA client may minimize what happened or explain injuries in a way that does not match what you observe. A person causing harm may act helpful in front of the aide. The HHA should document objective facts and report concerns without trying to prove what happened.\n\nRespectful Language\n\nUse calm, nonjudgmental language. Instead of saying, “Why do you let this happen?” say, “I am concerned about your safety. I can report this concern to my supervisor and help connect you with support according to agency policy.”\n\nQuick Learner Check\nDoes abuse always leave visible injuries?\nWhat is financial abuse?\nWhy should documentation be objective?\nSuggested Answers\nNo. Emotional, financial, digital, sexual, isolation, and neglect-related abuse may not leave visible marks.\nFinancial abuse includes taking or controlling a client’s money, benefits, bank cards, property, or financial choices without permission.\nObjective documentation records what was seen, heard, or reported without guesses, blame, or personal opinions.\nRemember\n\nIf something feels unsafe or does not match the client’s usual pattern, report the concern. Patterns matter.\n\nCanvas source: https://hic.instructure.com/courses/287/pages/chc-111-topic-2-types-of-abuse-and-control?module_item_id=3138"
        },
        {
          "title": "CHC 111 Topic 3: Warning Signs During Home Visits",
          "durationMinutes": 17,
          "content": "CHC 111 Topic 3: Warning Signs During Home Visits\nCHC 111 Topic 3: Warning Signs During Home Visits\nWarning Signs During Home Visits\n\nThe HHA may notice physical, emotional, environmental, or relationship clues that suggest abuse or danger.\n\nPhysical and Health Warning Signs\nUnexplained bruises, burns, cuts, fractures, or repeated injuries.\nInjuries in different stages of healing.\nFrequent missed appointments or delayed medical care.\nPoor hygiene, untreated pain, dehydration, malnutrition, or medication problems.\nClient seems fearful, withdrawn, anxious, tearful, or unusually quiet around one person.\nBehavior and Relationship Warning Signs\nAnother person refuses to leave the room or answer allows no privacy.\nAnother person answers every question for the client.\nClient looks at another person before speaking or seems afraid to disagree.\nClient is not allowed to use the phone, see visitors, or make choices.\nStories about injuries change or do not match what you observe.\nSudden changes in mood, sleep, appetite, grooming, or daily routine.\nHome Environment Warning Signs\nUnsafe living conditions that the client cannot correct alone.\nNo food, clean clothing, medications, or needed equipment available.\nLocked rooms, blocked exits, missing glasses/hearing aids/mobility aids, or controlled access to money or identification.\nSigns that the client is being isolated from support people.\nQuick Learner Check\nName two possible physical warning signs.\nWhat does it mean if another person will not allow the client to speak privately?\nDoes one warning sign always prove abuse?\nSuggested Answers\nPossible signs include unexplained bruises, burns, cuts, fractures, repeated injuries, injuries in different stages of healing, untreated pain, or poor hygiene.\nIt may be a safety concern because the client may not be free to speak honestly. The HHA should not force privacy if unsafe, but should report the concern.\nNo. One sign may not prove abuse, but patterns, repeated concerns, or fear should be reported according to agency policy.\nRemember\n\nObserve carefully. You are not expected to prove abuse, but you are expected to report concerns.\n\nCanvas source: https://hic.instructure.com/courses/287/pages/chc-111-topic-3-warning-signs-during-home-visits?module_item_id=3139"
        },
        {
          "title": "CHC 111 Topic 4: Trauma-Informed Communication",
          "durationMinutes": 17,
          "content": "CHC 111 Topic 4: Trauma-Informed Communication\nCHC 111 Topic 4: Trauma-Informed Communication\nTrauma-Informed Communication\n\nA trauma-informed response helps the client feel safer, respected, and in control of what they can choose.\n\nWhat Trauma-Informed Means\n\nTrauma-informed care recognizes that a person may have experienced fear, control, violence, humiliation, or loss of safety. The HHA should avoid actions that make the client feel blamed, rushed, trapped, or judged.\n\nImportant principles include safety, trust, choice, collaboration, empowerment, and respect for culture, history, and personal experience.\n\nHow to Speak With the Client\nUse a calm voice and private setting when it is safe to do so.\nAsk permission before discussing sensitive concerns.\nUse supportive statements such as, “I am concerned about your safety.”\nBelieve the client’s feelings even if you do not know all the facts.\nAvoid blaming questions like “Why didn’t you leave?”\nOffer choices within your role, such as whether the client wants you to call the supervisor while you are present.\nWhat Not to Say\nDo not say, “You should just leave.” Leaving can be dangerous and complicated.\nDo not say, “I would never tolerate that.” This can shame the client.\nDo not promise, “I won’t tell anyone.” Reporting rules and safety policies may require action.\nDo not pressure the client to share details they are not ready to share.\nQuick Learner Check\nName one trauma-informed principle.\nWhy should the aide avoid asking, “Why didn’t you leave?”\nCan the HHA promise to keep abuse secret?\nSuggested Answers\nExamples include safety, trust, choice, collaboration, empowerment, and cultural respect.\nIt can sound blaming and may not recognize fear, danger, finances, disability needs, family pressure, or other barriers.\nNo. The HHA should be honest that safety concerns may need to be reported according to agency policy and law.\nRemember\n\nThe way you respond can either increase shame or increase safety. Choose calm, respectful, nonjudgmental words.\n\nCanvas source: https://hic.instructure.com/courses/287/pages/chc-111-topic-4-trauma-informed-communication?module_item_id=3140"
        },
        {
          "title": "CHC 111 Topic 5: Safety and Privacy in the Home",
          "durationMinutes": 17,
          "content": "CHC 111 Topic 5: Safety and Privacy in the Home\nCHC 111 Topic 5: Safety and Privacy in the Home\nSafety and Privacy\n\nDomestic violence situations can become dangerous quickly. The HHA must protect the client, self, and agency by following safety procedures.\n\nImmediate Danger\n\nIf violence is happening now, weapons are present, threats are immediate, a child or vulnerable adult is in danger, or someone needs urgent medical help, call 911. Leave the home if your own safety is at risk and follow agency emergency policy.\n\nPrivacy Matters\n\nNever leave printed domestic violence information where the suspected abuser may find it unless agency policy specifically directs you to do so. Do not send texts, emails, or voicemail messages that could put the client at greater risk. A client’s phone, computer, or location may be monitored.\n\nSafer HHA Practices\nKnow your agency’s emergency procedure before a crisis happens.\nKeep your phone accessible according to agency policy.\nAvoid arguing with or confronting the suspected abuser.\nDo not transport a client to an unknown location unless assigned and approved by agency policy.\nIf you need to leave for safety, contact your supervisor as soon as possible.\nUse private conversation only when it is safe and natural.\nQuick Learner Check\nWhen should 911 be called?\nWhy can leaving pamphlets or sending messages be unsafe?\nShould the HHA confront the suspected abuser?\nSuggested Answers\nCall 911 when there is immediate danger, active violence, urgent medical need, threats, weapons, or danger to a child or vulnerable adult.\nThe suspected abuser may find the information or monitor the client’s phone, computer, voicemail, or location, which could increase danger.\nNo. Confrontation can increase risk. The HHA should follow safety and reporting procedures.\nRemember\n\nSafety planning is specialized. Your role is to protect immediate safety, report concerns, and follow agency procedure.\n\nCanvas source: https://hic.instructure.com/courses/287/pages/chc-111-topic-5-safety-and-privacy-in-the-home?module_item_id=3141"
        },
        {
          "title": "CHC 111 Topic 6: Documentation and Reporting",
          "durationMinutes": 17,
          "content": "CHC 111 Topic 6: Documentation and Reporting\nCHC 111 Topic 6: Documentation and Reporting\nDocumentation and Reporting\n\nClear documentation and prompt reporting help the care team respond while protecting the client and the aide.\n\nDocument Facts, Not Opinions\n\nDocumentation should be objective, specific, and timely. Write what you saw, heard, smelled, or were told. Avoid diagnosing, blaming, or guessing. Use quotation marks for the client’s exact words when possible.\n\nObjective Examples\nInstead of: “The husband is abusive.” Write: “Client stated, ‘He grabbed my arm last night.’ Purple bruise observed on left upper arm, approximately 2 inches wide.”\nInstead of: “The daughter is neglecting her.” Write: “No food observed in refrigerator. Client stated she had not eaten since yesterday morning.”\nInstead of: “Client is scared of him.” Write: “Client became silent and looked down when spouse entered the room.”\nReporting Path\n\nReport suspected domestic violence, abuse, neglect, exploitation, or unsafe conditions according to agency policy and state requirements. This may include contacting your supervisor, nurse, case manager, Adult Protective Services, Child Protective Services, law enforcement, or emergency services depending on the situation and policy. The HHA does not decide to ignore a concern because there is no proof.\n\nConfidentiality\n\nShare information only with people who are allowed to know it through the care plan, agency policy, and reporting requirements. Do not gossip, post, text personal details, or discuss the situation with people outside the care team.\n\nQuick Learner Check\nWhat should documentation focus on?\nWhy should exact client words be placed in quotation marks?\nWho should the HHA report concerns to first if there is no immediate danger?\nSuggested Answers\nDocumentation should focus on objective facts: what was seen, heard, smelled, observed, or reported.\nQuotation marks show the statement came from the client and was not the aide’s interpretation.\nFollow agency policy. Usually the HHA reports promptly to the supervisor, nurse, or agency contact listed in the chain of command.\nRemember\n\nGood documentation is clear, factual, timely, and private.\n\nCanvas source: https://hic.instructure.com/courses/287/pages/chc-111-topic-6-documentation-and-reporting?module_item_id=3142"
        },
        {
          "title": "CHC 111 Topic 7: Vulnerable Adults, Elder Abuse, and Disability",
          "durationMinutes": 17,
          "content": "CHC 111 Topic 7: Vulnerable Adults, Elder Abuse, and Disability\nCHC 111 Topic 7: Vulnerable Adults, Elder Abuse, and Disability\nVulnerable Adults and Abuse\n\nOlder adults and people with disabilities may face extra risks when they depend on others for care, transportation, money, medication, or communication.\n\nWhy Risk May Be Higher\n\nA vulnerable adult may rely on another person for bathing, meals, medications, money, housing, mobility, interpretation, transportation, or communication. This dependence can make it harder to report abuse or leave an unsafe situation.\n\nThe person causing harm may be a spouse, adult child, relative, caregiver, neighbor, or another trusted person. Abuse can also happen when care is withheld, rushed, humiliating, unsafe, or used as punishment.\n\nPossible Signs in Vulnerable Adults\nUntreated injuries, pressure injuries, pain, poor hygiene, or missed medications.\nFear of a caregiver or sudden withdrawal when a certain person enters.\nLack of food, clean clothing, glasses, hearing aids, dentures, mobility aids, or medical supplies.\nUnpaid bills, missing money, sudden changes in who controls finances, or pressure to sign documents.\nClient is prevented from speaking privately or making choices.\nUnsafe home conditions that are not being corrected.\nRespecting Ability and Choice\n\nDo not assume a client lacks capacity because they are older, disabled, quiet, or dependent on care. Speak to the client directly when possible. Offer choices. Follow communication supports and report concerns if someone blocks the client from communicating.\n\nQuick Learner Check\nWhy can dependence increase abuse risk?\nName one sign of financial abuse.\nShould the aide assume an older adult cannot make choices?\nSuggested Answers\nDependence can give another person control over food, medication, money, transportation, communication, or housing, making it harder for the client to get help.\nExamples include missing money, unpaid bills despite available funds, sudden financial control by another person, pressure to sign papers, or missing belongings.\nNo. The aide should speak respectfully to the client, support choices, and follow the care plan and agency policy.\nRemember\n\nDependence should never be used to control, punish, humiliate, or silence a client.\n\nCanvas source: https://hic.instructure.com/courses/287/pages/chc-111-topic-7-vulnerable-adults-elder-abuse-and-disability?module_item_id=3143"
        },
        {
          "title": "CHC 111 Topic 8: HHA Role, Boundaries, and Support Resources",
          "durationMinutes": 17,
          "content": "CHC 111 Topic 8: HHA Role, Boundaries, and Support Resources\nCHC 111 Topic 8: HHA Role, Boundaries, and Support Resources\nHHA Role and Support Resources\n\nThe HHA supports safety by observing, reporting, documenting, protecting privacy, and connecting concerns to the proper care team member.\n\nWhat the HHA Can Do\nObserve and document objective signs of possible abuse or danger.\nListen calmly if the client chooses to speak.\nUse supportive, nonjudgmental language.\nReport concerns promptly through the chain of command.\nCall 911 for immediate danger or urgent medical need.\nFollow agency policy for Adult Protective Services, Child Protective Services, law enforcement, or domestic violence resources.\nWhat the HHA Should Not Do\nDo not investigate, interrogate, or try to prove abuse.\nDo not confront the suspected abuser.\nDo not make promises you cannot keep.\nDo not give legal advice or tell the client what decision to make.\nDo not share personal phone numbers or make private arrangements outside agency policy.\nDo not post or discuss the situation outside the care team.\nSupport Resources\n\nFor instructor and learner awareness, national domestic violence support is available through the National Domestic Violence Hotline at 1-800-799-SAFE (7233), TTY 1-800-787-3224, and thehotline.org. If using this information with a client, follow agency policy and consider whether the client’s phone, computer, mail, or location may be monitored.\n\nIn immediate danger, call 911. For suspected abuse, neglect, or exploitation of a vulnerable adult, follow agency policy for contacting Adult Protective Services or the appropriate state/local reporting system.\n\nQuick Learner Check\nName two things the HHA can do when domestic violence is suspected.\nName one thing the HHA should not do.\nWhat national hotline number can learners be aware of?\nSuggested Answers\nThe HHA can observe, document facts, listen calmly, report concerns, protect privacy, follow agency policy, and call 911 for immediate danger.\nThe HHA should not investigate, confront the suspected abuser, give legal advice, promise secrecy, or make private arrangements outside agency policy.\nThe National Domestic Violence Hotline is 1-800-799-SAFE (7233). TTY is 1-800-787-3224.\nRemember\n\nStay within your role. A calm report through the right channel can help protect the client without putting anyone at greater risk.\n\nCanvas source: https://hic.instructure.com/courses/287/pages/chc-111-topic-8-hha-role-boundaries-and-support-resources?module_item_id=3144"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "CHC 112 - Nutrition (3 hours)",
      "lessons": [
        {
          "title": "CHC 112: Nutrition Overview",
          "durationMinutes": 17,
          "content": "CHC 112: Nutrition Overview\nCHC 112: Nutrition Overview\nNutrition and the HHA Role\n\nNutrition is part of safe, respectful home care. Food can support healing, comfort, independence, energy, mood, and quality of life for the client.\n\nWhy Nutrition Matters in Home Care\n\nOne meaningful part of caregiving is helping clients enjoy meals that are safe, nourishing, and pleasant. For many older adults, food also brings comfort, memory, culture, family connection, and routine.\n\nWhen older adults eat alone or feel isolated, they may lose interest in food. Poor intake can lead to weakness, depression, weight loss, or worsening health. The HHA can help make mealtime feel calm, social, and dignified.\n\nWhat the HHA Can Do\nFollow the care plan and any ordered diet instructions.\nPrepare foods the client prefers when allowed by the care plan.\nEncourage fluids and balanced meals.\nReport appetite changes, weight changes, swallowing concerns, or signs of malnutrition.\nUse safe food handling and clean the kitchen after meals.\nRespect culture, preferences, budget, and independence.\nQuick Learner Check\nWhy can mealtime affect a client's mood and health?\nWhat should the HHA do if the client is not eating well?\nWhy should the aide follow the care plan when preparing meals?\nSuggested Answers\nMeals can provide comfort, connection, routine, and nutrition. Pleasant meals may improve appetite and emotional well-being.\nThe aide should observe, encourage food and fluids as allowed, and report appetite changes or poor intake to the supervisor.\nThe care plan may include diet restrictions, safety needs, swallowing precautions, or provider instructions that protect the client.\nRemember\n\nNutrition is not only about food on a plate. It is also about safety, dignity, comfort, and careful observation.\n\nCanvas source: https://hic.instructure.com/courses/287/pages/chc-112-nutrition-overview?module_item_id=3022"
        },
        {
          "title": "CHC 112 Topic 1: Nutrition Needs of Older Adults",
          "durationMinutes": 17,
          "content": "CHC 112 Topic 1: Nutrition Needs of Older Adults\nCHC 112 Topic 1: Nutrition Needs of Older Adults\nHow Aging Changes Nutrition\n\nOlder adults may need fewer calories, but they still need nutrient-rich foods. A smaller appetite does not mean nutrition is less important.\n\nCommon Age-Related Changes\nOlder adults may absorb fewer nutrients from food.\nThe ability to digest fats may decrease.\nSense of taste or smell may become weaker.\nIllness, dementia, medications, loneliness, or trouble shopping can reduce appetite.\nSome older adults snack on foods high in sugar, fat, or salt instead of eating balanced meals.\nCalorie and Protein Needs\n\nMany adults over age 70 need fewer calories, often about 1,200 to 1,600 calories per day depending on the person. However, protein needs often stay the same or increase. Protein helps maintain muscle, strength, skin health, and healing.\n\nBest Food Choices\nWhole grains and cereals.\nBright or deeply colored vegetables and fruits.\nBeans, lentils, and nuts.\nLow-fat dairy products.\nLean meat, fish, poultry, and eggs.\nFresh, healthy, less processed foods whenever possible.\nQuick Learner Check\nWhy might an older adult need fewer calories but still need good nutrition?\nName two reasons an older adult may lose appetite.\nWhy is protein important for older adults?\nSuggested Answers\nThe body may need less energy with age, but it still needs vitamins, minerals, protein, fiber, and fluids to maintain health.\nPossible reasons include illness, dementia, medications, loneliness, trouble shopping or cooking, and decreased taste or smell.\nProtein helps maintain muscle, supports healing, protects skin, and helps the body stay stronger.\nRemember\n\nOlder adults may eat less, so each meal should be as nourishing and appealing as possible.\n\nCanvas source: https://hic.instructure.com/courses/287/pages/chc-112-topic-1-nutrition-needs-of-older-adults?module_item_id=3023"
        },
        {
          "title": "CHC 112 Topic 2: Serving Sizes and Daily Food Guide",
          "durationMinutes": 17,
          "content": "CHC 112 Topic 2: Serving Sizes and Daily Food Guide\nCHC 112 Topic 2: Serving Sizes and Daily Food Guide\nUnderstanding Portions\n\nServing sizes help the aide plan meals that are balanced and not too large or too small. Visual examples make portions easier to understand.\n\nDaily Food Goals\nAbout 6 ounces of protein foods across the day.\n2 to 3 servings of low-fat dairy products.\n1 1/2 to 2 cups of bright colored cooked vegetables.\n2 to 4 servings of fruit.\n6 or more servings of whole grains and cereals.\nAbout eight 8-ounce glasses of water or other liquids unless restricted by the care plan.\nCommon Serving Size Guides\nFood\tServing Size Example\nMeat or fish\t3 ounces, about the size of a deck of cards.\nGreen salad or raw vegetables\t1 cup, about two hands cupped.\nCooked beans, rice, pasta, cooked cereal, or cooked vegetables\t1/2 cup, about one hand cupped.\nCold cereal\t3/4 cup for one serving.\nCheese\t2 ounces, about the size of two dominoes.\nPeanut butter, salad dressing, or mayonnaise\t1 tablespoon.\nMilk or dairy serving\t8 ounces.\nBread\t1 slice equals one serving; a sandwich usually provides two grain servings.\nQuick Learner Check\nWhat is one serving of meat or fish about the size of?\nIf a client eats 1 cup of cooked rice, how many 1/2-cup servings is that?\nWhy are visual portion guides helpful?\nSuggested Answers\nOne serving of meat or fish is about 3 ounces, roughly the size of a deck of cards.\nOne cup equals two 1/2-cup servings.\nThey help the aide estimate portions more accurately without guessing or overserving.\nRemember\n\nPortions matter. A balanced plate can help the client receive enough nutrients without unnecessary excess.\n\nCanvas source: https://hic.instructure.com/courses/287/pages/chc-112-topic-2-serving-sizes-and-daily-food-guide?module_item_id=3024"
        },
        {
          "title": "CHC 112 Topic 3: Hydration",
          "durationMinutes": 17,
          "content": "CHC 112 Topic 3: Hydration\nCHC 112 Topic 3: Hydration\nEncouraging Fluids Safely\n\nOlder adults may lose some sense of thirst and may not drink enough. Poor fluid intake can lead to serious health problems.\n\nWhy Hydration Matters\n\nWater and other fluids support digestion, temperature control, circulation, elimination, skin health, and alertness. Dehydration may contribute to weakness, confusion, constipation, urinary problems, and falls.\n\nWays the HHA Can Encourage Fluids\nOffer water and other allowed liquids often.\nKeep a pitcher of water available if this is part of the care plan.\nOffer fluids with meals, snacks, and medication routines as directed.\nUse cups or straws the client can manage safely.\nReport poor fluid intake, signs of dehydration, or any swallowing problems.\nFollow fluid restrictions if the client has one.\nQuick Learner Check\nWhy may older adults not drink enough fluids?\nWhat are two ways an aide can encourage fluids?\nWhat should the aide do if the client has a fluid restriction?\nSuggested Answers\nOlder adults may have a reduced sense of thirst, may forget to drink, may avoid drinking due to toileting concerns, or may have illness or swallowing issues.\nOffer allowed drinks often, keep water available, provide fluids with meals and snacks, and make drinks easy to reach.\nThe aide must follow the care plan exactly and report concerns to the supervisor instead of encouraging extra fluids.\nRemember\n\nEncourage fluids, but always follow the care plan and report concerns.\n\nCanvas source: https://hic.instructure.com/courses/287/pages/chc-112-topic-3-hydration?module_item_id=3025"
        },
        {
          "title": "CHC 112 Topic 4: Meal Planning and Client Preferences",
          "durationMinutes": 17,
          "content": "CHC 112 Topic 4: Meal Planning and Client Preferences\nCHC 112 Topic 4: Meal Planning and Client Preferences\nPlanning Meals That Clients Will Eat\n\nGood meal planning saves time and money and helps provide meals that are appetizing, varied, and nutritious.\n\nPlan With the Client in Mind\n\nThe goal is to provide the best nutrition possible in a way the client will actually enjoy. Prepare foods the client prefers rather than only foods the aide prefers. If unsure, ask the client or family for ideas, recipes, or cultural food preferences.\n\nMeal Planning Tips\nPlan meals for about one week when possible.\nConsider calories, protein, carbohydrates, fats, sodium, and fiber.\nUse the food guide for older adults as a planning tool.\nInclude variety in color, texture, temperature, and taste.\nRespect the client's budget and dietary restrictions.\nMake meals social when the client wants company.\nAsk before sitting with the client during meals.\nQuick Learner Check\nWhy should the aide consider the client's food preferences?\nHow can meal planning save time and money?\nWhy should the aide ask before joining the client during a meal?\nSuggested Answers\nClients are more likely to eat foods they enjoy and that match their culture, routines, and comfort foods.\nPlanning helps create a shopping list, avoid waste, use the budget wisely, and prepare balanced meals ahead of time.\nSome clients enjoy company, but others prefer privacy or eating with family. Asking respects choice and dignity.\nRemember\n\nA nutritious meal only helps if the client is willing and able to eat it.\n\nCanvas source: https://hic.instructure.com/courses/287/pages/chc-112-topic-4-meal-planning-and-client-preferences?module_item_id=3026"
        },
        {
          "title": "CHC 112 Topic 5: Fiber, Whole Grains, and Healthy Choices",
          "durationMinutes": 17,
          "content": "CHC 112 Topic 5: Fiber, Whole Grains, and Healthy Choices\nCHC 112 Topic 5: Fiber, Whole Grains, and Healthy Choices\nChoosing Foods That Support Health\n\nFresh fruits, vegetables, beans, and whole grains provide nutrients and fiber that support health and elimination.\n\nWhy Fiber Matters\n\nFiber helps support digestion and bowel elimination. Many fruits, vegetables, whole grains, beans, and lentils contain fiber. A high-fiber diet may include about 20 to 35 grams of fiber per day, depending on the care plan and provider instructions.\n\nBetter Fiber Choices\nChoose breads labeled whole-wheat or whole grain.\nKnow that bread labeled only wheat or enriched wheat may not be true whole grain.\nUse beans such as chickpeas, pinto beans, and lentils when appropriate.\nInclude fruits and vegetables often.\nChoose less processed foods when the budget and care plan allow.\nBudget-Friendly Healthy Meals\n\nNutritious meals do not have to be expensive. Examples include eggs with whole grain toast and fruit, beans with rice and vegetables, oatmeal with fruit, or a simple soup made with vegetables and lean protein.\n\nQuick Learner Check\nWhy is fiber helpful for older adults?\nWhat label words suggest a better bread choice?\nName one budget-friendly nutritious meal idea.\nSuggested Answers\nFiber supports digestion and bowel elimination and is often found in nutrient-rich foods.\nWhole-wheat or whole grain are better signs than simply wheat or enriched wheat.\nExamples include eggs with whole grain toast and fruit, beans with rice and vegetables, oatmeal with fruit, or vegetable soup with lean protein.\nRemember\n\nWhole foods, whole grains, fruits, vegetables, and beans can add nutrients without needing expensive meals.\n\nCanvas source: https://hic.instructure.com/courses/287/pages/chc-112-topic-5-fiber-whole-grains-and-healthy-choices?module_item_id=3027"
        },
        {
          "title": "CHC 112 Topic 6: Special Diets",
          "durationMinutes": 17,
          "content": "CHC 112 Topic 6: Special Diets\nCHC 112 Topic 6: Special Diets\nLow-Sodium, Heart-Healthy, and Diabetic Diets\n\nSome clients have diets ordered by a doctor, such as low-sodium, heart-healthy, or diabetic diets. The aide must follow the care plan and report concerns.\n\nLow-Sodium Diets\n\nA low-sodium diet may limit sodium to about 2,000 to 3,000 milligrams per day. Sodium is listed in milligrams on food labels. Processed foods can be high in sodium, including canned soup, frozen dinners, soy sauce, teriyaki sauce, and salty seasonings. One teaspoon of salt has about 2,300 milligrams of sodium.\n\nUse herbs, garlic, basil, oregano, sage, lemon juice, or vinegar for flavor when allowed.\nChoose fresh foods and lower-sodium convenience foods when needed.\nDo not add salt unless the care plan allows it.\nHeart-Healthy Diets\n\nA heart-healthy diet usually limits total fat and saturated fat. Saturated fat is found in foods such as cream, whole milk, fatty red meat, butter, ice cream, and some cheeses. Trans fats should be avoided when possible.\n\nBake instead of frying.\nUse low-fat or nonfat milk when allowed.\nTrim fat from meat.\nLimit fried and processed foods.\nChoose fish, poultry, lean meat, vegetables, fruits, whole grains, and some nuts.\nDiabetic Diets\n\nFor diabetic diets, total carbohydrate is usually more important than just the sugar line on the label. Many clients may need about 45 to 60 grams of carbohydrate per meal, but the care plan must guide the aide.\n\nWatch total carbohydrates on the label.\nAvoid regular soda and large amounts of syrup unless specifically allowed.\nServe portions carefully.\nReport if the client is not following the prescribed diet.\nQuick Learner Check\nWhere can the aide find sodium or carbohydrates on packaged foods?\nWhy should the aide not guess about a prescribed diet?\nName one way to reduce fat in a meal.\nSuggested Answers\nThe Nutrition Facts label lists sodium in milligrams and carbohydrates in grams.\nPrescribed diets are medical instructions. Guessing can harm the client, so the aide must follow the care plan and ask the supervisor when unsure.\nBake instead of frying, trim fat from meat, use low-fat dairy, add less oil, and limit processed or restaurant foods.\nRemember\n\nSpecial diets are part of the care plan. Follow them carefully and report concerns.\n\nCanvas source: https://hic.instructure.com/courses/287/pages/chc-112-topic-6-special-diets?module_item_id=3028"
        },
        {
          "title": "CHC 112 Topic 7: Malnutrition",
          "durationMinutes": 17,
          "content": "CHC 112 Topic 7: Malnutrition\nCHC 112 Topic 7: Malnutrition\nWarning Signs and Helpful Responses\n\nOlder adults are at higher risk for malnutrition. Malnutrition can weaken the immune system, increase infection risk, and contribute to confusion or decline.\n\nWarning Signs of Malnutrition\nIllness that affects the type or amount of food eaten.\nEating fewer than two meals per day.\nNot eating a balanced diet.\nDrinking three or more alcoholic beverages daily.\nTooth or mouth problems that make eating difficult.\nEating alone most of the time.\nUnintentional weight gain or loss of 10 or more pounds in six months.\nInability to shop, cook, or feed oneself.\nChanges in skin appearance or sores on the skin.\nSimple Solutions That May Help\nMake meals more social if the client wants company.\nVary texture, color, and temperature of foods.\nPlan healthy between-meal snacks.\nOffer nutrient-dense snacks such as fruit, cheese, peanut butter on a cracker, or smoothies when allowed.\nEncourage regular exercise if it is part of the care plan.\nServe foods with more protein and calories when appropriate.\nUse liquid nutrition supplements such as Ensure or Boost only when allowed by the care plan or supervisor.\nQuick Learner Check\nName two warning signs of malnutrition.\nWhy can eating alone contribute to poor nutrition?\nWhat should the aide do if signs of malnutrition are noticed?\nSuggested Answers\nExamples include eating fewer than two meals per day, weight change, mouth problems, lack of balanced diet, inability to shop or cook, skin changes, or eating alone most of the time.\nEating alone can reduce enjoyment, increase isolation, lower appetite, and lead to poor intake.\nThe aide should report observations to the supervisor promptly and follow the care plan.\nRemember\n\nThe HHA does not diagnose malnutrition, but careful observation and reporting can protect the client.\n\nCanvas source: https://hic.instructure.com/courses/287/pages/chc-112-topic-7-malnutrition?module_item_id=3029"
        },
        {
          "title": "CHC 112 Topic 8: Shopping and Reading Food Labels",
          "durationMinutes": 17,
          "content": "CHC 112 Topic 8: Shopping and Reading Food Labels\nCHC 112 Topic 8: Shopping and Reading Food Labels\nUsing Labels and Budgets Wisely\n\nHealthy eating starts with healthy shopping. The aide may help choose foods that match the client's diet, preferences, budget, and safety needs.\n\nBefore Shopping\nCheck food already in the home against the planned menu.\nMake a shopping list based on ingredients needed.\nFollow dietary restrictions and food preferences.\nConsider the food budget.\nChoose fresh fruits and vegetables in season when possible.\nBuy refrigerated items near the end of the shopping trip and store them quickly.\nReading Labels\n\nFood labels show serving size, servings per container, calories, ingredients, and nutrition information. The first ingredient listed is present in the highest amount. Dates may include packed on, sell by, best if used by, or expiration dates.\n\nCheck serving size first because all nutrition numbers are based on that amount.\nIf the client eats double the serving size, calories, sodium, fat, and carbohydrates are doubled.\nPay attention to calories, fat, saturated fat, trans fat, cholesterol, sodium, carbohydrates, fiber, and protein as directed by the care plan.\nSeven grams of protein on a label is about equal to one ounce of meat.\nUnit Pricing and Receipts\n\nUnit pricing helps compare cost by ounce or pound. Larger packages are not always cheaper. Keep records according to agency policy, including date, amount spent, logbook entries, and receipts.\n\nQuick Learner Check\nWhy should the aide look at serving size first on a label?\nWhat does the first ingredient on a food label mean?\nWhy is unit pricing useful?\nSuggested Answers\nAll nutrition information on the label is based on the listed serving size, so larger portions must be calculated differently.\nThe first ingredient is present in the greatest amount in the product.\nUnit pricing helps compare the true cost of products by ounce or pound, even when package sizes are different.\nRemember\n\nLabels help the aide choose foods that fit the client's health needs, budget, and care plan.\n\nCanvas source: https://hic.instructure.com/courses/287/pages/chc-112-topic-8-shopping-and-reading-food-labels?module_item_id=3030"
        },
        {
          "title": "CHC 112 Topic 9: Food Safety",
          "durationMinutes": 17,
          "content": "CHC 112 Topic 9: Food Safety\nCHC 112 Topic 9: Food Safety\nPreventing Foodborne Illness\n\nFood poisoning can occur when food is not stored, handled, or cooked properly. It can be especially dangerous for older adults.\n\nCore Food Safety Practices\nWash hands with warm soapy water for at least 20 seconds before and after handling food.\nKeep kitchen surfaces, dishes, cutting boards, countertops, and utensils clean.\nWash dishcloths and towels often in hot water.\nAvoid kitchen sponges when possible because damp sponges can hold germs.\nKeep raw meat, poultry, seafood, and their juices away from other foods.\nUse separate cutting boards for produce and raw meat when possible.\nPreparation and Cooking Safety\nNever thaw food on the countertop; thaw it in the refrigerator.\nMarinate foods in the refrigerator.\nUse a meat thermometer to check safe cooking temperatures.\nRefrigerate leftovers as soon as possible.\nDiscard cooked meats if not eaten within three to four days.\nDo not leave food out longer than two hours; if the temperature is 80 degrees or higher, refrigerate within one hour.\nQuick Learner Check\nHow long should hands be washed before and after handling food?\nWhy should raw meat be kept away from fruits and vegetables?\nHow quickly should food be refrigerated if the room is 80 degrees or hotter?\nSuggested Answers\nHands should be washed with warm soapy water for at least 20 seconds.\nRaw meat juices can spread germs to foods that may not be cooked, causing cross-contamination.\nFood should be returned to the refrigerator in less than one hour when the temperature is 80 degrees or higher.\nRemember\n\nClean, separate, cook, and chill. Food safety protects older adults from serious illness.\n\nCanvas source: https://hic.instructure.com/courses/287/pages/chc-112-topic-9-food-safety?module_item_id=3031"
        },
        {
          "title": "CHC 112 Topic 10: Measuring, Cooking, and Serving Meals",
          "durationMinutes": 17,
          "content": "CHC 112 Topic 10: Measuring, Cooking, and Serving Meals\nCHC 112 Topic 10: Measuring, Cooking, and Serving Meals\nPreparing Meals Safely and Pleasantly\n\nRecipes, measuring tools, kitchen safety, and attractive serving all help the aide prepare meals safely and respectfully.\n\nRecipes and Measurements\n\nRecipes usually list the number of servings, cooking time, ingredients, and step-by-step directions. Common abbreviations include tsp for teaspoon, tbsp for tablespoon, c for cup, oz for ounce, pt for pint, qt for quart, lb for pound, and doz for dozen.\n\nUse clear measuring cups for liquids such as milk, water, or oil.\nUse dry measuring cups for flour, nuts, shredded cheese, and other dry or solid foods.\nUse measuring spoons for small amounts of dry or liquid ingredients.\nLevel dry ingredients with a knife or spatula when needed.\nCooking Safety\nUse only microwave-safe cookware in the microwave.\nNever put metal in the microwave.\nUse pot holders when moving hot pans.\nKeep sleeves short or rolled up near the stove.\nTurn pot handles toward the back of the stove.\nServing Meals\n\nBefore serving a meal, make sure the client has used the bathroom if needed, washed hands, and has dentures or bridges in place if applicable. Serve food attractively with different colors, textures, and tastes. A simple plate guide is one quarter protein, one quarter carbohydrate, and the remaining half vegetables, salad, or fruit. Clean the kitchen after each meal to reduce germs.\n\nQuick Learner Check\nWhich measuring cup should be used for liquids?\nWhy should pot handles be turned toward the back of the stove?\nWhat should be done before serving a meal to the client?\nSuggested Answers\nUse glass or clear plastic measuring cups designed for liquid ingredients.\nTurning pot handles toward the back helps prevent spills, burns, and accidents while cooking.\nMake sure the client is comfortable, has washed hands, has used the bathroom if needed, and has dentures or bridges in place if applicable.\nRemember\n\nSafe preparation and pleasant serving can make meals healthier, safer, and more enjoyable for the client.\n\nCanvas source: https://hic.instructure.com/courses/287/pages/chc-112-topic-10-measuring-cooking-and-serving-meals?module_item_id=3032"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "CHC 113 - Emergency Procedure (4 hours)",
      "lessons": [
        {
          "title": "CHC 113: Emergency Procedure Overview",
          "durationMinutes": 17,
          "content": "CHC 113: Emergency Procedure Overview\nCHC 113: Emergency Procedure Overview\nCHC 113: Emergency Procedure Overview\n\nEmergencies require calm action, quick reporting, and careful protection of the client’s safety and dignity.\n\nLesson Objectives\n\nBy the end of this module, students should be able to describe how to prepare for emergencies, recognize warning signs that require emergency help, follow agency policy during falls and disasters, understand DNR basics, and respond safely to blood spills.\n\nWhat This Module Covers\nEmergency information and agency policy\nHeart attack warning signs\nStroke warning signs\nFalls and injury response\nDNR orders\nFire and natural-disaster readiness\nMoving a client to safety\nPreventing abandonment during emergencies\nCleaning blood spills safely\nYour First Responsibility\n\nIn an emergency, the HHA should stay calm, protect the client from further harm, call for emergency assistance when needed, notify the supervisor according to policy, and stay with the client until help arrives or the client is safely transferred.\n\nQuick Learner Check\nWhat is the HHA’s first responsibility in an emergency?\nWhy should emergency information be easy to find?\nWho should the HHA notify according to agency policy?\nSuggested Answers\nProtect the client from further harm, call for help when needed, and follow agency policy calmly.\nEmergency responders and caregivers need correct phone numbers, address information, and contacts quickly.\nThe agency supervisor, nurse, or other designated contact according to agency policy.\nRemember\n\nEmergency response is not about panic. It is about preparation, calm action, and following the plan.\n\nCanvas source: https://hic.instructure.com/courses/287/pages/chc-113-emergency-procedure-overview?module_item_id=3082"
        },
        {
          "title": "CHC 113 Topic 1: Emergency Information and Agency Policy",
          "durationMinutes": 17,
          "content": "CHC 113 Topic 1: Emergency Information and Agency Policy\nCHC 113 Topic 1: Emergency Information and Agency Policy\nCHC 113 Topic 1: Emergency Information and Agency Policy\n\nPreparation begins before an emergency happens. The right information must be easy to locate.\n\nEmergency Information by the Telephone\n\nEmergency information should be posted by the telephone or kept in the location directed by the care plan. In many areas, the emergency number is 911. The HHA should know where the information is before an emergency occurs.\n\nWhat the Emergency List Should Include\nEmergency phone number for the area\nClient’s name and phone number\nClient’s home address\nPharmacy phone number\nRelative or neighbor contact information\nAgency supervisor name and phone number\nAny other contacts required by agency policy\nFollow Agency Policy\n\nEvery agency has procedures for handling emergencies. The HHA should know when to call 911, when to call the supervisor, what to document, and what to do while waiting for help.\n\nStay Calm and Give Clear Information\n\nWhen calling for help, speak clearly. Be ready to state the address, what happened, the client’s condition, and whether there are immediate dangers such as fire, injury, or unconsciousness.\n\nQuick Learner Check\nWhere should emergency information be kept?\nName three items that belong on an emergency information list.\nWhy is the client’s address important during a 911 call?\nSuggested Answers\nIt should be posted by the telephone or kept where the care plan/agency policy directs.\nExamples include emergency number, client name and phone, home address, pharmacy, relative/neighbor contact, and supervisor contact.\nEmergency responders need the exact location to reach the client quickly.\nRemember\n\nDo not wait for an emergency to look for emergency information. Know where it is before care begins.\n\nCanvas source: https://hic.instructure.com/courses/287/pages/chc-113-topic-1-emergency-information-and-agency-policy?module_item_id=3083"
        },
        {
          "title": "CHC 113 Topic 2: Heart Attack Warning Signs",
          "durationMinutes": 17,
          "content": "CHC 113 Topic 2: Heart Attack Warning Signs\nCHC 113 Topic 2: Heart Attack Warning Signs\nCHC 113 Topic 2: Heart Attack Warning Signs\n\nA suspected heart attack is a medical emergency. Call for emergency medical assistance immediately.\n\nCommon Warning Signs\nChest pain, pressure, squeezing, or discomfort\nPain or discomfort that spreads to the shoulder, neck, jaw, back, or arms\nDizziness or lightheadedness\nSweating\nNausea or vomiting\nDifficulty breathing or shortness of breath\nSymptoms May Look Different\n\nWomen may have less predictable symptoms and may not have chest pain. Shortness of breath, nausea, vomiting, unusual fatigue, or discomfort in the upper body can still be serious. Older adults may also show symptoms less clearly.\n\nWhat the HHA Should Do\nCall emergency medical assistance immediately if a heart attack is suspected.\nStay with the client.\nKeep the client as calm and comfortable as possible.\nFollow agency policy and supervisor instructions.\nDo not delay because symptoms seem mild or unusual.\nWhat to Report\n\nBe ready to report when symptoms began, what the client says they feel, what you observed, and any changes in breathing, skin color, sweating, alertness, or pain.\n\nQuick Learner Check\nName two warning signs of a heart attack.\nWhy should symptoms in women be taken seriously even without chest pain?\nWhat should the HHA do if a heart attack is suspected?\nSuggested Answers\nExamples include chest discomfort, pain spreading to the shoulder/neck/arms, sweating, nausea, dizziness, or difficulty breathing.\nWomen may have less predictable symptoms and may have shortness of breath, nausea, vomiting, fatigue, or upper-body discomfort without chest pain.\nCall emergency medical assistance immediately, stay with the client, and follow agency policy.\nRemember\n\nWhen heart attack is suspected, quick action can save a life. Call for emergency help immediately.\n\nCanvas source: https://hic.instructure.com/courses/287/pages/chc-113-topic-2-heart-attack-warning-signs?module_item_id=3084"
        },
        {
          "title": "CHC 113 Topic 3: Stroke Warning Signs",
          "durationMinutes": 17,
          "content": "CHC 113 Topic 3: Stroke Warning Signs\nCHC 113 Topic 3: Stroke Warning Signs\nCHC 113 Topic 3: Stroke Warning Signs\n\nStroke symptoms can appear suddenly. Emergency help is needed right away.\n\nCommon Stroke Signs\nWeakness or paralysis on one side of the body\nFacial drooping\nSlurred, unclear, or incoherent speech\nSudden trouble walking, balance problems, or dizziness\nSudden vision changes\nSudden severe headache with no known cause\nThink BE FAST\n\nBE FAST is an easy memory tool: Balance changes, Eye/vision changes, Face drooping, Arm weakness, Speech difficulty, Time to call emergency services. The transcript especially emphasizes one-sided weakness, facial drooping, and slurred or incoherent speech.\n\nWhat the HHA Should Do\nCall emergency assistance immediately if stroke is suspected.\nNote the time symptoms were first noticed, if known.\nStay with the client and keep them safe from falls or injury.\nDo not give food, drink, or medication unless directed by emergency personnel or agency policy.\nNotify the supervisor according to agency policy.\nWhy Time Matters\n\nStroke care is time-sensitive. Even if symptoms improve or come and go, the client still needs emergency evaluation.\n\nQuick Learner Check\nName three possible stroke warning signs.\nWhat does the “T” in BE FAST remind you to do?\nShould the HHA wait to see if stroke symptoms go away?\nSuggested Answers\nExamples include facial drooping, one-sided weakness/paralysis, slurred speech, balance changes, vision changes, or sudden severe headache.\nTime to call emergency services immediately.\nNo. Call emergency assistance immediately if stroke is suspected.\nRemember\n\nFor stroke, do not wait. Sudden face, arm, speech, balance, or vision changes require emergency help.\n\nCanvas source: https://hic.instructure.com/courses/287/pages/chc-113-topic-3-stroke-warning-signs?module_item_id=3085"
        },
        {
          "title": "CHC 113 Topic 4: Falls and Injury Response",
          "durationMinutes": 17,
          "content": "CHC 113 Topic 4: Falls and Injury Response\nCHC 113 Topic 4: Falls and Injury Response\nCHC 113 Topic 4: Falls and Injury Response\n\nFalls can signal serious injury or illness, especially for older adults.\n\nWhy Falls Are Serious\n\nFalls are a major cause of injury for adults age 65 and older. A fall may cause a hip fracture or may be a sign of a serious medical condition such as weakness, infection, medication reaction, dizziness, or stroke.\n\nFollow Agency Procedure\n\nThe HHA should follow the agency’s procedure for handling falls. Do not assume the client is fine because they say they are okay. Observe carefully, report, and document according to policy.\n\nInformation to Report and Record\nDay and time of the fall\nLocation of the fall\nHow the fall occurred, if known\nAny history of previous falls\nClient’s complaints of pain, dizziness, weakness, or injury\nWhat actions were taken and who was notified\nIf the Client Is Unconscious or May Be Seriously Injured\n\nCall 911 immediately. Do not move the client because there may be a neck, spine, head, hip, or other serious injury. Cover the client with a blanket to prevent chilling, notify the supervisor, and stay with the client until help arrives.\n\nQuick Learner Check\nWhy should a fall always be taken seriously?\nWhat information should be reported after a fall?\nWhat should the HHA do if the client is unconscious after a fall?\nSuggested Answers\nA fall can cause serious injury or may be a sign of a medical problem.\nReport the day, time, location, how it happened, history of falls, symptoms/injuries, and who was notified.\nCall 911, do not move the client, keep them warm, notify the supervisor, and stay until help arrives.\nRemember\n\nAfter a fall, do not rush the client up. Stop, assess, call for help when needed, and follow policy.\n\nCanvas source: https://hic.instructure.com/courses/287/pages/chc-113-topic-4-falls-and-injury-response?module_item_id=3086"
        },
        {
          "title": "CHC 113 Topic 5: Understanding DNR Orders",
          "durationMinutes": 17,
          "content": "CHC 113 Topic 5: Understanding DNR Orders\nCHC 113 Topic 5: Understanding DNR Orders\nCHC 113 Topic 5: Understanding DNR Orders\n\nA DNR order is a medical order. The HHA must know where it is and follow agency policy.\n\nWhat DNR Means\n\nDNR stands for Do Not Resuscitate. It is a doctor’s order that resuscitation should not be attempted if the client’s breathing or heart stops.\n\nWhat the Order Means\n\nA DNR means the client does not wish to be brought back to life if breathing or heartbeat stops. This does not mean the client should be ignored, left alone, or denied comfort care. The client still deserves safety, dignity, and respectful care.\n\nCall Emergency Services When Directed\n\nThe transcript states that even with a DNR, emergency services should still be called if the client stops breathing so emergency personnel can determine the proper medical procedure. The HHA should follow agency policy and supervisor instructions exactly.\n\nMake the DNR Easy to Locate\n\nIf the client has a DNR order, it should be visible and easy for care providers and emergency personnel to locate. The HHA should know where the document is before an emergency happens.\n\nQuick Learner Check\nWhat does DNR stand for?\nDoes a DNR mean the client should be left alone?\nWhy should the DNR order be easy to find?\nSuggested Answers\nDo Not Resuscitate.\nNo. The client still needs safety, comfort, dignity, and appropriate care.\nEmergency personnel and caregivers need to locate it quickly so proper procedures can be followed.\nRemember\n\nA DNR is a medical order. Do not interpret it on your own; follow agency policy and emergency personnel direction.\n\nCanvas source: https://hic.instructure.com/courses/287/pages/chc-113-topic-5-understanding-dnr-orders?module_item_id=3087"
        },
        {
          "title": "CHC 113 Topic 6: Fire and Natural Disaster Readiness",
          "durationMinutes": 17,
          "content": "CHC 113 Topic 6: Fire and Natural Disaster Readiness\nCHC 113 Topic 6: Fire and Natural Disaster Readiness\nCHC 113 Topic 6: Fire and Natural Disaster Readiness\n\nOlder adults may need extra support during fires, storms, power outages, and other disasters.\n\nWhy Older Adults Are at Higher Risk\n\nOlder clients may have reduced mobility, hearing loss, vision changes, confusion, medical equipment, or other impairments that make emergency response harder. They may need help hearing alarms, moving quickly, understanding directions, or staying safe in a shelter.\n\nSmoke Alarms\n\nWorking smoke alarms provide early warning of fire. The transcript emphasizes that smoke alarms should be tested monthly as part of the home safety checklist. Report missing or nonworking alarms according to agency policy.\n\nAgency Disaster Plan\n\nIn an emergency, follow the agency’s plan for moving the client to safety or arranging for another staff member to replace you. If you cannot contact the agency because of a power outage or communication problem, listen to a battery-operated radio or other approved emergency information source.\n\nPreparation Questions\nWhere are exits located?\nDoes the client need mobility assistance?\nDoes the client use oxygen, medical equipment, or assistive devices?\nWhere is the emergency information list?\nWhere is the DNR or advance directive if applicable?\nWhat is the agency’s disaster procedure?\nQuick Learner Check\nWhy are older adults more vulnerable during disasters?\nHow often should smoke alarms be tested according to this lesson?\nWhat should the HHA follow during a fire or natural disaster?\nSuggested Answers\nThey may have reduced mobility, hearing, vision, confusion, or medical needs that make emergency response harder.\nMonthly.\nThe agency’s emergency or disaster plan.\nRemember\n\nEmergency readiness starts before the alarm sounds.\n\nCanvas source: https://hic.instructure.com/courses/287/pages/chc-113-topic-6-fire-and-natural-disaster-readiness?module_item_id=3088"
        },
        {
          "title": "CHC 113 Topic 7: Moving a Client to Safety",
          "durationMinutes": 17,
          "content": "CHC 113 Topic 7: Moving a Client to Safety\nCHC 113 Topic 7: Moving a Client to Safety\nCHC 113 Topic 7: Moving a Client to Safety\n\nDuring an emergency, move the client only when necessary and according to agency policy.\n\nFollow the Plan First\n\nThe HHA should follow the agency emergency plan for moving the client to safety. If the client can move safely with assistance, use the method directed by the care plan. If the client may have a neck, spine, head, or hip injury after a fall, do not move them unless there is immediate danger such as fire.\n\nWrap and Slide Technique\n\nWhen caring for someone on bedrest, the transcript describes the wrap and slide technique as a way to move the person out of danger. A blanket or sheet is used to wrap the body, support the head and shoulders, and gently slide the person off the bed toward the exit. This should be done only in an emergency and according to training and agency policy.\n\nProtect the Client\nSupport the head and shoulders.\nMove gently and avoid twisting the body.\nKeep the client covered when possible.\nMove toward the safest exit or location.\nCall for help as soon as possible.\nAfter Moving\n\nStay with the client until help arrives or until the client is safely transferred to a physically stable and secure location. Continue to observe and report changes.\n\nQuick Learner Check\nWhen should a client not be moved after a fall?\nWhat does the wrap and slide technique use?\nWhat should the HHA do after moving the client to safety?\nSuggested Answers\nDo not move the client if they may have a neck, spine, head, hip, or other serious injury unless there is immediate danger.\nA blanket or sheet to wrap and slide the client while supporting the head and shoulders.\nStay with the client, call for help, and follow agency reporting procedures.\nRemember\n\nMove a client only when it is safer than leaving them where they are, and follow emergency training.\n\nCanvas source: https://hic.instructure.com/courses/287/pages/chc-113-topic-7-moving-a-client-to-safety?module_item_id=3089"
        },
        {
          "title": "CHC 113 Topic 8: Staying With the Client and Avoiding Abandonment",
          "durationMinutes": 17,
          "content": "CHC 113 Topic 8: Staying With the Client and Avoiding Abandonment\nCHC 113 Topic 8: Staying With the Client and Avoiding Abandonment\nCHC 113 Topic 8: Staying With the Client and Avoiding Abandonment\n\nA client still needs care during an emergency, especially if they are confused, injured, or frightened.\n\nDo Not Leave the Client Unsafe\n\nLeaving a client in an unsafe situation during an emergency is considered abandonment or desertion. The HHA should stay with the client until help arrives, another staff member replaces the aide, or the client has been moved to a physically stable and secure location.\n\nConfused Clients Need Extra Support\n\nA confused client should not be left alone at an emergency shelter. They may continue to need one-on-one care, supervision, reassurance, help communicating, help using mobility equipment, or assistance following shelter instructions.\n\nWhen Communication Fails\n\nIf phone lines, electricity, or agency contact systems are not working, follow the agency emergency plan. Use approved emergency information sources such as a battery-operated radio when directed.\n\nWhat to Communicate During Handoff\nClient’s name and condition\nWhat happened and when\nMedications, oxygen, mobility needs, or equipment needs if known\nDNR or emergency documents if applicable\nWho has been notified\nAny changes observed while waiting\nQuick Learner Check\nWhat is abandonment during an emergency?\nWhy should a confused client not be left alone at a shelter?\nWhen may the HHA leave the client?\nSuggested Answers\nLeaving the client in an unsafe situation without proper replacement, transfer, or safety support.\nThey may not understand the situation or may still need one-on-one care and supervision.\nOnly when help has arrived, another authorized person has taken over, or the client is physically stable and secure according to policy.\nRemember\n\nIn emergencies, safety includes staying with the client until care is properly handed off.\n\nCanvas source: https://hic.instructure.com/courses/287/pages/chc-113-topic-8-staying-with-the-client-and-avoiding-abandonment?module_item_id=3090"
        },
        {
          "title": "CHC 113 Topic 9: Blood Spills and Infection Control",
          "durationMinutes": 17,
          "content": "CHC 113 Topic 9: Blood Spills and Infection Control\nCHC 113 Topic 9: Blood Spills and Infection Control\nCHC 113 Topic 9: Blood Spills and Infection Control\n\nBlood spills must be handled quickly and safely to reduce infection risk.\n\nRespond Promptly\n\nBlood spills should be cleaned according to agency policy and infection-control procedures. Wear gloves and use disposable cleaning materials. Protect yourself and others from contact with blood.\n\nSmall Spills\n\nThe transcript describes cleaning small spills with paper towels and a bleach-water solution, using the agency’s approved directions. Always follow your agency’s current policy for mixing, using, and storing disinfectant solutions.\n\nLarger Spills\n\nA blood spill kit may include gloves, absorbent powder, disinfectant cloths, and biohazard bags. Follow the directions on the kit. After the spill is absorbed, use the provided tools to gather the material and place waste in the biohazard bag.\n\nFinish Safely\nClean the area with disinfectant cloths as directed.\nUse additional wipes if needed.\nDry the area if directed.\nPlace disposable gloves and cleaning materials in the biohazard bag.\nSeal the bag securely.\nWash hands thoroughly after removing gloves.\nReport and Document\n\nReport the incident according to agency policy, especially if there was injury, exposure to blood, a fall, or any unsafe condition that caused the spill.\n\nQuick Learner Check\nWhy must blood spills be cleaned carefully?\nWhat should be worn when cleaning a blood spill?\nWhere should disposable gloves and contaminated cleaning materials go?\nSuggested Answers\nBlood can carry infection risk, so cleanup protects the client, aide, and others.\nGloves and any other protective equipment required by agency policy.\nInto the biohazard bag or approved disposal container according to policy.\nRemember\n\nBlood spill cleanup protects everyone. Use gloves, follow the kit directions, dispose safely, and wash hands.\n\nCanvas source: https://hic.instructure.com/courses/287/pages/chc-113-topic-9-blood-spills-and-infection-control?module_item_id=3091"
        },
        {
          "title": "CHC 113 Topic 11: Choking Warning Signs",
          "durationMinutes": 17,
          "content": "CHC 113 Topic 11: Choking Warning Signs\nCHC 113 Topic 11: Choking Warning Signs\nRecognizing Choking Warning Signs\n\nChoking can become life-threatening within minutes. The HHA must recognize the warning signs quickly, stay calm, call for help according to agency policy, and respond within the scope of training.\n\nLesson Objectives\n\nBy the end of this lesson, you should be able to recognize the difference between mild choking and severe choking, identify common warning signs, and know when emergency help is needed.\n\nExplain what choking means.\nRecognize signs that a person may still be able to cough or speak.\nRecognize signs that the airway may be blocked.\nDescribe what the HHA should do first when choking is suspected.\nKnow when to call 911 or activate emergency help.\nWhat Is Choking?\n\nChoking happens when food, liquid, or another object blocks the airway. A partial blockage may still allow some air to move. A complete blockage can prevent the person from breathing and can quickly become a medical emergency.\n\nAn HHA should never ignore choking signs. Stay with the person, call for help according to agency policy, and use only the emergency procedures you have been trained and authorized to perform.\n\nMild Choking Warning Signs\n\nMild choking may mean the person can still move air. If the person can cough forcefully, speak, cry, or breathe, encourage coughing and stay close. Do not leave the person alone. Watch carefully in case the choking becomes worse.\n\nThe person can cough or make sounds.\nThe person can speak or answer you.\nThe person may gag, cough, or look uncomfortable.\nThe person may point to the throat but still breathe.\nThe person may become anxious but is still moving air.\nSevere Choking Warning Signs\n\nSevere choking means little or no air is getting through. This is an emergency. The person may not be able to cough, speak, breathe, or make sound. Call 911 or activate emergency help right away according to agency policy.\n\nCannot speak, cough, cry, or breathe.\nMakes weak, silent, or high-pitched breathing attempts.\nClutches the throat with one or both hands.\nLooks panicked, frightened, or confused.\nSkin, lips, or nail beds may turn blue, gray, or pale.\nMay become weak, collapse, or lose consciousness.\nWhat the HHA Should Do First\n\nWhen choking is suspected, act quickly but calmly. Ask, “Are you choking?” If the person can cough strongly, encourage coughing and monitor. If the person cannot speak, cough, or breathe, call 911 or have someone call 911 immediately and follow your emergency training and agency policy.\n\nStay with the person.\nCall for help immediately if severe choking signs are present.\nFollow your training for choking response, such as abdominal thrusts, only if you have been trained and authorized.\nIf the person becomes unconscious, call 911 if not already done and begin CPR only if trained to do so.\nReport and document the emergency according to agency policy after the situation is handled.\nSpecial Reminder for Home Care\n\nClients may have dentures, swallowing problems, stroke history, neurological conditions, weakness, or medications that increase choking risk. If you notice coughing during meals, pocketing food in the cheek, drooling, wet-sounding voice, or repeated swallowing difficulty, report it to the supervisor even if the client does not fully choke.\n\nQuick Learner Check\nWhat is one sign that a person may have severe choking?\nIf a person can cough forcefully, what should the aide do?\nWhen should 911 be called?\nSuggested Answers\nA severe sign is inability to speak, cough, cry, or breathe. Other signs include clutching the throat, blue or gray color, panic, collapse, or loss of consciousness.\nEncourage the person to keep coughing, stay with them, and watch closely in case the airway becomes fully blocked.\nCall 911 or activate emergency help when the person cannot speak, cough, breathe, or make sound, or if they become weak, collapse, or lose consciousness.\nRemember\n\nIf the person cannot speak, cough, or breathe, treat it as an emergency. Call 911, stay with the client, and follow only the choking response steps you have been trained and authorized to perform.\n\nSources for Instructor Review\nMedlinePlus: Choking\nLinks to an external site.\nAmerican Red Cross: Adult and Child Choking\nLinks to an external site.\n\nCanvas source: https://hic.instructure.com/courses/287/pages/chc-113-topic-11-choking-warning-signs?module_item_id=3135"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "CHC 114 - Changes in Health (2 hours)",
      "lessons": [
        {
          "title": "CHC 114: Changes in Health Overview",
          "durationMinutes": 17,
          "content": "CHC 114: Changes in Health Overview\nCHC 114: Changes in Health Overview\nNoticing Change Is Part of Safe Care\n\nHome Health Aides often notice small changes before anyone else. Careful observation and clear reporting help the care team respond early and protect the client.\n\nLesson Objectives\n\nBy the end of this module, the learner should understand how to recognize and report changes in a client’s health, behavior, and daily function.\n\nExplain why observing changes is an important HHA responsibility.\nDescribe the difference between gradual changes and sudden changes.\nIdentify physical, mental, emotional, skin, appetite, elimination, breathing, and mobility changes that should be reported.\nRecognize warning signs that may require urgent help.\nReport and document changes using clear, objective information.\nWhy Changes Matter\n\nA change in health may be the first clue that something is wrong. The client may not notice the change, may be afraid to report it, or may not be able to explain what is happening. Because the HHA sees the client during normal daily routines, the aide may notice changes in appearance, movement, mood, appetite, hygiene, or safety.\n\nYour Role as the HHA\n\nThe HHA does not diagnose illness, decide treatment, or change the care plan. The aide observes, keeps the client safe, follows agency policy, reports promptly, and documents accurately. Even small changes can be important when they are new, unusual, getting worse, or different from the client’s normal baseline.\n\nBaseline Means Usual\n\nA baseline is what is normal for that client. Some clients normally move slowly, eat small meals, or need extra time to answer. A change means something is different from that client’s usual pattern.\n\nQuick Learner Check\nWhat is a client’s baseline?\nWhy might the HHA notice changes before others?\nDoes the HHA diagnose the cause of a change?\nSuggested Answers\nA baseline is the client’s usual condition, behavior, or routine.\nThe HHA often spends time with the client during daily care and may notice changes in appearance, mood, movement, appetite, or safety.\nNo. The HHA observes, reports, documents, and follows the care plan. Diagnosis is done by licensed healthcare professionals.\nRemember\n\nDo not ignore a change just because it seems small. New, unusual, or worsening changes should be reported.\n\nReference for instructor review: CDC Stroke Signs and Symptoms\nLinks to an external site.\n | CDC Heart Attack Symptoms\nLinks to an external site.\n | CDC Sepsis\nLinks to an external site.\n | MedlinePlus Confusion\nLinks to an external site.\n\nCanvas source: https://hic.instructure.com/courses/287/pages/chc-114-changes-in-health-overview?module_item_id=3236"
        },
        {
          "title": "CHC 114 Topic 1: Physical Changes to Observe and Report",
          "durationMinutes": 17,
          "content": "CHC 114 Topic 1: Physical Changes to Observe and Report\nCHC 114 Topic 1: Physical Changes to Observe and Report\nThe Body Gives Clues\n\nPhysical changes may appear in breathing, skin, eating, elimination, movement, pain, strength, or energy level. The HHA should observe closely and report changes promptly.\n\nGeneral Physical Changes\n\nA client may show changes in energy, strength, appetite, sleep, hygiene, balance, or comfort. These changes may happen suddenly or slowly. Report changes that are new, unusual, severe, or getting worse.\n\nUnusual tiredness, weakness, shaking, or dizziness.\nNew pain or pain that is worse than usual.\nSwelling in feet, ankles, hands, face, or abdomen.\nShortness of breath, coughing, wheezing, or trouble lying flat.\nPoor appetite, nausea, vomiting, choking, or trouble swallowing.\nChanges in urine, stool, toileting habits, or signs of dehydration.\nNew bruises, redness, rashes, wounds, drainage, or skin breakdown.\nSkin Changes\n\nSkin can show early signs of illness, poor circulation, pressure injury, infection, dehydration, or injury. Observe color, temperature, moisture, swelling, redness, open areas, bruising, drainage, odor, and pain. Report any new skin change, especially over bony areas such as heels, hips, tailbone, elbows, or shoulders.\n\nAppetite and Hydration Changes\n\nReport when a client eats or drinks much less than usual, refuses meals, coughs during meals, has vomiting or diarrhea, has a very dry mouth, becomes dizzy, or has very little urine. These changes may become serious quickly, especially in older adults.\n\nMobility Changes\n\nReport new trouble walking, standing, transferring, using hands, following directions, or staying balanced. A client who suddenly needs more help than usual may be at higher risk for falls or illness.\n\nQuick Learner Check\nName three physical changes an HHA should report.\nWhy are skin changes important?\nWhat should the aide do if a client suddenly needs more help walking?\nSuggested Answers\nExamples include new pain, weakness, swelling, shortness of breath, poor appetite, vomiting, diarrhea, skin redness, wounds, dizziness, or changes in urine or stool.\nSkin changes can be early signs of pressure injury, infection, poor circulation, dehydration, or injury.\nThe aide should keep the client safe, provide only assigned assistance, and report the change promptly.\nRemember\n\nReport what you see, hear, smell, and measure. Specific details help the nurse decide what to do next.\n\nReference for instructor review: CDC Stroke Signs and Symptoms\nLinks to an external site.\n | CDC Heart Attack Symptoms\nLinks to an external site.\n | CDC Sepsis\nLinks to an external site.\n | MedlinePlus Confusion\nLinks to an external site.\n\nCanvas source: https://hic.instructure.com/courses/287/pages/chc-114-topic-1-physical-changes-to-observe-and-report?module_item_id=3237"
        },
        {
          "title": "CHC 114 Topic 2: Mental, Emotional, and Behavior Changes",
          "durationMinutes": 17,
          "content": "CHC 114 Topic 2: Mental, Emotional, and Behavior Changes\nCHC 114 Topic 2: Mental, Emotional, and Behavior Changes\nChanges Are Not Always Physical\n\nHealth changes can show through mood, memory, behavior, speech, sleep, or ability to follow normal routines.\n\nMental Status Changes\n\nA mental status change means the client is thinking, speaking, remembering, or responding differently than usual. Sudden confusion is especially important and should be reported right away according to agency policy.\n\nNew confusion or not knowing where they are.\nTrouble speaking clearly or understanding simple directions.\nNew forgetfulness that is different from usual.\nSeeing or hearing things that are not there.\nExtreme sleepiness, hard to wake, or unusual agitation.\nSudden change in personality or behavior.\nEmotional Changes\n\nClients may experience sadness, fear, loneliness, frustration, grief, anxiety, or anger. Emotional changes can affect eating, sleeping, hygiene, safety, and cooperation with care. The HHA should respond with respect and report concerns, especially if changes are new or severe.\n\nBehavior Changes\n\nBehavior is communication. A client who refuses care, becomes withdrawn, yells, cries, wanders, or becomes unusually suspicious may be showing discomfort, fear, confusion, pain, infection, medication effects, or another concern. Do not take behavior personally. Observe and report facts.\n\nUse Respectful Language\n\nInstead of documenting “client was crazy,” write facts such as “client stated there were people in the room when no one else was present” or “client paced in hallway for 20 minutes and would not sit.”\n\nQuick Learner Check\nWhy is sudden confusion important?\nName two emotional or behavior changes that should be reported.\nHow should an HHA document behavior changes?\nSuggested Answers\nSudden confusion can be a sign of illness, medication problems, infection, dehydration, stroke, or another urgent condition.\nExamples include new sadness, fear, agitation, withdrawal, crying, yelling, wandering, refusal of care, or unusual suspicion.\nThe aide should document objective facts: what the client said, did, when it happened, how long it lasted, and what was reported.\nRemember\n\nBehavior changes are health clues. Stay calm, stay respectful, and report facts.\n\nReference for instructor review: CDC Stroke Signs and Symptoms\nLinks to an external site.\n | CDC Heart Attack Symptoms\nLinks to an external site.\n | CDC Sepsis\nLinks to an external site.\n | MedlinePlus Confusion\nLinks to an external site.\n\nCanvas source: https://hic.instructure.com/courses/287/pages/chc-114-topic-2-mental-emotional-and-behavior-changes?module_item_id=3238"
        },
        {
          "title": "CHC 114 Topic 3: Urgent Warning Signs and When to Get Help",
          "durationMinutes": 17,
          "content": "CHC 114 Topic 3: Urgent Warning Signs and When to Get Help\nCHC 114 Topic 3: Urgent Warning Signs and When to Get Help\nSome Changes Cannot Wait\n\nSome health changes may be emergencies. The HHA must know warning signs, follow agency policy, and call emergency help when required.\n\nEmergency Warning Signs\n\nIf a client appears to have a life-threatening change, follow emergency procedures. Call 911 first when required by agency policy, then notify the supervisor. Do not wait to see if the problem goes away.\n\nChest pain, pressure, or discomfort, especially with shortness of breath, sweating, nausea, or pain spreading to arm, jaw, back, or shoulder.\nSudden trouble breathing, blue lips, severe wheezing, choking, or gasping.\nSigns of stroke such as face drooping, arm weakness, speech difficulty, sudden confusion, sudden vision trouble, sudden severe headache, or sudden trouble walking.\nLoss of consciousness, seizure, or client is hard to wake.\nSevere bleeding, fall with injury, head injury, or suspected broken bone.\nSudden severe pain, severe allergic reaction, or signs of shock.\nSigns of possible sepsis such as extreme illness, confusion, fever or very low temperature, fast breathing, clammy skin, or severe weakness.\nStroke Reminder: Think FAST\n\nFAST is a simple reminder: Face drooping, Arm weakness, Speech difficulty, Time to call emergency help. Stroke treatment is time-sensitive. Do not drive the client yourself unless specifically directed by emergency services or agency policy.\n\nHeart Attack Warning Signs\n\nChest discomfort is common, but symptoms can also include shortness of breath, nausea, sweating, lightheadedness, pain in the arm, back, neck, jaw, or stomach, or unusual fatigue. Symptoms may look different from person to person.\n\nEmergency Boundary\n\nThe HHA should not diagnose a stroke, heart attack, or sepsis. The aide recognizes warning signs and gets help immediately according to policy.\n\nQuick Learner Check\nWhat does FAST help you remember?\nName two warning signs that may require emergency help.\nShould an HHA wait to see if severe chest pain goes away?\nSuggested Answers\nFAST means Face drooping, Arm weakness, Speech difficulty, and Time to call emergency help.\nExamples include chest pain, severe breathing trouble, stroke signs, loss of consciousness, seizure, severe bleeding, head injury, severe allergic reaction, or signs of shock.\nNo. Severe chest pain or chest pressure should be treated as urgent. Follow emergency procedures and agency policy.\nRemember\n\nWhen a change may be life-threatening, get help first. Reporting early can save a life.\n\nReference for instructor review: CDC Stroke Signs and Symptoms\nLinks to an external site.\n | CDC Heart Attack Symptoms\nLinks to an external site.\n | CDC Sepsis\nLinks to an external site.\n | MedlinePlus Confusion\nLinks to an external site.\n\nCanvas source: https://hic.instructure.com/courses/287/pages/chc-114-topic-3-urgent-warning-signs-and-when-to-get-help?module_item_id=3239"
        },
        {
          "title": "CHC 114 Topic 4: Reporting and Documenting Changes in Health",
          "durationMinutes": 17,
          "content": "CHC 114 Topic 4: Reporting and Documenting Changes in Health\nCHC 114 Topic 4: Reporting and Documenting Changes in Health\nClear Details Help the Care Team Respond\n\nObservation is only useful when it is shared clearly. The HHA should report promptly and document objective facts.\n\nWhat to Report\n\nReport any new, unusual, worsening, or unsafe change. Include what happened, when it started, what the client said, what you observed, what care was provided, and who was notified. If the client refused care or refused emergency help, follow agency policy and report immediately.\n\nUse Objective Information\n\nObjective information is factual and specific. It avoids guessing, blaming, or diagnosing. Compare the examples below:\n\nLess helpful: “Client looked bad.” Better: “Client was pale, sweating, and stated, ‘I feel dizzy.’”\nLess helpful: “Client was confused.” Better: “Client called me by the wrong name three times and asked where she was.”\nLess helpful: “Client did not eat.” Better: “Client ate two bites of toast and drank 2 oz of water at breakfast.”\nWhen to Report\n\nReport urgent changes immediately. Report non-emergency changes according to the care plan and agency policy. Do not save important concerns until the end of the shift if the client may be unsafe.\n\nSBAR for Clear Reporting\n\nSome agencies use SBAR: Situation, Background, Assessment/Appearance, and Recommendation/Request. For an HHA, this can mean: what is happening now, what is normal for the client, what you observed, and what help or instruction is needed.\n\nSituation: “Mrs. Lee became short of breath while walking to the bathroom.”\nBackground: “She usually walks with her walker without shortness of breath.”\nAppearance/Observation: “She sat down, was breathing fast, and said she felt tightness in her chest.”\nRequest: “I am calling for instructions and emergency help according to policy.”\nQuick Learner Check\nWhat makes documentation objective?\nWhen should urgent changes be reported?\nWhat does SBAR help with?\nSuggested Answers\nObjective documentation uses facts: what was seen, heard, measured, done, and reported. It avoids opinions and diagnoses.\nUrgent changes should be reported immediately according to agency policy.\nSBAR helps organize information clearly so the supervisor or nurse understands the situation quickly.\nRemember\n\nThe HHA is the eyes and ears of the care team. Clear reporting turns observation into action.\n\nReference for instructor review: CDC Stroke Signs and Symptoms\nLinks to an external site.\n | CDC Heart Attack Symptoms\nLinks to an external site.\n | CDC Sepsis\nLinks to an external site.\n | MedlinePlus Confusion\nLinks to an external site.\n\nCanvas source: https://hic.instructure.com/courses/287/pages/chc-114-topic-4-reporting-and-documenting-changes-in-health?module_item_id=3240"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "CHC 115 - Rehabilitative Nursing (3 hours)",
      "lessons": [
        {
          "title": "CHC 115: Rehabilitative Nursing Overview",
          "durationMinutes": 17,
          "content": "CHC 115: Rehabilitative Nursing Overview\nCHC 115: Rehabilitative Nursing Overview\nSupporting Independence and Recovery\n\nRehabilitative nursing helps clients maintain or regain the highest level of function possible. The HHA supports safe movement, daily routines, confidence, and independence under the care plan.\n\nLesson Objectives\nExplain the purpose of rehabilitative nursing in home care.\nDescribe how the HHA supports independence during daily care.\nIdentify safe ways to assist with mobility, transfers, positioning, and range of motion.\nRecognize when to report pain, weakness, falls, skin concerns, or changes in ability.\nStay within the HHA role and follow the care plan, therapist instructions, and agency policy.\nWhy Rehabilitation Matters\n\nIllness, injury, surgery, aging, stroke, weakness, pain, or disability can make everyday tasks harder. Rehabilitation focuses on helping the client do as much as possible safely. This may include walking, dressing, bathing, eating, communicating, using equipment, and participating in meaningful routines.\n\nThe HHA is often the person who sees how the client functions in real life at home. Your observations help the nurse, therapist, and care team know whether the plan is working or whether the client needs more support.\n\nThe HHA Role\nEncourage the client to do what they can safely do.\nFollow the care plan exactly for exercises, transfers, walking, and equipment use.\nProtect dignity by offering choices and privacy.\nWatch for pain, fatigue, dizziness, shortness of breath, swelling, skin changes, or sudden weakness.\nReport changes promptly to the supervisor.\nQuick Learner Check\nWhat is the main goal of rehabilitative nursing?\nWhy should the HHA encourage the client to do parts of care they can safely do?\nWho should the HHA report changes in ability to?\nSuggested Answers\nThe main goal is to help the client maintain or regain the highest level of function and independence possible.\nDoing safe parts of care helps maintain strength, confidence, dignity, and independence.\nThe HHA should report changes to the supervisor, nurse, or agency contact according to the chain of command.\nRemember\n\nRehabilitation is not doing everything for the client. It is safely helping the client do as much as they can.\n\nSources for Instructor Review\nMedlinePlus: Rehabilitation\nLinks to an external site.\nNational Institute on Aging: Exercise and Physical Activity\nLinks to an external site.\nCDC: Older Adult Fall Prevention\nLinks to an external site.\nMerck Manual Consumer Version: Overview of Rehabilitation\nLinks to an external site.\n\nCanvas source: https://hic.instructure.com/courses/287/pages/chc-115-rehabilitative-nursing-overview?module_item_id=3145"
        },
        {
          "title": "CHC 115 Topic 1: Principles of Rehabilitative Care",
          "durationMinutes": 17,
          "content": "CHC 115 Topic 1: Principles of Rehabilitative Care\nCHC 115 Topic 1: Principles of Rehabilitative Care\nPrinciples of Rehabilitative Care\n\nRehabilitative care is built on patience, safety, repetition, encouragement, and respect for the client’s goals.\n\nWhole-Person Care\n\nRehabilitation is not only physical. A client may be coping with fear, frustration, grief, embarrassment, pain, or loss of independence. A calm HHA can help the client feel respected and capable. Small successes matter because they build confidence over time.\n\nThe care plan may include instructions from nurses, physical therapists, occupational therapists, speech-language pathologists, or other professionals. The HHA follows those instructions and reports what happens during care.\n\nKey Principles\nSafety: Prevent falls, injury, skin breakdown, and overexertion.\nIndependence: Let the client do what they can safely do.\nConsistency: Use the same safe methods taught by the care team.\nPatience: Allow extra time and avoid rushing.\nEncouragement: Praise effort, not just results.\nObservation: Notice changes and report concerns promptly.\nWhat the HHA Does Not Do\n\nThe HHA does not create exercise programs, change therapy instructions, force activity, or decide that a client no longer needs equipment. If the client refuses, has pain, becomes dizzy, or cannot complete a task, report it.\n\nQuick Learner Check\nName two principles of rehabilitative care.\nWhy should the aide avoid rushing?\nCan the HHA create a new exercise plan for the client?\nSuggested Answers\nExamples include safety, independence, consistency, patience, encouragement, and observation.\nRushing can increase falls, frustration, pain, and loss of dignity. Extra time helps the client participate safely.\nNo. The HHA follows the care plan and therapist or nurse instructions.\nRemember\n\nThe HHA supports the plan; the HHA does not redesign the plan.\n\nCanvas source: https://hic.instructure.com/courses/287/pages/chc-115-topic-1-principles-of-rehabilitative-care?module_item_id=3146"
        },
        {
          "title": "CHC 115 Topic 2: Promoting Independence with ADLs",
          "durationMinutes": 17,
          "content": "CHC 115 Topic 2: Promoting Independence with ADLs\nCHC 115 Topic 2: Promoting Independence with ADLs\nPromoting Independence with ADLs\n\nActivities of daily living are everyday self-care tasks. Supporting ADLs means helping only as much as needed while protecting safety and dignity.\n\nWhat Are ADLs?\n\nADLs are basic daily tasks such as bathing, dressing, grooming, toileting, eating, transferring, and walking. After illness or injury, a client may need help relearning or adapting these tasks. The HHA encourages participation whenever it is safe.\n\nHow to Encourage Independence\nSet up supplies within reach before beginning care.\nAsk the client which parts they can do independently.\nGive simple step-by-step cues instead of taking over right away.\nAllow enough time for the client to try.\nUse adaptive equipment listed in the care plan, such as grab bars, shower chairs, reachers, or special utensils.\nPraise effort and progress respectfully.\nBalancing Help and Safety\n\nIndependence does not mean leaving the client unsafe. Stay close when supervision is required. If the client becomes tired, dizzy, confused, short of breath, or unsafe, stop the task, help the client rest, and report according to policy.\n\nQuick Learner Check\nWhat does ADL mean?\nName one way to encourage independence during bathing or dressing.\nWhat should the HHA do if the client becomes dizzy during care?\nSuggested Answers\nADL means activity of daily living, such as bathing, dressing, eating, toileting, transferring, or walking.\nThe HHA can set up supplies, give cues, allow time, let the client do safe parts, or use approved adaptive equipment.\nStop the task, keep the client safe, allow rest, and report the dizziness according to agency policy.\nRemember\n\nHelping too much can take away independence. Helping too little can risk safety. Follow the care plan and observe carefully.\n\nCanvas source: https://hic.instructure.com/courses/287/pages/chc-115-topic-2-promoting-independence-with-adls?module_item_id=3147"
        },
        {
          "title": "CHC 115 Topic 3: Body Alignment and Positioning",
          "durationMinutes": 17,
          "content": "CHC 115 Topic 3: Body Alignment and Positioning\nCHC 115 Topic 3: Body Alignment and Positioning\nBody Alignment and Positioning\n\nGood positioning supports comfort, breathing, circulation, skin protection, and safe movement.\n\nWhy Positioning Matters\n\nClients who sit or lie in one position for too long may develop pain, stiffness, swelling, breathing difficulty, or pressure injuries. Proper alignment keeps the body in a natural position and reduces strain on muscles, joints, and skin.\n\nPositioning may include pillows, wedges, foot support, turning schedules, wheelchair positioning, or bed positioning. Always follow the care plan and nurse instructions.\n\nBasic Alignment Tips\nKeep the head, neck, spine, hips, knees, and feet supported as instructed.\nAvoid pulling on arms, shoulders, or weak limbs.\nUse pillows to prevent bony areas from rubbing together when directed.\nKeep heels, elbows, hips, and tailbone protected according to the care plan.\nMake sure the client can reach the call device, water, glasses, hearing aids, and needed items when appropriate.\nLock bed or wheelchair brakes before repositioning or transferring.\nReport Positioning Problems\n\nReport pain, redness that does not fade, swelling, numbness, tingling, new skin openings, shortness of breath, or a client who cannot maintain safe posture.\n\nQuick Learner Check\nWhy is positioning important?\nWhat should be locked before many transfers or repositioning tasks?\nName one skin or comfort concern to report.\nSuggested Answers\nPositioning helps comfort, breathing, circulation, skin protection, body alignment, and safe movement.\nWheelchair brakes, bed brakes, or equipment brakes should be locked as instructed before transfers or repositioning.\nReport redness that does not fade, swelling, pain, numbness, tingling, skin openings, or pressure areas.\nRemember\n\nA comfortable position is also a safety intervention. Poor alignment can lead to pain, falls, or skin injury.\n\nCanvas source: https://hic.instructure.com/courses/287/pages/chc-115-topic-3-body-alignment-and-positioning?module_item_id=3148"
        },
        {
          "title": "CHC 115 Topic 4: Range of Motion and Exercise Support",
          "durationMinutes": 17,
          "content": "CHC 115 Topic 4: Range of Motion and Exercise Support\nCHC 115 Topic 4: Range of Motion and Exercise Support\nRange of Motion and Exercise Support\n\nRange of motion helps keep joints flexible and muscles active. The HHA performs only exercises listed in the care plan and taught by the care team.\n\nWhat Range of Motion Means\n\nRange of motion means moving a joint through the movement it is supposed to make. ROM may be active, where the client moves independently; active-assisted, where the client moves with help; or passive, where the caregiver moves the body part for the client. Passive exercises require careful training and must follow the care plan.\n\nSafe Exercise Support\nExplain what you are going to do before starting.\nProvide privacy and position the client comfortably.\nMove slowly and gently according to the plan.\nNever force a joint or move past pain.\nWatch for pain, swelling, dizziness, shortness of breath, fatigue, or distress.\nStop and report if the client has new pain, refuses, or cannot complete the activity.\nWhy Activity Matters\n\nRegular approved activity can help maintain strength, flexibility, balance, circulation, mood, sleep, and independence. Even small movements can matter when they are done safely and consistently.\n\nQuick Learner Check\nWhat does range of motion mean?\nShould the HHA force a stiff joint to move farther?\nWhat should the aide do if exercise causes new pain?\nSuggested Answers\nRange of motion means moving a joint through its allowed movement.\nNo. Never force a joint or move past pain. Follow the care plan.\nStop the activity, keep the client safe, and report the new pain according to policy.\nRemember\n\nExercise support should feel controlled and safe, never forced.\n\nCanvas source: https://hic.instructure.com/courses/287/pages/chc-115-topic-4-range-of-motion-and-exercise-support?module_item_id=3149"
        },
        {
          "title": "CHC 115 Topic 5: Transfers, Ambulation, and Assistive Devices",
          "durationMinutes": 17,
          "content": "CHC 115 Topic 5: Transfers, Ambulation, and Assistive Devices\nCHC 115 Topic 5: Transfers, Ambulation, and Assistive Devices\nTransfers, Ambulation, and Assistive Devices\n\nSafe movement protects the client and the aide. Follow the care plan for gait belts, walkers, canes, wheelchairs, and transfer methods.\n\nTransfers and Ambulation\n\nA transfer means moving from one surface to another, such as bed to chair, chair to toilet, or wheelchair to shower chair. Ambulation means walking. Both can be high-risk activities, especially after illness, surgery, stroke, weakness, dizziness, or falls.\n\nThe HHA should use only the transfer and walking methods taught by the agency or care team. If the client needs more help than the plan allows, stop and call the supervisor.\n\nAssistive Devices\nUse walkers, canes, wheelchairs, gait belts, braces, prosthetics, and other devices exactly as instructed.\nCheck that equipment is nearby and in good condition before beginning.\nRemove clutter, loose rugs, wet spots, and cords from the path.\nMake sure the client has proper footwear when walking, if required.\nStay on the weaker side if directed and keep close enough to assist safely.\nDo not allow the client to use broken, poorly fitting, or unsafe equipment without reporting it.\nWarning Signs During Movement\n\nStop and report if the client has chest pain, new shortness of breath, dizziness, fainting, sudden weakness, severe pain, confusion, or a fall.\n\nQuick Learner Check\nWhat is ambulation?\nWhat should the aide do if the client needs more help than the care plan says?\nName one environmental hazard to remove before walking.\nSuggested Answers\nAmbulation means walking.\nStop the task if safe to do so, keep the client safe, and contact the supervisor for instructions.\nExamples include clutter, loose rugs, cords, wet floors, poor lighting, or furniture blocking the walkway.\nRemember\n\nA transfer is not routine if the client is weak, dizzy, confused, or unsafe. Ask for help before someone falls.\n\nCanvas source: https://hic.instructure.com/courses/287/pages/chc-115-topic-5-transfers-ambulation-and-assistive-devices?module_item_id=3150"
        },
        {
          "title": "CHC 115 Topic 6: Preventing Complications of Immobility",
          "durationMinutes": 17,
          "content": "CHC 115 Topic 6: Preventing Complications of Immobility\nCHC 115 Topic 6: Preventing Complications of Immobility\nPreventing Complications of Immobility\n\nWhen a client moves less, the risk of skin injury, weakness, stiffness, constipation, blood circulation problems, breathing problems, and mood changes can increase.\n\nWhy Immobility Is Risky\n\nImmobility means reduced movement. A client may become less mobile because of pain, illness, surgery, weakness, fear of falling, depression, or disability. When movement decreases, the body can lose strength and flexibility quickly. Skin may also be damaged by pressure, moisture, or friction.\n\nHHA Prevention Support\nReposition the client as directed in the care plan.\nEncourage approved activity and participation in ADLs.\nKeep skin clean and dry and report redness or open areas.\nOffer fluids and nutrition according to the care plan.\nAssist with toileting routines to reduce constipation and skin problems.\nKeep needed items within reach to prevent unsafe stretching or falls.\nSupport social interaction and normal routines when possible.\nReport These Concerns\nRedness, blisters, open skin, or drainage.\nNew swelling, pain, warmth, or color change in a limb.\nShortness of breath, cough, fever, or chest pain.\nSudden weakness, confusion, or decreased ability to move.\nNew sadness, withdrawal, or loss of interest in usual activities.\nQuick Learner Check\nName one complication of immobility.\nWhy should skin redness be reported?\nHow can ADL participation help the client?\nSuggested Answers\nComplications may include pressure injuries, weakness, stiffness, constipation, circulation problems, breathing problems, falls, or mood changes.\nRedness can be an early sign of pressure injury or skin breakdown, especially if it does not fade.\nParticipating in ADLs helps maintain strength, coordination, confidence, routine, and independence.\nRemember\n\nSmall movements, safe positioning, and early reporting can prevent larger problems.\n\nCanvas source: https://hic.instructure.com/courses/287/pages/chc-115-topic-6-preventing-complications-of-immobility?module_item_id=3151"
        },
        {
          "title": "CHC 115 Topic 7: Communication, Motivation, and Emotional Support",
          "durationMinutes": 17,
          "content": "CHC 115 Topic 7: Communication, Motivation, and Emotional Support\nCHC 115 Topic 7: Communication, Motivation, and Emotional Support\nCommunication and Motivation\n\nRecovery can be frustrating. The HHA supports progress with patience, encouragement, respectful choices, and clear reporting.\n\nThe Emotional Side of Rehabilitation\n\nClients may feel embarrassed, angry, sad, afraid, or discouraged when they cannot do tasks they used to do easily. They may refuse activity because of pain, fear of falling, depression, fatigue, or past bad experiences. The HHA should respond with patience, not judgment.\n\nHelpful Communication\nGive clear, simple instructions one step at a time.\nOffer choices when possible, such as which shirt to put on first.\nPraise effort: “You worked hard on standing today.”\nAvoid talking to adults like children.\nDo not argue if the client refuses. Report refusals according to policy.\nUse active listening when the client expresses fear or frustration.\nMotivation Without Pressure\n\nEncouragement is different from forcing. If a task is in the care plan, explain its purpose and offer support. If the client refuses or has symptoms, respect the refusal, keep the client safe, and report.\n\nQuick Learner Check\nWhy might a client refuse rehabilitation activities?\nGive one example of encouraging language.\nWhat should the aide do if the client refuses an assigned activity?\nSuggested Answers\nReasons may include pain, fear of falling, fatigue, depression, embarrassment, confusion, or lack of understanding.\nExample: “You worked hard today,” “Let’s take this one step at a time,” or “I can see your effort.”\nDo not force the client. Respect the refusal, keep the client safe, document or report according to agency policy, and notify the supervisor.\nRemember\n\nEncouragement should build confidence, not pressure the client into unsafe activity.\n\nCanvas source: https://hic.instructure.com/courses/287/pages/chc-115-topic-7-communication-motivation-and-emotional-support-2?module_item_id=3152"
        },
        {
          "title": "CHC 115 Topic 8: Reporting Changes and Staying Within Scope",
          "durationMinutes": 17,
          "content": "CHC 115 Topic 8: Reporting Changes and Staying Within Scope\nCHC 115 Topic 8: Reporting Changes and Staying Within Scope\nReporting Changes and Staying Within Scope\n\nThe HHA is an important observer. Reporting changes quickly helps the care team update the plan and prevent injury.\n\nWhat to Report\nFalls, near falls, new fear of walking, or unsafe transfers.\nNew or worsening pain, swelling, weakness, numbness, tingling, or stiffness.\nDizziness, fainting, shortness of breath, chest pain, or unusual fatigue.\nSkin redness, open areas, blisters, drainage, or pressure areas.\nChanges in appetite, toileting, sleep, mood, confusion, or behavior.\nEquipment problems, missing supplies, broken devices, or unsafe home conditions.\nClient refusal of exercises, walking, positioning, or ADL participation.\nStay Within Scope\n\nThe HHA follows the care plan and agency policy. Do not change exercises, add new therapy activities, stop required equipment, adjust braces, change weight-bearing instructions, or decide that a client is safe to walk alone unless the care plan says so. When unsure, ask the supervisor.\n\nGood Documentation\n\nDocument objective facts. For example: “Client walked 10 feet with walker and gait belt, then stated, ‘I feel dizzy.’ Client sat in chair. Supervisor notified.” This is more useful than “Client did badly today.”\n\nQuick Learner Check\nName two changes the HHA should report.\nCan the HHA change a therapist’s exercise instructions?\nWhy is objective documentation important?\nSuggested Answers\nExamples include falls, near falls, pain, weakness, dizziness, shortness of breath, skin redness, refusal, equipment problems, or unsafe home conditions.\nNo. The HHA follows the care plan and reports concerns to the supervisor or therapist through the proper channel.\nObjective documentation gives the care team clear facts they can use to make safe decisions.\nRemember\n\nWhen in doubt, report. Small changes can be early signs of a bigger problem.\n\nCanvas source: https://hic.instructure.com/courses/287/pages/chc-115-topic-8-reporting-changes-and-staying-within-scope?module_item_id=3153"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "CHC 116 - Patient Care Skills (10 hours)",
      "lessons": [
        {
          "title": "CHC 116: The 12 Body Systems Overview",
          "durationMinutes": 17,
          "content": "CHC 116: The 12 Body Systems Overview\nCHC 116: The 12 Body Systems Overview\nUnderstanding the Body Helps You Provide Better Care\n\nHome Health Aides do not need to diagnose disease, but they do need to understand how body systems work together and what changes should be reported.\n\nLesson Objectives\n\nBy the end of this module, learners should be able to name the 12 body systems, explain basic functions, connect each system to daily HHA care, and identify changes that should be reported.\n\nDescribe the basic purpose of each body system.\nRecognize that body systems work together, not separately.\nObserve changes during bathing, dressing, eating, walking, toileting, and conversation.\nReport new, unusual, worsening, or unsafe changes promptly.\nStay within the HHA role by observing, reporting, documenting, and following the care plan.\nThe 12 Systems Covered\n1. Integumentary System\n2. Skeletal System\n3. Muscular System\n4. Nervous System\n5. Sensory System\n6. Cardiovascular System\n7. Respiratory System\n8. Digestive System\n9. Urinary System\n10. Endocrine System\n11. Reproductive System\n12. Lymphatic and Immune System\nWhy This Matters in Patient Care Skills\n\nWhen an HHA helps with personal care, they are also observing the client’s condition. Skin color, breathing, appetite, balance, mood, urine, bowel patterns, pain, and activity level all give important information. Understanding body systems helps the aide notice and report meaningful changes.\n\nImportant\n\nLearning body systems does not make the HHA responsible for diagnosis. It helps the HHA observe better and communicate clearly with the care team.\n\nQuick Learner Check\nWhy should an HHA learn the body systems?\nDoes the HHA diagnose body system problems?\nName three daily care activities where an HHA may observe health changes.\nSuggested Answers\nLearning body systems helps the HHA understand what they are observing and what changes may need reporting.\nNo. The HHA observes, reports, documents, and follows the care plan.\nExamples include bathing, dressing, eating, walking, toileting, transfers, oral care, skin care, and conversation.\nRemember\n\nThe HHA is the eyes and ears of the care team. Understanding the body makes those observations stronger.\n\nReference for instructor review: MedlinePlus Health Topics\nLinks to an external site.\n | NCI Body System Definition\nLinks to an external site.\n | OpenStax Anatomy and Physiology\nLinks to an external site.\n\nCanvas source: https://hic.instructure.com/courses/287/pages/chc-116-the-12-body-systems-overview?module_item_id=3241"
        },
        {
          "title": "CHC 116 Body Systems Topic 1: Integumentary System",
          "durationMinutes": 17,
          "content": "CHC 116 Body Systems Topic 1: Integumentary System\nCHC 116 Body Systems Topic 1: Integumentary System\nSkin, Hair, Nails, and Protection\n\nThe integumentary system includes the skin, hair, nails, and glands. It protects the body from injury, germs, fluid loss, and temperature changes.\n\nIntegumentary system: skin layers and protective structures. Image source: Wikimedia Commons / National Cancer Institute, public domain. View source\nLinks to an external site.\n.\nWhat This System Does\n\nSkin protects the body, helps control temperature, allows touch sensation, and gives clues about hydration, circulation, infection, nutrition, and injury.\n\nHow This Connects to HHA Care\n\nIn patient care, the HHA observes skin during bathing, dressing, toileting, repositioning, and personal care. Always protect privacy and only inspect areas related to assigned care.\n\nWhat to Observe and Report\n\nReport redness that does not fade, open areas, bruises, burns, rashes, swelling, drainage, odor, pain, itching, pressure areas, skin that is very hot or cold, or changes in color.\n\nStay in Your Role\n\nThe HHA observes and reports. The HHA does not diagnose, promise outcomes, or change the care plan without direction.\n\nQuick Learner Check\nWhat body parts are included in the integumentary system?\nWhy is skin observation important during personal care?\nName two skin changes the HHA should report.\nSuggested Answers\nSkin, hair, nails, and glands are part of the integumentary system.\nPersonal care gives the aide a chance to notice redness, wounds, bruising, pressure areas, hygiene concerns, or signs of infection.\nExamples include redness, open areas, bruises, burns, rashes, swelling, drainage, odor, pain, or skin color changes.\nRemember\n\nSkin changes can be early warning signs. Report new, unusual, or worsening skin concerns promptly.\n\nReference for instructor review: MedlinePlus Health Topics\nLinks to an external site.\n | NCI Body System Definition\nLinks to an external site.\n | OpenStax Anatomy and Physiology\nLinks to an external site.\n\nCanvas source: https://hic.instructure.com/courses/287/pages/chc-116-body-systems-topic-1-integumentary-system?module_item_id=3242"
        },
        {
          "title": "CHC 116 Body Systems Topic 2: Skeletal System",
          "durationMinutes": 17,
          "content": "CHC 116 Body Systems Topic 2: Skeletal System\nCHC 116 Body Systems Topic 2: Skeletal System\nBones, Joints, and Body Support\n\nThe skeletal system gives the body shape, protects organs, stores minerals, and works with muscles to allow movement.\n\nSkeletal system: bones provide structure, protection, and support for movement. Image source: Wikimedia Commons, public domain. View source\nLinks to an external site.\n.\nWhat This System Does\n\nBones protect important organs such as the brain, heart, and lungs. Joints allow movement, and posture depends on the strength and alignment of the skeleton.\n\nHow This Connects to HHA Care\n\nAn HHA supports the skeletal system by using safe body mechanics, helping with proper positioning, following fall-prevention steps, and encouraging safe movement as directed by the care plan.\n\nWhat to Observe and Report\n\nReport new pain, swelling, deformity, limited movement, falls, difficulty standing, unusual posture, or any injury after a fall. Do not move a client with suspected fracture unless emergency instructions require it.\n\nStay in Your Role\n\nThe HHA observes and reports. The HHA does not diagnose, promise outcomes, or change the care plan without direction.\n\nQuick Learner Check\nWhat does the skeletal system do?\nHow can an HHA protect the client’s bones and joints?\nWhat should be reported after a fall?\nSuggested Answers\nIt supports the body, protects organs, stores minerals, and works with muscles for movement.\nUse safe transfers, proper positioning, fall prevention, and follow the care plan.\nReport the fall, pain, swelling, deformity, bruising, limited movement, head injury, or any change in condition.\nRemember\n\nBones and joints need safe handling. Never force movement or ignore pain after a fall.\n\nReference for instructor review: MedlinePlus Health Topics\nLinks to an external site.\n | NCI Body System Definition\nLinks to an external site.\n | OpenStax Anatomy and Physiology\nLinks to an external site.\n\nCanvas source: https://hic.instructure.com/courses/287/pages/chc-116-body-systems-topic-2-skeletal-system?module_item_id=3243"
        },
        {
          "title": "CHC 116 Body Systems Topic 3: Muscular System",
          "durationMinutes": 17,
          "content": "CHC 116 Body Systems Topic 3: Muscular System\nCHC 116 Body Systems Topic 3: Muscular System\nMovement, Strength, and Body Control\n\nThe muscular system helps the body move, maintain posture, breathe, swallow, and perform daily activities.\n\nMuscular system: muscles support movement, posture, and daily activity. Image source: Wikimedia Commons, CC BY-SA. View source\nLinks to an external site.\n.\nWhat This System Does\n\nMuscles work with bones and nerves. Some muscles are voluntary, such as arm and leg muscles. Others work automatically, such as muscles involved in digestion and the heartbeat.\n\nHow This Connects to HHA Care\n\nIn home care, muscle strength affects bathing, dressing, transfers, walking, toileting, feeding, and fall risk. The HHA should encourage the client to do what they safely can, instead of taking over every task.\n\nWhat to Observe and Report\n\nReport new weakness, muscle pain, tremors, stiffness, cramping, poor coordination, trouble swallowing, reduced ability to transfer, or a sudden change in one side of the body.\n\nStay in Your Role\n\nThe HHA observes and reports. The HHA does not diagnose, promise outcomes, or change the care plan without direction.\n\nQuick Learner Check\nWhy are muscles important for daily care?\nWhy should the HHA encourage safe independence?\nName one muscle-related change to report.\nSuggested Answers\nMuscles help with movement, posture, breathing, swallowing, transfers, walking, and self-care.\nDoing safe tasks helps the client maintain strength, confidence, and independence.\nReport new weakness, pain, tremors, stiffness, cramping, poor coordination, trouble swallowing, or sudden one-sided weakness.\nRemember\n\nSupport movement, but do not push beyond safety. Sudden weakness may be urgent.\n\nReference for instructor review: MedlinePlus Health Topics\nLinks to an external site.\n | NCI Body System Definition\nLinks to an external site.\n | OpenStax Anatomy and Physiology\nLinks to an external site.\n\nCanvas source: https://hic.instructure.com/courses/287/pages/chc-116-body-systems-topic-3-muscular-system?module_item_id=3244"
        },
        {
          "title": "CHC 116 Body Systems Topic 4: Nervous System",
          "durationMinutes": 17,
          "content": "CHC 116 Body Systems Topic 4: Nervous System\nCHC 116 Body Systems Topic 4: Nervous System\nBrain, Spinal Cord, and Nerves\n\nThe nervous system controls thinking, movement, sensation, speech, memory, and many body functions.\n\nNervous system: brain, spinal cord, and nerves control body messages. Image source: Wikimedia Commons, CC BY-SA. View source\nLinks to an external site.\n.\nWhat This System Does\n\nThe brain and spinal cord send messages through nerves. These messages help the client move, feel pain or touch, speak, remember, and respond to the environment.\n\nHow This Connects to HHA Care\n\nThe HHA may notice nervous system changes during conversation, walking, eating, dressing, or following directions. Sudden changes can be serious.\n\nWhat to Observe and Report\n\nReport sudden confusion, new trouble speaking, facial drooping, one-sided weakness, new numbness, severe headache, seizures, loss of consciousness, new dizziness, or major behavior changes.\n\nStay in Your Role\n\nThe HHA observes and reports. The HHA does not diagnose, promise outcomes, or change the care plan without direction.\n\nQuick Learner Check\nWhat does the nervous system control?\nName two nervous system changes that should be reported quickly.\nWhy are sudden changes important?\nSuggested Answers\nIt controls thinking, movement, sensation, speech, memory, and many body functions.\nExamples include sudden confusion, trouble speaking, facial drooping, one-sided weakness, seizure, severe headache, loss of consciousness, or new numbness.\nSudden changes may signal an emergency such as stroke, seizure, infection, medication problem, or other serious condition.\nRemember\n\nSudden nervous system changes can be emergencies. Follow agency policy and get help quickly.\n\nReference for instructor review: MedlinePlus Health Topics\nLinks to an external site.\n | NCI Body System Definition\nLinks to an external site.\n | OpenStax Anatomy and Physiology\nLinks to an external site.\n\nCanvas source: https://hic.instructure.com/courses/287/pages/chc-116-body-systems-topic-4-nervous-system?module_item_id=3245"
        },
        {
          "title": "CHC 116 Body Systems Topic 5: Sensory System",
          "durationMinutes": 17,
          "content": "CHC 116 Body Systems Topic 5: Sensory System\nCHC 116 Body Systems Topic 5: Sensory System\nSight, Hearing, Taste, Smell, and Touch\n\nThe sensory system helps people understand the world through sight, hearing, taste, smell, touch, balance, and body awareness.\n\nSensory system example: the eye helps the client receive visual information from the environment. Image source: Wikimedia Commons. View source\nLinks to an external site.\n.\nWhat This System Does\n\nSensory changes can affect safety and communication. A client with poor vision may trip. A client with hearing loss may miss instructions. A client with reduced feeling in the feet may not notice injury.\n\nHow This Connects to HHA Care\n\nThe HHA should speak clearly, face the client, reduce background noise, keep pathways clear, make sure glasses or hearing aids are available if used, and report changes.\n\nWhat to Observe and Report\n\nReport new vision loss, hearing changes, dizziness, balance problems, numbness, tingling, loss of feeling, burns or injuries the client did not notice, or inability to smell smoke, spoiled food, or gas.\n\nStay in Your Role\n\nThe HHA observes and reports. The HHA does not diagnose, promise outcomes, or change the care plan without direction.\n\nQuick Learner Check\nHow can sensory changes affect safety?\nWhat can an HHA do to support a client with hearing loss?\nName one sensory change to report.\nSuggested Answers\nThey can increase fall risk, communication problems, burns, unnoticed injuries, or difficulty recognizing hazards.\nFace the client, speak clearly, reduce noise, allow time, and make sure hearing aids are available if used.\nReport new vision loss, hearing changes, dizziness, numbness, tingling, poor balance, or injuries the client did not notice.\nRemember\n\nSensory loss can make ordinary tasks unsafe. Adapt care and report changes.\n\nReference for instructor review: MedlinePlus Health Topics\nLinks to an external site.\n | NCI Body System Definition\nLinks to an external site.\n | OpenStax Anatomy and Physiology\nLinks to an external site.\n\nCanvas source: https://hic.instructure.com/courses/287/pages/chc-116-body-systems-topic-5-sensory-system?module_item_id=3246"
        },
        {
          "title": "CHC 116 Body Systems Topic 6: Cardiovascular System",
          "durationMinutes": 17,
          "content": "CHC 116 Body Systems Topic 6: Cardiovascular System\nCHC 116 Body Systems Topic 6: Cardiovascular System\nHeart, Blood, and Circulation\n\nThe cardiovascular system moves blood through the body, carrying oxygen and nutrients to tissues and removing waste products.\n\nCardiovascular system: the heart and blood vessels move blood through the body. Image source: Wikimedia Commons, public domain. View source\nLinks to an external site.\n.\nWhat This System Does\n\nThe heart pumps blood through blood vessels. Good circulation helps the skin, brain, muscles, and organs receive oxygen and nutrients.\n\nHow This Connects to HHA Care\n\nThe HHA may observe cardiovascular clues such as skin color, swelling, fatigue, shortness of breath with activity, dizziness, chest discomfort, or changes in endurance.\n\nWhat to Observe and Report\n\nReport chest pain or pressure, shortness of breath, fainting, sudden weakness, blue or gray lips, new swelling in feet or legs, sudden weight gain, unusual fatigue, or fast/irregular pulse if pulse is assigned.\n\nStay in Your Role\n\nThe HHA observes and reports. The HHA does not diagnose, promise outcomes, or change the care plan without direction.\n\nQuick Learner Check\nWhat does the cardiovascular system do?\nName two cardiovascular changes to report.\nWhy might swelling in the legs matter?\nSuggested Answers\nIt circulates blood, oxygen, nutrients, and waste products through the body.\nExamples include chest pain, shortness of breath, fainting, blue lips, new swelling, sudden weight gain, dizziness, or unusual fatigue.\nSwelling may be a sign of fluid changes or circulation concerns and should be reported according to policy.\nRemember\n\nChest pain, severe shortness of breath, or fainting may be urgent. Follow emergency procedures.\n\nReference for instructor review: MedlinePlus Health Topics\nLinks to an external site.\n | NCI Body System Definition\nLinks to an external site.\n | OpenStax Anatomy and Physiology\nLinks to an external site.\n\nCanvas source: https://hic.instructure.com/courses/287/pages/chc-116-body-systems-topic-6-cardiovascular-system?module_item_id=3247"
        },
        {
          "title": "CHC 116 Body Systems Topic 7: Respiratory System",
          "durationMinutes": 17,
          "content": "CHC 116 Body Systems Topic 7: Respiratory System\nCHC 116 Body Systems Topic 7: Respiratory System\nBreathing and Oxygen\n\nThe respiratory system brings oxygen into the body and removes carbon dioxide through breathing.\n\nRespiratory system: airways and lungs bring oxygen into the body. Image source: Wikimedia Commons, public domain. View source\nLinks to an external site.\n.\nWhat This System Does\n\nThe respiratory system includes the nose, throat, airways, and lungs. Breathing problems can become serious quickly, especially for older adults or clients with chronic illness.\n\nHow This Connects to HHA Care\n\nThe HHA observes breathing during rest, walking, bathing, dressing, eating, and sleep. Notice rate, effort, cough, sputum, wheezing, and whether the client can speak comfortably.\n\nWhat to Observe and Report\n\nReport new or worsening shortness of breath, wheezing, chest tightness, coughing blood, blue lips, fever with cough, choking, noisy breathing, or needing to sit upright to breathe.\n\nStay in Your Role\n\nThe HHA observes and reports. The HHA does not diagnose, promise outcomes, or change the care plan without direction.\n\nQuick Learner Check\nWhat is the main job of the respiratory system?\nName two breathing changes to report.\nWhat should the HHA observe during activity?\nSuggested Answers\nIt brings oxygen into the body and removes carbon dioxide.\nExamples include shortness of breath, wheezing, chest tightness, blue lips, coughing blood, choking, fever with cough, or noisy breathing.\nObserve breathing effort, fatigue, cough, color, dizziness, and whether the client can continue safely.\nRemember\n\nBreathing changes can worsen fast. Stay calm, keep the client safe, and report immediately when needed.\n\nReference for instructor review: MedlinePlus Health Topics\nLinks to an external site.\n | NCI Body System Definition\nLinks to an external site.\n | OpenStax Anatomy and Physiology\nLinks to an external site.\n\nCanvas source: https://hic.instructure.com/courses/287/pages/chc-116-body-systems-topic-7-respiratory-system?module_item_id=3248"
        },
        {
          "title": "CHC 116 Body Systems Topic 8: Digestive System",
          "durationMinutes": 17,
          "content": "CHC 116 Body Systems Topic 8: Digestive System\nCHC 116 Body Systems Topic 8: Digestive System\nFood, Nutrition, and Elimination\n\nThe digestive system breaks down food, absorbs nutrients, and removes solid waste from the body.\n\nDigestive system: organs break down food, absorb nutrients, and remove solid waste. Image source: Wikimedia Commons, public domain. View source\nLinks to an external site.\n.\nWhat This System Does\n\nThe digestive system includes the mouth, esophagus, stomach, intestines, liver, gallbladder, pancreas, and rectum. Nutrition and elimination are closely connected to health.\n\nHow This Connects to HHA Care\n\nThe HHA supports digestion by preparing meals as assigned, encouraging safe eating, observing appetite, helping with oral care, and reporting concerns.\n\nWhat to Observe and Report\n\nReport poor appetite, difficulty chewing or swallowing, coughing during meals, nausea, vomiting, diarrhea, constipation, abdominal pain, blood in stool, black/tarry stool, dehydration signs, or sudden weight changes.\n\nStay in Your Role\n\nThe HHA observes and reports. The HHA does not diagnose, promise outcomes, or change the care plan without direction.\n\nQuick Learner Check\nWhat does the digestive system do?\nWhy is coughing during meals important?\nName two digestive changes to report.\nSuggested Answers\nIt breaks down food, absorbs nutrients, and removes solid waste.\nCoughing during meals may show swallowing difficulty or choking risk and should be reported.\nExamples include poor appetite, vomiting, diarrhea, constipation, abdominal pain, blood in stool, black stool, dehydration, or weight change.\nRemember\n\nEating, drinking, and bowel patterns tell an important health story. Report changes clearly.\n\nReference for instructor review: MedlinePlus Health Topics\nLinks to an external site.\n | NCI Body System Definition\nLinks to an external site.\n | OpenStax Anatomy and Physiology\nLinks to an external site.\n\nCanvas source: https://hic.instructure.com/courses/287/pages/chc-116-body-systems-topic-8-digestive-system?module_item_id=3249"
        },
        {
          "title": "CHC 116 Body Systems Topic 9: Urinary System",
          "durationMinutes": 17,
          "content": "CHC 116 Body Systems Topic 9: Urinary System\nCHC 116 Body Systems Topic 9: Urinary System\nFluid Balance and Urine\n\nThe urinary system removes waste from the blood, makes urine, and helps balance fluids in the body.\n\nUrinary system: kidneys, ureters, bladder, and urethra help remove waste and balance fluids. Image source: Wikimedia Commons, CC BY-SA. View source\nLinks to an external site.\n.\nWhat This System Does\n\nThe urinary system includes the kidneys, ureters, bladder, and urethra. Urine changes can show hydration problems, infection, kidney concerns, or other health changes.\n\nHow This Connects to HHA Care\n\nThe HHA may assist with toileting, catheter bag observation if assigned, perineal care, and intake/output recording. Always provide privacy and use infection control.\n\nWhat to Observe and Report\n\nReport pain or burning with urination, blood in urine, very little urine, strong odor, cloudy urine, new incontinence, lower abdominal pain, fever, confusion, catheter problems, or swelling.\n\nStay in Your Role\n\nThe HHA observes and reports. The HHA does not diagnose, promise outcomes, or change the care plan without direction.\n\nQuick Learner Check\nWhat organs are part of the urinary system?\nWhy is privacy important during urinary care?\nName two urinary changes to report.\nSuggested Answers\nKidneys, ureters, bladder, and urethra are part of the urinary system.\nUrinary care is personal and private. Respect protects dignity and trust.\nExamples include pain or burning, blood, cloudy urine, strong odor, very little urine, new incontinence, fever, confusion, or catheter problems.\nRemember\n\nUrine changes can be health clues. Report changes without embarrassment or judgment.\n\nReference for instructor review: MedlinePlus Health Topics\nLinks to an external site.\n | NCI Body System Definition\nLinks to an external site.\n | OpenStax Anatomy and Physiology\nLinks to an external site.\n\nCanvas source: https://hic.instructure.com/courses/287/pages/chc-116-body-systems-topic-9-urinary-system?module_item_id=3250"
        },
        {
          "title": "CHC 116 Body Systems Topic 10: Endocrine System",
          "durationMinutes": 17,
          "content": "CHC 116 Body Systems Topic 10: Endocrine System\nCHC 116 Body Systems Topic 10: Endocrine System\nHormones and Body Balance\n\nThe endocrine system uses hormones to help control blood sugar, growth, metabolism, stress response, and many body functions.\n\nEndocrine system: hormone-producing glands help regulate body functions. Image source: Wikimedia Commons / NIH, public domain. View source\nLinks to an external site.\n.\nWhat This System Does\n\nEndocrine glands release hormones into the blood. Diabetes is one common endocrine condition HHAs may see in home care.\n\nHow This Connects to HHA Care\n\nThe HHA does not adjust medications or diagnose blood sugar problems. The aide follows the care plan, observes symptoms, supports meals and safety, and reports concerns.\n\nWhat to Observe and Report\n\nReport unusual sweating, shakiness, confusion, extreme thirst, frequent urination, unusual hunger, weakness, dizziness, fruity breath odor, wounds that heal slowly, or behavior changes in a client with diabetes or endocrine problems.\n\nStay in Your Role\n\nThe HHA observes and reports. The HHA does not diagnose, promise outcomes, or change the care plan without direction.\n\nQuick Learner Check\nWhat does the endocrine system use to control body functions?\nWhat common endocrine condition may HHAs see?\nShould an HHA adjust diabetes medication?\nSuggested Answers\nIt uses hormones.\nDiabetes is a common endocrine condition in home care.\nNo. Medication changes are outside the HHA role. The aide reports concerns and follows the care plan.\nRemember\n\nHormone problems can affect the whole body. Observe symptoms and stay within the HHA role.\n\nReference for instructor review: MedlinePlus Health Topics\nLinks to an external site.\n | NCI Body System Definition\nLinks to an external site.\n | OpenStax Anatomy and Physiology\nLinks to an external site.\n\nCanvas source: https://hic.instructure.com/courses/287/pages/chc-116-body-systems-topic-10-endocrine-system?module_item_id=3251"
        },
        {
          "title": "CHC 116 Body Systems Topic 11: Reproductive System",
          "durationMinutes": 17,
          "content": "CHC 116 Body Systems Topic 11: Reproductive System\nCHC 116 Body Systems Topic 11: Reproductive System\nPrivacy, Dignity, and Personal Care\n\nThe reproductive system includes organs related to reproduction and sexual health. In home care, the HHA mainly supports privacy, hygiene, dignity, and reporting concerns.\n\nReproductive system example: reproductive organs require privacy, dignity, and respectful care. Image source: Wikimedia Commons, public domain. View source\nLinks to an external site.\n.\nWhat This System Does\n\nClients may need help with bathing, toileting, incontinence care, menstrual care, perineal care, or dressing. This care must be respectful, private, and professional.\n\nHow This Connects to HHA Care\n\nThe HHA should explain care before touching, cover the client as much as possible, use gloves when appropriate, wipe front to back during perineal care, and follow infection control and agency policy.\n\nWhat to Observe and Report\n\nReport unusual bleeding, discharge, odor, pain, itching, sores, swelling, signs of infection, sudden behavior changes during care, or any concern for abuse or unsafe sexual contact.\n\nStay in Your Role\n\nThe HHA observes and reports. The HHA does not diagnose, promise outcomes, or change the care plan without direction.\n\nQuick Learner Check\nWhy is dignity especially important during reproductive or perineal care?\nWhat direction is usually used for wiping during perineal care?\nName one concern to report.\nSuggested Answers\nThis care involves private body areas, so respect, privacy, and professional behavior protect the client’s dignity and trust.\nFront to back is used to reduce the spread of germs from the rectal area toward the urinary or genital area.\nReport unusual bleeding, discharge, odor, pain, itching, sores, swelling, infection signs, or abuse concerns.\nRemember\n\nPrivate care must always be respectful care. Protect dignity and report concerns.\n\nReference for instructor review: MedlinePlus Health Topics\nLinks to an external site.\n | NCI Body System Definition\nLinks to an external site.\n | OpenStax Anatomy and Physiology\nLinks to an external site.\n\nCanvas source: https://hic.instructure.com/courses/287/pages/chc-116-body-systems-topic-11-reproductive-system?module_item_id=3252"
        },
        {
          "title": "CHC 116 Body Systems Topic 12: Lymphatic and Immune System",
          "durationMinutes": 17,
          "content": "CHC 116 Body Systems Topic 12: Lymphatic and Immune System\nCHC 116 Body Systems Topic 12: Lymphatic and Immune System\nDefense, Fluid Movement, and Infection Protection\n\nThe lymphatic and immune system helps defend the body against infection and helps move fluid through tissues.\n\nLymphatic and immune system: lymph vessels and immune defenses help protect the body. Image source: Wikimedia Commons / NIH, public domain. View source\nLinks to an external site.\n.\nWhat This System Does\n\nThe immune system fights germs. The lymphatic system includes lymph nodes and vessels that help move fluid and support immune defense.\n\nHow This Connects to HHA Care\n\nOlder adults and clients with chronic illness may have weaker defenses. Infection control, hand hygiene, clean supplies, safe food handling, and reporting symptoms are important HHA responsibilities.\n\nWhat to Observe and Report\n\nReport fever, chills, new confusion, swollen glands, redness, warmth, drainage, worsening wounds, unusual fatigue, sore throat, cough, diarrhea, or signs of infection. Follow standard precautions with every client.\n\nStay in Your Role\n\nThe HHA observes and reports. The HHA does not diagnose, promise outcomes, or change the care plan without direction.\n\nQuick Learner Check\nWhat does the immune system do?\nWhy is infection control important for HHAs?\nName two signs of infection to report.\nSuggested Answers\nIt helps defend the body against germs and infection.\nMany clients are vulnerable. Hand hygiene, PPE, cleaning, and safe care reduce the spread of germs.\nExamples include fever, chills, redness, warmth, drainage, swollen glands, cough, sore throat, diarrhea, worsening wounds, or new confusion.\nRemember\n\nInfection prevention is patient care. Clean hands and early reporting protect vulnerable clients.\n\nReference for instructor review: MedlinePlus Health Topics\nLinks to an external site.\n | NCI Body System Definition\nLinks to an external site.\n | OpenStax Anatomy and Physiology\nLinks to an external site.\n\nCanvas source: https://hic.instructure.com/courses/287/pages/chc-116-body-systems-topic-12-lymphatic-and-immune-system?module_item_id=3253"
        },
        {
          "title": "CHC 116: Cultural Competence in Patient Care Overview",
          "durationMinutes": 17,
          "content": "CHC 116: Cultural Competence in Patient Care Overview\nCHC 116: Cultural Competence in Patient Care Overview\nCultural Competence in Patient Care\n\nCultural competence helps the Home Health Aide provide respectful care that protects dignity, builds trust, and supports the client as a whole person.\n\nLesson Objectives\nExplain why culture matters in home care and patient care skills.\nDescribe how beliefs, values, language, family roles, food, touch, time, and past experiences can affect care.\nUse respectful questions to learn what each client prefers.\nRecognize personal bias and avoid stereotyping.\nBuild trust through honesty, permission, consistency, and follow-through.\nWhy This Matters\n\nEvery client brings a life story into care. Culture may include race, ethnicity, religion, language, family traditions, gender, sexual orientation, education, work history, disability, and personal experience. Two people from the same background may still have very different preferences.\n\nFor the HHA, cultural competence means being ready to respond to the unique qualities of each person. It does not mean memorizing rules about groups. It means listening, observing, asking respectful questions, and following the care plan while honoring the client’s dignity.\n\nWhat You Will Study\nWhat culture means in health care.\nCultural competence and cultural humility.\nHealth beliefs and healing practices.\nRespectful communication, forms of address, gestures, and eye contact.\nLanguage, literacy, interpreters, personal space, touch, modesty, food, family, and decision-making.\nSelf-awareness, bias, historical trauma, trust, and the Platinum Rule.\nQuick Learner Check\nWhat does cultural competence help protect?\nDoes cultural competence mean treating every person from one group the same way?\nWhat is one respectful way to learn a client’s preference?\nSuggested Answers\nIt helps protect the client’s dignity, choices, safety, privacy, and trust.\nNo. Culture gives helpful clues, but each client is an individual. The aide should ask and observe instead of assuming.\nAsk open-ended questions such as, “How would you like me to help?” or “Is there anything about your culture or religion I should know to give better care?”\nRemember\n\nCultural competence begins with respect. The client is the expert on their own preferences, routines, and meaning of quality care.\n\nCanvas source: https://hic.instructure.com/courses/287/pages/chc-116-cultural-competence-in-patient-care-overview?module_item_id=3124"
        },
        {
          "title": "CHC 116 Topic 1: What Culture Means in Health Care",
          "durationMinutes": 17,
          "content": "CHC 116 Topic 1: What Culture Means in Health Care\nCHC 116 Topic 1: What Culture Means in Health Care\nWhat Culture Means in Health Care\n\nCulture influences how people understand illness, privacy, family roles, food, time, communication, and care decisions.\n\nCulture Is Broad\n\nCulture is not only nationality or race. It can include language, religion, family customs, age, disability, education, work, military experience, gender identity, sexual orientation, neighborhood, and personal history. Culture shapes what feels respectful, safe, private, or acceptable.\n\nHealth care also has its own culture. In many health care settings, providers value individual choice, schedules, written instructions, technology, and fast problem solving. Some clients may share these values, and others may not. A client may value family discussion, traditional healing practices, prayer, privacy, or relationship-building before tasks are done.\n\nCulture Affects Care\nHow a client explains illness or pain.\nWho the client trusts with information.\nWhether the client prefers direct or gentle communication.\nWhich foods, clothing, routines, or spiritual practices matter.\nHow the client feels about touch, bathing, modesty, medicine, or outside help.\nAvoid Assumptions\n\nA cultural pattern is not a rule. The safest approach is to treat each client as an individual. Ask before assuming, listen to the answer, and report important preferences to the supervisor according to agency policy.\n\nQuick Learner Check\nName two things culture can include besides race or nationality.\nWhy can health care itself be considered a culture?\nWhat should an HHA do instead of assuming what a client wants?\nSuggested Answers\nCulture can include language, religion, family customs, gender, sexual orientation, age, disability, education, work history, and personal experience.\nHealth care has shared habits and values, such as schedules, written instructions, technology, and certain ways of making decisions.\nThe HHA should ask respectful questions, listen carefully, follow the care plan, and report important preferences to the supervisor.\nRemember\n\nCulture is part of care because care happens to a whole person, not just a diagnosis or task list.\n\nCanvas source: https://hic.instructure.com/courses/287/pages/chc-116-topic-1-what-culture-means-in-health-care?module_item_id=3125"
        },
        {
          "title": "CHC 116 Topic 2: Cultural Competence and Cultural Humility",
          "durationMinutes": 17,
          "content": "CHC 116 Topic 2: Cultural Competence and Cultural Humility\nCHC 116 Topic 2: Cultural Competence and Cultural Humility\nCompetence and Humility\n\nA culturally competent aide learns, asks, respects, and adapts while staying within the care plan and agency rules.\n\nCultural Competence\n\nCultural competence means providing care in a way that fits the client’s beliefs, values, customs, language, and preferences as much as possible. It is a skill that grows with practice. The HHA does not need to know everything about every culture, but the aide must be willing to learn and respond respectfully.\n\nA culturally competent approach includes the client’s strengths and values. For example, a client’s family support, prayer routine, food tradition, or preferred communication style may help the client feel safer and more involved in care.\n\nCultural Humility\n\nCultural humility means recognizing that you do not know everything about another person’s experience. It means staying curious, being willing to apologize when you make a mistake, and allowing the client to teach you what respectful care looks like for them.\n\nHow an HHA Shows Respect\nAsk permission before beginning care tasks.\nUse the client’s preferred name and pronouns.\nExplain what you are doing and why.\nFollow through when you promise something.\nReport preferences, concerns, or misunderstandings to the supervisor.\nQuick Learner Check\nWhat is cultural competence?\nWhat is cultural humility?\nWhy is follow-through important when building trust?\nSuggested Answers\nIt is providing care in a way that respects the client’s beliefs, values, customs, language, and preferences while following the care plan.\nIt is recognizing that you do not know everything about another person and staying open, respectful, and willing to learn.\nWhen an aide keeps promises and is consistent, the client learns that the aide is dependable and safe to trust.\nRemember\n\nYou do not have to be perfect to be respectful. You do need to be honest, willing to learn, and careful with the client’s dignity.\n\nCanvas source: https://hic.instructure.com/courses/287/pages/chc-116-topic-2-cultural-competence-and-cultural-humility?module_item_id=3126"
        },
        {
          "title": "CHC 116 Topic 3: Health Beliefs and Healing Practices",
          "durationMinutes": 17,
          "content": "CHC 116 Topic 3: Health Beliefs and Healing Practices\nCHC 116 Topic 3: Health Beliefs and Healing Practices\nHealth Beliefs and Healing Practices\n\nClients may have different beliefs about what causes illness, what healing means, and which treatments feel acceptable.\n\nDifferent Ways People Understand Illness\n\nSome clients may see illness mainly as a medical problem. Others may connect illness with spiritual concerns, imbalance, punishment, stress, family history, diet, weather, or other beliefs. These beliefs can affect whether a client accepts medicine, diet changes, bathing routines, therapy, or outside help.\n\nSome clients use folk or traditional healing practices along with Western medicine. The HHA should never mock these practices. The aide also should not give medical advice or approve treatments. Instead, listen respectfully and report information to the supervisor when it may affect the care plan or safety.\n\nWhen Beliefs and the Care Plan Differ\n\nA client may refuse a task or request something different because of personal or cultural beliefs. Stay calm. Explain the task simply, ask what concerns the client has, and report refusals or concerns to the supervisor. The goal is to protect safety without taking away dignity.\n\nHelpful Questions\n“What do you think is causing this problem?”\n“What helps you feel better when you are sick?”\n“Are there any practices or routines I should know about before I help you?”\n“Would you like me to report this preference to the nurse or supervisor?”\nQuick Learner Check\nShould an HHA laugh at or criticize a client’s traditional healing practice?\nWhat should the aide do if a belief may affect safety or the care plan?\nWhy are open-ended questions useful?\nSuggested Answers\nNo. The aide should be respectful, even when the practice is unfamiliar.\nThe aide should listen, avoid giving medical advice, follow agency policy, and report the concern to the supervisor.\nThey allow the client to explain their own beliefs and preferences instead of forcing a yes-or-no answer.\nRemember\n\nRespect does not mean the HHA makes medical decisions. Respect means listening carefully and reporting important information through the proper chain of command.\n\nCanvas source: https://hic.instructure.com/courses/287/pages/chc-116-topic-3-health-beliefs-and-healing-practices?module_item_id=3127"
        },
        {
          "title": "CHC 116 Topic 4: Respectful Communication and Forms of Address",
          "durationMinutes": 17,
          "content": "CHC 116 Topic 4: Respectful Communication and Forms of Address\nCHC 116 Topic 4: Respectful Communication and Forms of Address\nRespectful Communication\n\nRespectful communication begins with how you speak to the client, how you listen, and how you ask what the client prefers.\n\nNames and Titles Matter\n\nIn some families and cultures, using a first name may feel friendly. In others, it may feel rude or too familiar, especially when speaking to an older adult. The safest practice is to ask the client how they would like to be addressed.\n\nExamples include “Mrs. Lee,” “Mr. Johnson,” “Ms. Rivera,” a preferred first name, a nickname, or another respectful title. Once the client tells you their preference, use it consistently.\n\nTone and Pace\n\nSpeak clearly, calmly, and respectfully. Some clients may speak softly or slowly because that is their communication style, not because they lack confidence or understanding. Other clients may be direct and expressive. Do not judge the client’s tone through your own cultural expectations only.\n\nRespectful Phrases\n“How would you like me to address you?”\n“I want to make sure I understood you correctly.”\n“Is this a good time to begin?”\n“Would you like privacy before we continue?”\n“Thank you for telling me. I will report that to my supervisor.”\nQuick Learner Check\nWhat is the safest way to know what name or title to use?\nWhat should an aide do if they are not sure they understood the client?\nWhy should the aide avoid judging a client’s tone too quickly?\nSuggested Answers\nAsk the client how they would like to be addressed.\nThe aide should repeat back the message respectfully and ask for clarification.\nTone, pace, and expression can be influenced by culture, health, stress, language, or personality.\nRemember\n\nRespectful words are part of patient care. The way you speak can help the client feel safe or make the client feel ignored.\n\nCanvas source: https://hic.instructure.com/courses/287/pages/chc-116-topic-4-respectful-communication-and-forms-of-address?module_item_id=3128"
        },
        {
          "title": "CHC 116 Topic 5: Nonverbal Communication, Gestures, and Eye Contact",
          "durationMinutes": 17,
          "content": "CHC 116 Topic 5: Nonverbal Communication, Gestures, and Eye Contact\nCHC 116 Topic 5: Nonverbal Communication, Gestures, and Eye Contact\nNonverbal Communication\n\nBody language can support trust, but gestures and eye contact do not mean the same thing in every culture.\n\nWhat Nonverbal Communication Includes\n\nNonverbal communication includes facial expression, posture, eye contact, gestures, touch, distance, and movement. Clients may notice your body language even before they respond to your words.\n\nA smile, relaxed posture, and calm movements can help a client feel safe. However, some gestures that feel harmless to one person can be offensive or confusing to another person. Eye contact can also mean different things. In some cultures, steady eye contact shows respect. In others, looking down may show respect, privacy, or modesty.\n\nWhen a Mistake Happens\n\nIf a gesture, facial expression, or movement seems to offend or confuse the client, apologize respectfully. You can say, “I am sorry. I did not mean to be disrespectful. Please tell me what you prefer.” Then adjust your behavior and, if needed, report the concern to your supervisor.\n\nGood HHA Habits\nMove calmly and avoid rushing the client.\nKeep your facial expression professional and kind.\nDo not assume lack of eye contact means dishonesty or disinterest.\nAvoid unfamiliar gestures when clear words would be better.\nAsk what the client prefers when you are unsure.\nQuick Learner Check\nDoes eye contact mean the same thing to every client?\nWhat should an aide do if a gesture seems to offend a client?\nName one example of nonverbal communication.\nSuggested Answers\nNo. Eye contact can mean respect in one culture and disrespect or discomfort in another.\nThe aide should apologize, ask what the client prefers, adjust behavior, and report concerns if needed.\nExamples include facial expression, posture, gestures, touch, personal space, eye contact, and movement.\nRemember\n\nYour body language speaks. Make sure it says respect, patience, and safety.\n\nCanvas source: https://hic.instructure.com/courses/287/pages/chc-116-topic-5-nonverbal-communication-gestures-and-eye-contact?module_item_id=3129"
        },
        {
          "title": "CHC 116 Topic 6: Language, Literacy, and Professional Interpreters",
          "durationMinutes": 17,
          "content": "CHC 116 Topic 6: Language, Literacy, and Professional Interpreters\nCHC 116 Topic 6: Language, Literacy, and Professional Interpreters\nLanguage and Understanding\n\nSafe care requires clear understanding. Language barriers and reading difficulties must be handled with patience and professionalism.\n\nLanguage Barriers\n\nA client may speak a different language, have limited English, use sign language, or have difficulty finding words because of illness or disability. Speak slowly, use simple words, and allow extra time. Do not shout unless the client has asked you to speak louder.\n\nWhen important information must be shared, follow agency policy for interpreter services. Professional interpreters are preferred when available because family members may not know medical terms, may leave out information, or may be involved in private family matters.\n\nLiteracy and Written Instructions\n\nDo not assume the client can read written directions, medication labels, appointment papers, or diet information. A client may be embarrassed to say they cannot read well. Offer help respectfully and use plain language. If instructions are unclear or the client seems confused, report the concern.\n\nRespectful Communication Tools\nUse short, clear sentences.\nAsk the client to explain instructions back in their own words when appropriate.\nUse approved communication boards, hearing aids, glasses, or written notes when helpful.\nUse interpreter services according to agency policy.\nProtect privacy when language assistance is needed.\nQuick Learner Check\nWhy are professional interpreters preferred for important information?\nShould an aide assume a client can read written instructions?\nWhat can an aide do if the client seems confused?\nSuggested Answers\nThey are trained to interpret accurately and protect privacy. Family members may not know medical terms or may change the message.\nNo. The aide should use plain language and check understanding respectfully.\nThe aide can repeat information, use simple words, ask for clarification, and report concerns to the supervisor.\nRemember\n\nClear communication is a safety skill. Understanding matters more than simply saying the words.\n\nCanvas source: https://hic.instructure.com/courses/287/pages/chc-116-topic-6-language-literacy-and-professional-interpreters?module_item_id=3130"
        },
        {
          "title": "CHC 116 Topic 7: Personal Space, Touch, Modesty, and Bathing",
          "durationMinutes": 17,
          "content": "CHC 116 Topic 7: Personal Space, Touch, Modesty, and Bathing\nCHC 116 Topic 7: Personal Space, Touch, Modesty, and Bathing\nPersonal Space and Touch\n\nPatient care skills often involve closeness and touch, so the HHA must protect privacy, modesty, and client choice.\n\nPersonal Space\n\nPeople differ in how close they feel comfortable standing or sitting. Illness, pain, trauma, disability, culture, and personal history can all affect personal space. Watch the client’s body language and ask permission before moving closer.\n\nTouch can also have different meanings. Some clients may welcome a hand on the shoulder. Others may feel uncomfortable or may have religious or cultural rules about touch, gender, or modesty. Always explain what you are about to do before touching the client.\n\nBathing and Personal Care\n\nBathing, dressing, toileting, grooming, and skin care are private tasks. The HHA should provide only the help needed, cover the client when possible, close doors or curtains, and encourage the client to do as much as they safely can.\n\nA respectful question can reduce embarrassment. For example: “How would you like me to proceed with helping you bathe?” or “Would you like to wash this area yourself?”\n\nProtecting Dignity\nKnock before entering private spaces.\nAsk permission before touching or moving clothing or covers.\nExplain each step before you do it.\nKeep the client covered as much as possible.\nReport refusal, discomfort, pain, or safety concerns.\nQuick Learner Check\nWhy should the aide ask before touching the client?\nName one way to protect modesty during bathing.\nWhat should the aide do if the client refuses care?\nSuggested Answers\nTouch may feel private, uncomfortable, painful, or culturally sensitive. Asking protects dignity and trust.\nClose the door or curtain, keep the client covered, explain each step, and allow the client to do as much as possible.\nStay calm, do not force the task, document or report according to policy, and notify the supervisor.\nRemember\n\nPersonal care is never “just a task.” It is a moment where the client’s dignity must be carefully protected.\n\nCanvas source: https://hic.instructure.com/courses/287/pages/chc-116-topic-7-personal-space-touch-modesty-and-bathing?module_item_id=3131"
        },
        {
          "title": "CHC 116 Topic 8: Time, Food, Family, and Decision-Making",
          "durationMinutes": 17,
          "content": "CHC 116 Topic 8: Time, Food, Family, and Decision-Making\nCHC 116 Topic 8: Time, Food, Family, and Decision-Making\nDaily Life and Decision-Making\n\nCulture can influence schedules, meals, family roles, privacy, support systems, and who the client wants involved in care.\n\nTime and Relationship-Building\n\nSome clients may expect tasks to happen at an exact time. Others may place more importance on greeting, conversation, prayer, or asking about family before beginning care. The HHA still follows the assignment and schedule, but respectful relationship-building can make care easier and more comfortable.\n\nFood Preferences and Taboos\n\nFood is closely connected to culture, religion, health, memory, and comfort. A client may avoid certain foods, fast on certain days, or prefer traditional foods. Do not criticize unfamiliar foods. If diet instructions conflict with preferences, report the concern so the care team can help find safe options.\n\nFamily and Decision-Making\n\nSome clients make health decisions privately. Others want family, a spiritual leader, a partner, or a trusted friend involved. Respect the client’s choice and privacy. Sexual orientation, family structure, and chosen support people must be treated with dignity. The aide should not decide who “counts” as family; follow the client’s wishes and agency policy.\n\nAsk who the client wants included in conversations, and share information only with people who are allowed to know it.\n\nQuick Learner Check\nWhat should an aide do if a client’s food preference conflicts with the care plan?\nWho decides which support people should be involved when possible?\nWhy should an aide avoid criticizing unfamiliar foods?\nSuggested Answers\nThe aide should respect the preference, avoid giving diet advice beyond the care plan, and report the concern to the supervisor.\nThe client decides whenever possible, and the aide follows agency policy and privacy rules.\nFood may be connected to culture, religion, comfort, and identity. Criticism can damage trust and dignity.\nRemember\n\nRespecting the client’s daily life includes meals, relationships, routines, privacy, and chosen support people.\n\nCanvas source: https://hic.instructure.com/courses/287/pages/chc-116-topic-8-time-food-family-and-decision-making?module_item_id=3132"
        },
        {
          "title": "CHC 116 Topic 9: Self-Awareness, Bias, and Cultural Assessment",
          "durationMinutes": 17,
          "content": "CHC 116 Topic 9: Self-Awareness, Bias, and Cultural Assessment\nCHC 116 Topic 9: Self-Awareness, Bias, and Cultural Assessment\nSelf-Awareness and Assessment\n\nAn HHA must understand personal bias and use respectful questions to learn about the client without stereotyping.\n\nKnow Your Own Lens\n\nEveryone has a culture and personal beliefs. Self-awareness means noticing your own habits, values, fears, and assumptions. You may have strong feelings about food, language, hygiene, family roles, time, religion, medicine, or personal choices. These feelings must not interfere with respectful care.\n\nBias can show up as impatience, judgment, joking, avoiding a client, assuming a client is difficult, or thinking “my way is normal and theirs is wrong.” Stereotyping means assuming all people from a group are the same. A professional HHA avoids stereotypes and responds to the individual client.\n\nQuestions for Self-Reflection\nWhat culture or communities shaped me?\nWho do I go to when I am sick?\nAre there foods, medicines, or care practices I avoid?\nDo accents or language differences make me impatient?\nDo I assume everyone should communicate the way I do?\nWhat do I need to learn so I can give better care?\nCultural Assessment Questions\n\nA cultural assessment is a respectful way to learn what matters to the client. The HHA may ask simple questions within the role and report important information to the supervisor.\n\n“What language do you prefer for health information?”\n“Are there foods you prefer or avoid?”\n“Are there religious or spiritual practices I should respect during care?”\n“Who do you want involved in care decisions?”\n“Is there anything about your culture or beliefs I should know to provide better care?”\nQuick Learner Check\nWhat is bias?\nWhat is stereotyping?\nWhy is self-awareness important for an HHA?\nSuggested Answers\nBias is a personal attitude or assumption that can affect how someone treats another person.\nStereotyping is assuming all people from a group are the same.\nSelf-awareness helps the aide notice personal assumptions and provide respectful care based on the individual client.\nRemember\n\nThe goal is not to be culture-free. The goal is to notice your own assumptions so they do not harm the client.\n\nCanvas source: https://hic.instructure.com/courses/287/pages/chc-116-topic-9-self-awareness-bias-and-cultural-assessment?module_item_id=3133"
        },
        {
          "title": "CHC 116 Topic 10: Historical Trauma, Trust, and the Platinum Rule",
          "durationMinutes": 17,
          "content": "CHC 116 Topic 10: Historical Trauma, Trust, and the Platinum Rule\nCHC 116 Topic 10: Historical Trauma, Trust, and the Platinum Rule\nTrust and the Platinum Rule\n\nSome clients may carry mistrust because of real historical harm. Trust grows when the aide is clear, respectful, consistent, and reliable.\n\nHistorical Trauma and Health Care Trust\n\nA client’s mistrust of health care may come from personal experience, family stories, discrimination, or historical events. Examples include segregation and Jim Crow laws, forced removal or confinement of groups, and other experiences where people were treated unfairly by systems in power.\n\nOne well-known example is the Tuskegee syphilis study, which took place from 1932 to 1972 in Macon County, Alabama. Low-income rural Black men were told they were being treated for “bad blood,” but men who had syphilis were not given proper treatment while researchers observed the effects of the disease. This history is one reason some African American clients and families may feel distrust toward health care systems.\n\nThe HHA should not take mistrust personally or argue with it. Instead, the aide should be honest about the purpose of each task, ask permission, answer questions within the HHA role, report concerns, and follow through on promises.\n\nBuilding Trust in Daily Care\nBe clear about why you are there and what care you will provide.\nAsk, “Is that all right with you?” before beginning personal care.\nInvite questions and listen without rushing.\nBe consistent with time, words, and actions.\nFollow through when you promise to do something.\nRespect that some health risks and screening needs may vary among populations, but never stereotype or diagnose a client.\nThe Platinum Rule\n\nMany people know the Golden Rule: treat others the way you want to be treated. In culturally competent care, the Platinum Rule is even better: treat people the way they want to be treated. This means asking, listening, and adapting respectfully within the care plan.\n\nQuick Learner Check\nWhy might some clients distrust health care systems?\nWhat are two ways an HHA can build trust?\nWhat is the Platinum Rule?\nSuggested Answers\nMistrust may come from personal experience, discrimination, family history, or historical harms such as the Tuskegee syphilis study.\nThe HHA can explain the purpose of care, ask permission, answer questions within the role, be consistent, and follow through on promises.\nTreat people the way they want to be treated, while staying within the care plan and agency policy.\nRemember\n\nTrust is built in small actions: tell the truth, ask permission, keep promises, and treat the client the way they want to be treated.\n\nCanvas source: https://hic.instructure.com/courses/287/pages/chc-116-topic-10-historical-trauma-trust-and-the-platinum-rule?module_item_id=3134"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "CHC 117 - Death and Dying (2 hours)",
      "lessons": [
        {
          "title": "CHC 117: Death and Dying Overview",
          "durationMinutes": 17,
          "content": "CHC 117: Death and Dying Overview\nCHC 117: Death and Dying Overview\nProviding Dignity, Comfort, and Respect\n\nEnd-of-life care focuses on comfort, dignity, privacy, and support. The HHA helps the client and family by following the care plan, observing changes, and providing calm compassionate care.\n\nLesson Objectives\nExplain the HHA role in end-of-life care.\nDescribe hospice, palliative care, comfort care, and dignity in simple terms.\nRecognize common physical, emotional, cultural, and spiritual needs near the end of life.\nUse respectful communication with clients and families.\nReport changes, concerns, pain, distress, or family needs according to agency policy.\nWhy This Module Matters\n\nDeath and dying can be emotional for the client, family, and care team. The HHA may spend important time with the client during this stage. Simple actions such as gentle care, privacy, mouth care, clean linens, quiet presence, and respectful communication can bring comfort.\n\nThe HHA does not diagnose death, make medical decisions, change medications, or discuss prognosis outside the care team plan. The HHA observes, supports, documents, reports, and follows the plan of care.\n\nCore Values\nComfort: reduce discomfort through assigned care tasks and prompt reporting.\nDignity: treat the client as a whole person, not as a task.\nPrivacy: protect personal information and family moments.\nChoice: respect preferences, culture, religion, and routines whenever possible.\nTeamwork: report changes and follow hospice, nurse, or agency instructions.\nQuick Learner Check\nWhat is the HHA role in end-of-life care?\nCan the HHA diagnose death?\nName one core value in death and dying care.\nSuggested Answers\nThe HHA follows the care plan, provides assigned comfort care, observes changes, documents facts, reports concerns, and supports dignity and privacy.\nNo. The HHA does not diagnose death or make medical decisions. Follow agency policy and notify the proper supervisor or nurse.\nExamples include comfort, dignity, privacy, choice, respect, and teamwork.\nRemember\n\nEnd-of-life care is still active care. Comfort, dignity, and presence matter.\n\nSources for Instructor Review\nNational Institute on Aging: Providing Care and Comfort at the End of Life\nLinks to an external site.\nMedlinePlus: End of Life Issues\nLinks to an external site.\nNational Institute on Aging: Palliative Care and Hospice Care\nLinks to an external site.\nHospice Foundation of America: Signs of Approaching Death\nLinks to an external site.\n\nCanvas source: https://hic.instructure.com/courses/287/pages/chc-117-death-and-dying-overview?module_item_id=3154"
        },
        {
          "title": "CHC 117 Topic 1: Understanding End-of-Life Care",
          "durationMinutes": 17,
          "content": "CHC 117 Topic 1: Understanding End-of-Life Care\nCHC 117 Topic 1: Understanding End-of-Life Care\nUnderstanding End-of-Life Care\n\nEnd-of-life care supports comfort and quality of life when a person is seriously ill, declining, or nearing death.\n\nKey Terms\n\nPalliative care focuses on relief from symptoms, stress, and discomfort during serious illness. It can be provided at any stage of illness and may be given along with treatment.\n\nHospice care focuses on comfort and quality of life when curative treatment is no longer the goal or when a person is expected to be near the end of life. Hospice care often supports both the client and family.\n\nComfort care means care aimed at easing discomfort and supporting dignity. It may include mouth care, repositioning, skin care, calm surroundings, privacy, and reporting symptoms to the nurse.\n\nWhat Quality of Life Means\n\nQuality of life is personal. For one client it may mean being free from pain. For another it may mean prayer, music, family presence, favorite routines, or being clean and comfortable. Ask what matters when it is appropriate and follow the care plan.\n\nHHA Boundaries\nDo not explain prognosis unless directed by the nurse or care team.\nDo not change medications, oxygen, treatments, or equipment settings unless assigned and trained.\nDo not promise what will happen next.\nDo report pain, distress, breathing changes, skin problems, agitation, family concerns, or client requests.\nQuick Learner Check\nWhat is palliative care?\nWhat does comfort care focus on?\nShould the HHA explain how long a client has to live?\nSuggested Answers\nPalliative care focuses on relief from symptoms, stress, and discomfort during serious illness.\nComfort care focuses on easing discomfort, protecting dignity, and supporting quality of life.\nNo. Prognosis questions should be referred to the nurse, hospice team, provider, or supervisor according to policy.\nRemember\n\nWhen unsure what to say, use simple honesty: “I will let the nurse know your question.”\n\nCanvas source: https://hic.instructure.com/courses/287/pages/chc-117-topic-1-understanding-end-of-life-care?module_item_id=3155"
        },
        {
          "title": "CHC 117 Topic 2: Emotional Responses to Dying",
          "durationMinutes": 17,
          "content": "CHC 117 Topic 2: Emotional Responses to Dying\nCHC 117 Topic 2: Emotional Responses to Dying\nEmotional Responses to Dying\n\nClients and families may experience fear, sadness, anger, denial, relief, guilt, confusion, or acceptance. There is no single correct way to grieve.\n\nCommon Feelings\n\nDying can bring many emotions. A client may want to talk, or may want quiet. A family member may cry, ask repeated questions, become angry, or seem numb. These responses do not always mean something is wrong; they may be part of coping with loss.\n\nSome people describe stages of grief, such as denial, anger, bargaining, depression, and acceptance. These stages do not happen in a perfect order, and not everyone experiences all of them. Avoid forcing a person into a “stage.”\n\nHow the HHA Can Respond\nListen without interrupting or rushing.\nUse calm statements such as, “I am here with you,” or “I can tell this is very hard.”\nAllow silence when the client or family does not want to talk.\nAvoid judgment about how someone grieves.\nReport signs of severe distress, safety concerns, or requests for spiritual or emotional support.\nWhat Not to Say\nAvoid “I know exactly how you feel.”\nAvoid “Everything happens for a reason.”\nAvoid “You need to be strong.”\nAvoid arguing with anger or correcting every emotional statement.\nQuick Learner Check\nDo all people grieve the same way?\nName one supportive statement an HHA can use.\nWhy should the aide avoid saying “I know exactly how you feel”?\nSuggested Answers\nNo. Grief is personal and may include many different emotions in different orders.\nExamples include “I am here with you,” “I can tell this is hard,” or “Would you like me to sit quietly with you?”\nBecause every person’s experience is different, and the statement may feel dismissive even if meant kindly.\nRemember\n\nYou do not have to fix grief. Calm presence and respectful listening are powerful.\n\nCanvas source: https://hic.instructure.com/courses/287/pages/chc-117-topic-2-emotional-responses-to-dying?module_item_id=3156"
        },
        {
          "title": "CHC 117 Topic 3: Communication with Clients and Families",
          "durationMinutes": 17,
          "content": "CHC 117 Topic 3: Communication with Clients and Families\nCHC 117 Topic 3: Communication with Clients and Families\nCommunication Near the End of Life\n\nEnd-of-life communication should be honest, gentle, respectful, and within the HHA role.\n\nRespectful Communication\n\nSpeak to the client even if they are very weak, sleepy, confused, or not responding. Hearing may remain meaningful even when a person cannot answer. Explain care before touching or moving the client.\n\nUse the client’s preferred name, protect privacy, and include the family only as allowed by the care plan and privacy rules. Some clients want family involved in all decisions; others want quiet or privacy.\n\nHelpful Phrases\n“I am going to help reposition you now.”\n“Would you like the room quieter or the light dimmed?”\n“I hear that you are worried. I will report this to the nurse.”\n“I cannot answer that medical question, but I can contact the nurse.”\n“Would you like a few minutes of privacy with your family?”\nFamily Communication\n\nFamilies may ask the HHA medical questions. Stay kind and clear about your role. Do not guess. Report questions to the nurse, hospice team, or supervisor. If family conflict occurs, stay calm and notify the supervisor.\n\nQuick Learner Check\nShould the HHA speak to an unresponsive client during care?\nWhat should the HHA do when asked a medical question outside the role?\nName one way to protect privacy.\nSuggested Answers\nYes. Speak respectfully, explain care, and assume the client deserves dignity even if they cannot respond.\nThe HHA should say they cannot answer that medical question and report it to the nurse or supervisor.\nClose doors or curtains, cover the client during care, use private voice, and share information only with approved people.\nRemember\n\nGentle communication protects dignity, even when the client cannot speak back.\n\nCanvas source: https://hic.instructure.com/courses/287/pages/chc-117-topic-3-communication-with-clients-and-families?module_item_id=3157"
        },
        {
          "title": "CHC 117 Topic 4: Comfort Care and Basic Needs",
          "durationMinutes": 17,
          "content": "CHC 117 Topic 4: Comfort Care and Basic Needs\nCHC 117 Topic 4: Comfort Care and Basic Needs\nComfort Care and Basic Needs\n\nComfort care includes simple, careful actions that reduce distress and support dignity.\n\nCommon Comfort Measures\nReposition the client as instructed to reduce pressure and discomfort.\nProvide mouth care and lip moisture according to the care plan.\nKeep skin clean, dry, and protected.\nChange linens and clothing gently when needed.\nKeep the room calm, clean, and at a comfortable temperature.\nReduce noise, bright lights, or unnecessary interruptions when possible.\nOffer emotional presence and privacy.\nPain and Distress\n\nThe HHA does not decide medication needs, but the HHA must report pain or distress. Watch for facial grimacing, moaning, restlessness, tense body posture, guarding, crying, agitation, or changes in breathing. Report what you see and what the client or family says.\n\nFood and Fluids\n\nNear the end of life, appetite and thirst often change. Do not force food or fluids. Follow the care plan and nurse instructions. Provide mouth care as assigned and report family concerns or signs of choking, coughing, or swallowing difficulty.\n\nQuick Learner Check\nName two comfort measures an HHA may provide if assigned.\nShould the HHA force food or fluids near the end of life?\nWhat should the HHA report about pain?\nSuggested Answers\nExamples include repositioning, mouth care, skin care, clean linens, calm environment, privacy, and reporting discomfort.\nNo. Follow the care plan and nurse instructions. Report concerns about appetite, swallowing, coughing, or dehydration.\nReport the client’s statements and objective signs such as grimacing, moaning, restlessness, guarding, crying, agitation, or breathing changes.\nRemember\n\nComfort care is made of small details done with patience and respect.\n\nCanvas source: https://hic.instructure.com/courses/287/pages/chc-117-topic-4-comfort-care-and-basic-needs?module_item_id=3158"
        },
        {
          "title": "CHC 117 Topic 5: Physical Changes Near Death",
          "durationMinutes": 17,
          "content": "CHC 117 Topic 5: Physical Changes Near Death\nCHC 117 Topic 5: Physical Changes Near Death\nPhysical Changes Near Death\n\nCertain physical changes may happen as the body slows down. The HHA observes and reports, while the nurse or hospice team guides care.\n\nPossible Changes\n\nEvery person is different, but common changes near death may include increased sleep, weakness, less interest in food or fluids, cool hands or feet, changes in skin color, irregular breathing, restlessness, confusion, decreased urine, or changes in responsiveness.\n\nSome breathing sounds can occur when secretions collect and the client is too weak to clear them. This can be distressing for family members. The HHA should report changes and follow nurse or hospice instructions.\n\nWhat to Report Promptly\nNew or worsening pain or distress.\nBreathing changes, choking, coughing, or noisy breathing that concerns the family.\nRestlessness, agitation, confusion, or sudden change in responsiveness.\nSkin breakdown, bleeding, fever, falls, or injury.\nFamily questions, panic, conflict, or requests for a nurse or spiritual support.\nStay Within Scope\n\nThe HHA does not declare death. If the client appears to have stopped breathing or has no response, follow agency policy immediately. This may include notifying the nurse, hospice, supervisor, or emergency services depending on the care plan and setting.\n\nQuick Learner Check\nName two physical changes that may happen near death.\nCan the HHA declare that a client has died?\nWhat should the HHA do when family members are frightened by breathing changes?\nSuggested Answers\nExamples include increased sleep, weakness, decreased appetite, cool hands or feet, skin color changes, irregular breathing, restlessness, confusion, decreased urine, or decreased responsiveness.\nNo. The HHA follows agency policy and contacts the appropriate nurse, hospice team, supervisor, or emergency service.\nStay calm, report the change promptly, and follow nurse or hospice instructions.\nRemember\n\nObserve, comfort, report. Do not guess or diagnose.\n\nCanvas source: https://hic.instructure.com/courses/287/pages/chc-117-topic-5-physical-changes-near-death?module_item_id=3159"
        },
        {
          "title": "CHC 117 Topic 6: Cultural and Spiritual Considerations",
          "durationMinutes": 17,
          "content": "CHC 117 Topic 6: Cultural and Spiritual Considerations\nCHC 117 Topic 6: Cultural and Spiritual Considerations\nCulture, Spirituality, and Personal Wishes\n\nBeliefs about death, family roles, prayer, touch, modesty, the body, and mourning can vary widely. Respect starts with asking and listening.\n\nRespecting Differences\n\nDeath and dying practices may be shaped by religion, culture, family tradition, personal values, military experience, trauma history, or individual preference. Some clients want prayer, music, rituals, clergy, family presence, or quiet. Others may not want spiritual discussion at all.\n\nDo not assume what a client believes based on appearance, language, age, or background. Ask respectful questions when appropriate and report preferences to the supervisor.\n\nHelpful Questions\n“Are there any spiritual or cultural practices we should respect during care?”\n“Would you like privacy or family present right now?”\n“Is there someone you would like us to contact?”\n“How would you like me to provide care in a way that feels respectful?”\nAfter Death Customs\n\nSome families have important practices about touching, washing, positioning, covering, praying over, or remaining with the body after death. The HHA should follow agency policy and supervisor instructions while showing respect for the family’s wishes whenever possible.\n\nQuick Learner Check\nWhy should the HHA avoid assuming a client’s beliefs?\nName one respectful question about cultural or spiritual needs.\nWhat should the HHA do if family customs involve care after death?\nSuggested Answers\nPeople from the same culture or religion may have different personal wishes. The safest approach is to ask respectfully and follow the care plan.\nExample: “Are there any spiritual or cultural practices we should respect during care?”\nFollow agency policy, notify the supervisor or nurse, and respect the family’s wishes when allowed.\nRemember\n\nRespectful care at the end of life includes the client’s beliefs, family, privacy, and personal meaning.\n\nCanvas source: https://hic.instructure.com/courses/287/pages/chc-117-topic-6-cultural-and-spiritual-considerations?module_item_id=3160"
        },
        {
          "title": "CHC 117 Topic 7: Grief, Loss, and Family Support",
          "durationMinutes": 17,
          "content": "CHC 117 Topic 7: Grief, Loss, and Family Support\nCHC 117 Topic 7: Grief, Loss, and Family Support\nGrief, Loss, and Family Support\n\nFamilies and caregivers may grieve before, during, and after death. The HHA offers calm support while staying within role boundaries.\n\nUnderstanding Grief\n\nGrief can begin before death when a family sees the client decline. This is sometimes called anticipatory grief. After death, grief may include sadness, anger, guilt, numbness, relief, confusion, or physical symptoms such as fatigue or poor sleep.\n\nPeople grieve differently. Some cry openly. Some become quiet. Some focus on tasks. Some ask repeated questions. The HHA should avoid judging the family’s response.\n\nSupportive Actions\nOffer quiet presence when appropriate.\nGive the family privacy when requested and safe.\nUse simple, kind words such as, “I am sorry for your loss.”\nReport requests for chaplain, clergy, social worker, counselor, hospice nurse, or supervisor.\nKeep the environment calm and respectful.\nProtect confidentiality.\nBoundaries\n\nThe HHA should not provide counseling, make promises, share personal religious beliefs unless invited and appropriate, or become the family’s only support. Refer needs through the proper care team channel.\n\nQuick Learner Check\nWhat is anticipatory grief?\nName one supportive action for family members.\nWhy are boundaries important when supporting grief?\nSuggested Answers\nAnticipatory grief is grief that begins before death as the person declines or the family expects a loss.\nExamples include quiet presence, privacy, kind words, calm environment, and reporting requests for spiritual or emotional support.\nBoundaries protect the client, family, and aide. The HHA supports but does not provide counseling or replace the care team.\nRemember\n\nSimple kindness matters. You do not need perfect words to be respectful.\n\nCanvas source: https://hic.instructure.com/courses/287/pages/chc-117-topic-7-grief-loss-and-family-support?module_item_id=3161"
        },
        {
          "title": "CHC 117 Topic 8: After Death Care and HHA Responsibilities",
          "durationMinutes": 17,
          "content": "CHC 117 Topic 8: After Death Care and HHA Responsibilities\nCHC 117 Topic 8: After Death Care and HHA Responsibilities\nAfter Death Care and HHA Responsibilities\n\nAfter death, the HHA follows agency policy exactly. The focus remains dignity, privacy, safety, and respectful communication.\n\nWhen Death Is Suspected\n\nIf a client appears to have stopped breathing, is unresponsive, or has no signs of life, follow agency policy immediately. Depending on the setting and care plan, this may mean calling the nurse, hospice team, supervisor, or 911. The HHA does not pronounce death.\n\nPostmortem Care\n\nPostmortem care means care of the body after death. The HHA may or may not perform this care depending on state rules, agency policy, hospice instructions, and the care plan. If assigned and trained, provide care gently and respectfully, protect privacy, use standard precautions, and honor cultural or spiritual needs when allowed.\n\nImportant Responsibilities\nNotify the correct person according to agency policy.\nDo not move, wash, remove tubes, remove equipment, or change the body unless instructed and authorized.\nProtect the client’s dignity by covering the body respectfully and providing privacy as allowed.\nSupport family with calm presence, but do not give medical or legal explanations.\nDocument objective facts and actions taken according to policy.\nTake care of your own emotional response and seek supervisor support if needed.\nQuick Learner Check\nCan the HHA pronounce death?\nWhat is postmortem care?\nShould the HHA remove medical equipment after death without instruction?\nSuggested Answers\nNo. The HHA follows agency policy and notifies the appropriate nurse, hospice team, supervisor, or emergency service.\nPostmortem care is respectful care of the body after death, performed only if the HHA is trained and authorized.\nNo. Do not remove tubes, devices, or equipment unless instructed and authorized by policy and the care team.\nRemember\n\nAfter death, dignity still matters. Follow policy, protect privacy, and ask for direction.\n\nCanvas source: https://hic.instructure.com/courses/287/pages/chc-117-topic-8-after-death-care-and-hha-responsibilities?module_item_id=3162"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "HHA 201 - The Health Aide in the Home Setting (4 hours)",
      "lessons": [
        {
          "title": "HHA 201: The Health Aide in the Home Setting Overview",
          "durationMinutes": 17,
          "content": "HHA 201: The Health Aide in the Home Setting Overview\nHHA 201: The Health Aide in the Home Setting Overview\nThe Health Aide in the Home Setting\n\nHome care is different because care happens in the client’s personal living space. The HHA must balance safety, professionalism, respect, privacy, and independence while following the care plan.\n\nLesson Objectives\nExplain what makes the home setting different from a facility.\nDescribe the HHA role, scope, chain of command, and care plan responsibilities.\nUse professional boundaries and respectful communication in the client’s home.\nProtect client privacy, dignity, rights, and independence.\nRecognize safety, infection control, family, documentation, and reporting responsibilities.\nWhy This Module Matters\n\nThe client’s home is both a care setting and a private personal space. The HHA enters that space as a professional guest. This requires respect for the client’s routines, belongings, culture, family, privacy, and choices while still completing assigned care safely.\n\nIn the home, the aide may work with less direct supervision than in a facility. This makes observation, judgment, communication, and accurate reporting very important. The HHA follows the care plan and uses the chain of command whenever something is unclear or unsafe.\n\nMain Responsibilities\nFollow the written care plan and assignment sheet.\nProvide assigned personal care, household support, and observation.\nEncourage client independence and choice whenever safe.\nMaintain professional boundaries and confidentiality.\nReport changes, concerns, refusals, safety hazards, and emergencies promptly.\nQuick Learner Check\nWhy is home care different from facility care?\nWhat document guides the HHA’s assigned tasks?\nWhat should the HHA do when something is unclear?\nSuggested Answers\nHome care happens in the client’s private living space, so the HHA must respect routines, belongings, privacy, family, culture, and choice while providing safe care.\nThe care plan and assignment sheet guide what the HHA is allowed and expected to do.\nThe HHA should ask the supervisor or follow the chain of command instead of guessing.\nRemember\n\nIn home care, you are both a caregiver and a professional guest. Respect and safety must work together.\n\nSources for Instructor Review\nMedlinePlus: Home Care Services\nLinks to an external site.\nCMS: Home Health Agency Survey and Certification\nLinks to an external site.\nOSHA: Home Healthcare\nLinks to an external site.\nCDC: About Hand Hygiene\nLinks to an external site.\n\nCanvas source: https://hic.instructure.com/courses/287/pages/hha-201-the-health-aide-in-the-home-setting-overview?module_item_id=3175"
        },
        {
          "title": "HHA 201 Topic 1: What Home Care Is",
          "durationMinutes": 17,
          "content": "HHA 201 Topic 1: What Home Care Is\nHHA 201 Topic 1: What Home Care Is\nWhat Home Care Is\n\nHome care helps clients remain safely in their own homes while receiving support with daily needs, health-related tasks, and independence.\n\nHome Care in Simple Terms\n\nHome care is support provided in the client’s place of living. The client may be an older adult, a person with a disability, someone recovering from illness or surgery, or someone who needs help to remain at home safely.\n\nThe home care team may include the client, family members, the HHA, nurse, therapist, case manager, social worker, physician, and agency supervisor. Each person has a role. The HHA’s role is guided by the care plan and agency policy.\n\nWhy Clients Receive Home Care\nTo remain in a familiar environment.\nTo receive help with bathing, dressing, grooming, toileting, meals, mobility, or light housekeeping.\nTo recover after illness, injury, surgery, or hospitalization.\nTo manage disability, weakness, chronic illness, or age-related changes.\nTo support safety, dignity, and independence at home.\nHome Care Is Person-Centered\n\nPerson-centered care means the client is treated as a whole person, not just a list of tasks. The HHA should notice the client’s preferences, strengths, routines, and goals while following the care plan.\n\nQuick Learner Check\nWho may receive home care?\nName one reason a client may need home care.\nWhat does person-centered care mean?\nSuggested Answers\nHome care may serve older adults, people with disabilities, people recovering from illness or surgery, or anyone who needs support to remain safely at home.\nReasons include help with personal care, recovery, mobility, meals, light housekeeping, chronic illness, safety, or independence.\nIt means caring for the client as a whole person with preferences, routines, strengths, dignity, and choices.\nRemember\n\nHome care supports the client’s life at home, not just the completion of tasks.\n\nCanvas source: https://hic.instructure.com/courses/287/pages/hha-201-topic-1-what-home-care-is?module_item_id=3176"
        },
        {
          "title": "HHA 201 Topic 2: The Client Home as the Workplace",
          "durationMinutes": 17,
          "content": "HHA 201 Topic 2: The Client Home as the Workplace\nHHA 201 Topic 2: The Client Home as the Workplace\nThe Client Home as the Workplace\n\nThe client’s home is your workplace, but it is still the client’s private space. Respect is essential.\n\nA Professional Guest\n\nWhen entering the home, the HHA should act as a professional guest. Knock or announce yourself, greet the client respectfully, ask permission before moving personal items, and leave the home as orderly as possible after assigned tasks.\n\nEvery home is different. Homes may have pets, family members, cultural practices, limited space, clutter, smoking, poor lighting, or equipment. The HHA must adapt professionally while also reporting safety concerns.\n\nRespecting the Home\nDo not use the client’s belongings for personal reasons.\nDo not eat the client’s food unless agency policy and the client clearly allow it.\nDo not invite visitors to the client’s home.\nDo not take photos or videos in the home unless specifically required and authorized by policy.\nDo not judge the client’s home, culture, finances, family, or lifestyle.\nKeep pathways safe when performing assigned tasks.\nWhen the Home Is Unsafe\n\nIf the home has hazards such as blocked exits, aggressive behavior, unsafe equipment, pests, no food, no running water, exposed wires, or dangerous clutter, report the concern according to agency policy. If there is immediate danger, follow emergency procedures.\n\nQuick Learner Check\nWhy is the HHA called a professional guest?\nName one respectful behavior in the client’s home.\nWhat should the HHA do if the home is unsafe?\nSuggested Answers\nBecause the HHA is working in the client’s private living space and must provide professional care while respecting the home.\nExamples include knocking, greeting respectfully, asking before moving items, protecting privacy, and not using belongings for personal reasons.\nReport the hazard according to agency policy and follow emergency procedures if there is immediate danger.\nRemember\n\nThe home may be your workplace for the visit, but it belongs to the client.\n\nCanvas source: https://hic.instructure.com/courses/287/pages/hha-201-topic-2-the-client-home-as-the-workplace?module_item_id=3177"
        },
        {
          "title": "HHA 201 Topic 3: HHA Role, Scope, and Chain of Command",
          "durationMinutes": 17,
          "content": "HHA 201 Topic 3: HHA Role, Scope, and Chain of Command\nHHA 201 Topic 3: HHA Role, Scope, and Chain of Command\nRole, Scope, and Chain of Command\n\nThe HHA provides assigned care, observes the client, and reports concerns. The aide does not make medical decisions or work outside the care plan.\n\nHHA Role\n\nThe HHA may help with personal care, mobility, meals, light housekeeping, observation, reminders, safety, and companionship depending on the care plan. The HHA is often the eyes and ears of the care team because the aide may notice daily changes first.\n\nScope of Practice\nDo only tasks you are trained, assigned, and allowed to perform.\nDo not diagnose medical problems.\nDo not change medications, treatments, diets, oxygen, exercises, or equipment settings unless authorized and trained.\nDo not perform tasks that are not on the assignment or care plan without direction.\nReport refusals, changes, concerns, and unsafe requests.\nChain of Command\n\nThe chain of command tells who gives instructions and who the HHA reports to. This may include a supervisor, nurse, case manager, scheduler, or agency contact. Using the chain of command protects the client, aide, and agency.\n\nQuick Learner Check\nWhy is the HHA sometimes called the eyes and ears of the care team?\nWhat does scope of practice mean?\nWhy is the chain of command important?\nSuggested Answers\nBecause the HHA may spend regular time with the client and notice changes in condition, mood, function, safety, or home environment.\nScope of practice means the tasks the HHA is trained, assigned, and legally/agency-approved to perform.\nIt tells the aide who to report to and helps ensure safe, organized care.\nRemember\n\nIf a task is not trained, assigned, and allowed, stop and ask before doing it.\n\nCanvas source: https://hic.instructure.com/courses/287/pages/hha-201-topic-3-hha-role-scope-and-chain-of-command?module_item_id=3178"
        },
        {
          "title": "HHA 201 Topic 4: The Care Plan and Assignment Sheet",
          "durationMinutes": 17,
          "content": "HHA 201 Topic 4: The Care Plan and Assignment Sheet\nHHA 201 Topic 4: The Care Plan and Assignment Sheet\nThe Care Plan and Assignment Sheet\n\nThe care plan tells the HHA what care to provide, how to provide it, and what special precautions to follow.\n\nWhat the Care Plan Includes\nClient care needs and goals.\nAssigned personal care tasks.\nMobility, transfer, equipment, or fall precautions.\nDiet, fluid, swallowing, or meal instructions.\nInfection control or safety precautions.\nSchedule, frequency, and documentation requirements.\nWhat changes or concerns must be reported.\nWhy It Matters\n\nThe care plan is not optional. It protects the client by making sure care is consistent and based on the care team’s instructions. It protects the aide by clearly showing what tasks are assigned.\n\nIf the client or family asks for something outside the plan, respond respectfully. Explain that you must follow the care plan and report the request to your supervisor.\n\nWhen to Ask for Clarification\nThe assignment is missing, unclear, or different from what the client expects.\nThe client refuses care or requests a new task.\nThe client seems weaker, more confused, or unsafe compared with usual.\nEquipment is missing, broken, or not being used correctly.\nYou do not feel trained or safe performing the task.\nQuick Learner Check\nWhat is the purpose of the care plan?\nWhat should the HHA do if the client requests a task outside the care plan?\nName one time the aide should ask for clarification.\nSuggested Answers\nThe care plan guides assigned care and safety precautions so care is consistent and appropriate.\nRespectfully explain that care must follow the plan, then report the request to the supervisor.\nAsk when instructions are unclear, the client refuses, equipment is unsafe, the client condition changes, or the aide does not feel trained or safe.\nRemember\n\nThe care plan is your roadmap. Do not improvise care when safety is involved.\n\nCanvas source: https://hic.instructure.com/courses/287/pages/hha-201-topic-4-the-care-plan-and-assignment-sheet?module_item_id=3179"
        },
        {
          "title": "HHA 201 Topic 5: Professionalism and Boundaries",
          "durationMinutes": 17,
          "content": "HHA 201 Topic 5: Professionalism and Boundaries\nHHA 201 Topic 5: Professionalism and Boundaries\nProfessionalism and Boundaries\n\nProfessional boundaries protect the client, the HHA, and the agency. Kindness is important, but the relationship is still professional.\n\nProfessional Behavior\nArrive on time and follow the schedule.\nDress neatly according to agency policy.\nUse respectful language and tone.\nKeep personal problems out of the visit.\nComplete assigned tasks and document accurately.\nAvoid gossip, arguments, and judgment.\nReport problems promptly.\nBoundary Examples\nDo not borrow or lend money.\nDo not accept large gifts or pressure for gifts.\nDo not share private personal information with the client or family.\nDo not become involved in family conflict.\nDo not provide care outside agency assignment or schedule.\nDo not use the client’s phone, computer, car, or belongings for personal needs.\nFriendly but Professional\n\nIt is normal to care about clients. Professional warmth can help build trust. Boundaries do not mean being cold; they mean keeping the relationship safe, respectful, and focused on the client’s care.\n\nQuick Learner Check\nWhy are professional boundaries important?\nName one boundary the HHA should keep.\nCan the HHA be kind while still being professional?\nSuggested Answers\nBoundaries protect the client, aide, agency, trust, privacy, and safety.\nExamples include not borrowing money, not accepting large gifts, not sharing private personal details, and not working outside the assignment.\nYes. Professional care can be warm and respectful while still keeping safe limits.\nRemember\n\nBoundaries are not rejection. Boundaries are part of safe professional care.\n\nCanvas source: https://hic.instructure.com/courses/287/pages/hha-201-topic-5-professionalism-and-boundaries?module_item_id=3180"
        },
        {
          "title": "HHA 201 Topic 6: Privacy, Confidentiality, and Client Rights at Home",
          "durationMinutes": 17,
          "content": "HHA 201 Topic 6: Privacy, Confidentiality, and Client Rights at Home\nHHA 201 Topic 6: Privacy, Confidentiality, and Client Rights at Home\nPrivacy, Confidentiality, and Rights\n\nThe client has rights in the home, including privacy, dignity, choice, respect, and protection of personal information.\n\nPrivacy in the Home\n\nPrivacy includes the client’s body, belongings, conversations, health information, mail, phone, computer, family matters, and personal routines. The HHA should knock, close doors or curtains during personal care, cover the client, and speak quietly about private information.\n\nConfidentiality\n\nConfidentiality means not sharing client information with people who are not allowed to know it. Do not discuss client details with friends, family, other clients, social media, or visitors. Share information only with the care team according to agency policy.\n\nRights in Home Care\nThe right to be treated with respect and dignity.\nThe right to participate in care choices when possible.\nThe right to privacy and confidentiality.\nThe right to refuse care or ask questions.\nThe right to safe care without abuse, neglect, or exploitation.\nThe right to have preferences and culture respected.\nQuick Learner Check\nWhat does confidentiality mean?\nName one way to protect privacy during personal care.\nCan a client refuse care?\nSuggested Answers\nIt means protecting client information and sharing it only with people allowed by policy and the care plan.\nClose the door or curtain, cover the client, explain care, and speak quietly.\nYes. The HHA should not force care. Report refusals according to agency policy.\nRemember\n\nPrivate information belongs to the client. Protect it in words, actions, and documentation.\n\nCanvas source: https://hic.instructure.com/courses/287/pages/hha-201-topic-6-privacy-confidentiality-and-client-rights-at-home?module_item_id=3181"
        },
        {
          "title": "HHA 201 Topic 7: Communication with the Client, Family, and Care Team",
          "durationMinutes": 17,
          "content": "HHA 201 Topic 7: Communication with the Client, Family, and Care Team\nHHA 201 Topic 7: Communication with the Client, Family, and Care Team\nCommunication in Home Care\n\nClear communication helps the client feel respected and helps the care team respond to changes quickly.\n\nWith the Client\nGreet the client respectfully and use their preferred name.\nExplain what you are doing before care tasks.\nAsk permission before touching, moving items, or entering private areas.\nListen carefully and avoid interrupting.\nUse simple language and check understanding.\nRespect choices when safe and allowed by the care plan.\nWith Family or Other Caregivers\n\nFamily members may be helpful, stressed, protective, confused, or involved in care. Stay professional and calm. Share only information that policy allows. If family requests conflict with the care plan, contact the supervisor rather than arguing.\n\nWith the Care Team\nReport changes promptly and clearly.\nUse objective facts, not guesses.\nAsk questions when instructions are unclear.\nDocument according to agency policy.\nNotify the supervisor about missed visits, late arrivals, refusals, or unsafe conditions.\nQuick Learner Check\nWhy should the HHA explain care before starting?\nWhat should the aide do if a family request conflicts with the care plan?\nWhat kind of information should be reported to the care team?\nSuggested Answers\nIt respects the client, reduces fear, supports cooperation, and protects dignity.\nStay respectful and contact the supervisor for direction.\nReport objective changes in condition, mood, function, safety, refusals, family concerns, missed visits, and unsafe home conditions.\nRemember\n\nGood communication is calm, respectful, timely, and factual.\n\nCanvas source: https://hic.instructure.com/courses/287/pages/hha-201-topic-7-communication-with-the-client-family-and-care-team?module_item_id=3182"
        },
        {
          "title": "HHA 201 Topic 8: Promoting Independence and Client-Directed Care",
          "durationMinutes": 17,
          "content": "HHA 201 Topic 8: Promoting Independence and Client-Directed Care\nHHA 201 Topic 8: Promoting Independence and Client-Directed Care\nPromoting Independence\n\nHome care should support what the client can still do, not take over everything.\n\nWhy Independence Matters\n\nIndependence supports dignity, confidence, strength, routine, and quality of life. Even small choices can help the client feel more in control. A client may need help and still have the right to guide parts of their day.\n\nWays to Support Independence\nAsk what the client would like to do for themselves.\nSet up supplies within reach instead of doing every step.\nGive time for the client to try safe parts of the task.\nOffer choices such as clothing, meal order, grooming routine, or activity timing when allowed.\nUse adaptive equipment listed in the care plan.\nEncourage effort without rushing or shaming.\nClient-Directed Care\n\nClient-directed care means the client has a voice in how care is provided. The HHA still follows the care plan and safety rules, but should respect preferences, routines, culture, and choices whenever possible.\n\nQuick Learner Check\nWhy is independence important?\nName one way to support independence during care.\nDoes client-directed care mean ignoring the care plan?\nSuggested Answers\nIt supports dignity, confidence, strength, routine, control, and quality of life.\nExamples include setting up supplies, offering choices, giving time, using adaptive equipment, and encouraging safe participation.\nNo. The HHA respects choices while still following the care plan and safety rules.\nRemember\n\nDo with the client when possible, not always for the client.\n\nCanvas source: https://hic.instructure.com/courses/287/pages/hha-201-topic-8-promoting-independence-and-client-directed-care?module_item_id=3183"
        },
        {
          "title": "HHA 201 Topic 9: Safety for the HHA in the Home",
          "durationMinutes": 17,
          "content": "HHA 201 Topic 9: Safety for the HHA in the Home\nHHA 201 Topic 9: Safety for the HHA in the Home\nHHA Safety in the Home\n\nThe HHA must protect the client and also protect personal safety while working in different home environments.\n\nCommon Home Care Safety Risks\nClutter, loose rugs, wet floors, poor lighting, or blocked exits.\nAggressive behavior, threatening visitors, weapons, or unsafe neighborhood conditions.\nUncontrolled pets or animal bites.\nUnsafe lifting, awkward spaces, or missing equipment.\nSmoke, strong odors, chemicals, pests, mold, or unsanitary conditions.\nBroken appliances, exposed wires, unsafe oxygen use, or fire hazards.\nSafe Work Habits\nKnow agency policy for entering homes, parking, personal belongings, and emergencies.\nKeep your phone accessible according to policy.\nDo not perform unsafe transfers or lifts without proper help and equipment.\nUse body mechanics and follow transfer instructions.\nLeave and call for help if there is immediate danger.\nReport hazards to the supervisor promptly.\nWhen to Leave or Call for Help\n\nIf you feel unsafe because of violence, threats, weapons, severe intoxication, fire, gas smell, aggressive animals, or another immediate hazard, follow agency policy, leave if safe to do so, and call 911 or the supervisor as appropriate.\n\nQuick Learner Check\nName two safety risks in the home setting.\nShould the HHA perform an unsafe lift alone?\nWhat should the aide do if there is immediate danger?\nSuggested Answers\nExamples include clutter, loose rugs, blocked exits, aggressive behavior, weapons, pets, unsafe equipment, exposed wires, smoke, pests, or fire hazards.\nNo. The HHA should follow the care plan, use proper equipment/help, and contact the supervisor if the task is unsafe.\nLeave if safe, call 911 when needed, and notify the supervisor according to agency policy.\nRemember\n\nYour safety matters. You cannot provide good care if the situation is unsafe.\n\nCanvas source: https://hic.instructure.com/courses/287/pages/hha-201-topic-9-safety-for-the-hha-in-the-home?module_item_id=3184"
        },
        {
          "title": "HHA 201 Topic 10: Infection Control in the Home Setting",
          "durationMinutes": 17,
          "content": "HHA 201 Topic 10: Infection Control in the Home Setting\nHHA 201 Topic 10: Infection Control in the Home Setting\nInfection Control at Home\n\nInfection control protects the client, HHA, family, and community. Clean hands and correct precautions matter in every home.\n\nWhy Infection Control Matters\n\nClients receiving home care may be older, recovering from illness, or living with weakened immune systems. Germs can spread through hands, surfaces, body fluids, food, equipment, linens, and personal care items.\n\nBasic Infection Control Practices\nWash hands or use hand sanitizer according to policy before and after care.\nWear gloves and other PPE when required by the task or care plan.\nClean and disinfect surfaces or equipment as assigned.\nHandle laundry, trash, and body fluids safely.\nDo not work when agency policy says illness symptoms must be reported before visiting.\nFollow isolation or special precautions exactly when listed in the care plan.\nHome Challenges\n\nThe home may not have ideal supplies or space. If soap, water, gloves, trash bags, cleaning supplies, or safe disposal options are missing, report the problem. Do not ignore infection risks because the setting is informal.\n\nQuick Learner Check\nWhat is one of the most important infection control practices?\nWhen should gloves be worn?\nWhat should the HHA do if needed supplies are missing?\nSuggested Answers\nHand hygiene is one of the most important practices.\nWear gloves when required by the task, care plan, agency policy, or when contact with body fluids or contaminated items is possible.\nReport missing supplies to the supervisor and follow agency policy.\nRemember\n\nA home can feel casual, but infection control must remain professional.\n\nCanvas source: https://hic.instructure.com/courses/287/pages/hha-201-topic-10-infection-control-in-the-home-setting?module_item_id=3185"
        },
        {
          "title": "HHA 201 Topic 11: Observing, Reporting, and Documentation at Home",
          "durationMinutes": 17,
          "content": "HHA 201 Topic 11: Observing, Reporting, and Documentation at Home\nHHA 201 Topic 11: Observing, Reporting, and Documentation at Home\nObservation, Reporting, and Documentation\n\nThe HHA may be the first to notice changes in the client or home. Clear reporting helps the care team act quickly.\n\nWhat to Observe\nChanges in mood, alertness, confusion, pain, breathing, appetite, sleep, or energy.\nChanges in walking, transferring, balance, falls, weakness, or ability to do ADLs.\nSkin redness, swelling, bruises, wounds, rashes, drainage, or hygiene concerns.\nMedication concerns, missed doses noticed, or client confusion about routines.\nUnsafe home conditions, lack of food, pests, broken equipment, or family concerns.\nRefusal of care, new requests, or tasks outside the care plan.\nReporting Clearly\n\nUse objective facts. Say what you saw, heard, smelled, measured, or did. For example: “Client was short of breath after walking from bedroom to bathroom and requested to sit. Supervisor notified.” This is clearer than “Client seemed bad today.”\n\nDocumentation Basics\nDocument as soon as possible according to agency policy.\nUse accurate times, tasks completed, refusals, and observations.\nDo not document care you did not provide.\nDo not erase, hide, or change facts to avoid trouble.\nProtect documentation from family, visitors, or unauthorized people.\nQuick Learner Check\nWhy is observation important in home care?\nWhat does objective reporting mean?\nShould the HHA document care that was not done?\nSuggested Answers\nThe HHA may notice changes first because they see the client and home environment regularly.\nIt means reporting facts such as what was seen, heard, smelled, measured, or done, not guesses or opinions.\nNo. Documentation must be accurate and honest. Report missed or refused care according to policy.\nRemember\n\nIf it is a change, concern, refusal, hazard, or emergency, report it through the proper channel.\n\nCanvas source: https://hic.instructure.com/courses/287/pages/hha-201-topic-11-observing-reporting-and-documentation-at-home?module_item_id=3186"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "HHA 202 - Maintenance Tasks of Home Care (4 hours)",
      "lessons": [
        {
          "title": "HHA 202: Maintenance Tasks of Home Care Overview",
          "durationMinutes": 17,
          "content": "HHA 202: Maintenance Tasks of Home Care Overview\nHHA 202: Maintenance Tasks of Home Care Overview\nHHA 202: Maintenance Tasks of Home Care Overview\n\nHome care includes keeping the client’s living space safe, clean, comfortable, and supportive of independence.\n\nLesson Objective\n\nBy the end of this lesson, students should feel more confident managing the client’s living space in a way that supports independence, dignity, safety, and quality of life.\n\nWhat This Module Covers\nHousekeeping responsibilities of the Home Health Aide\nThe difference between light housekeeping and heavy cleaning\nWorking from the care plan\nEncouraging client independence\nMaintaining a safe home environment\nReducing fall, infection, food-safety, and emergency risks\nCommunicating respectfully with the client about household tasks\nWhy the Home Environment Matters\n\nA clean and organized home is not only pleasant. It can protect health, prevent accidents, reduce infection risks, and help the client feel more comfortable and in control.\n\nQuick Learner Check\nWhy does the home environment matter in home care?\nWhat should guide the HHA’s housekeeping tasks?\nWhat client value should housekeeping support besides cleanliness?\nSuggested Answers\nA clean and organized home helps protect health, prevent accidents, reduce infection risks, and improve comfort.\nThe care plan and agency policy should guide what tasks are done and how often.\nHousekeeping should support the client’s independence and dignity.\nRemember\n\nMaintenance tasks are part of care because the home environment affects safety, health, comfort, and independence.\n\nCanvas source: https://hic.instructure.com/courses/287/pages/hha-202-maintenance-tasks-of-home-care-overview?module_item_id=3104"
        },
        {
          "title": "HHA 202 Topic 1: The HHA Role in Home Maintenance",
          "durationMinutes": 17,
          "content": "HHA 202 Topic 1: The HHA Role in Home Maintenance\nHHA 202 Topic 1: The HHA Role in Home Maintenance\nHHA 202 Topic 1: The HHA Role in Home Maintenance\n\nThe HHA helps maintain a safe and healthy home, but is not expected to perform heavy professional cleaning.\n\nWhat Home Maintenance Means\n\nHome maintenance in home care means helping with basic tasks that keep the client’s living area clean, safe, and usable. These tasks support daily living and reduce hazards that could affect the client’s health.\n\nRole Boundaries\n\nThe HHA may provide light housekeeping assigned in the care plan. The aide is not expected to do heavy cleaning, deep scrubbing, home repairs, yard work, or tasks for people who are not the client unless the care plan and agency policy specifically allow it.\n\nClient-Centered Care\n\nThe home belongs to the client. Ask before moving personal items, respect privacy, and involve the client in choices whenever possible. Keeping the home safe should never mean taking control away from the client.\n\nExamples of Appropriate Support\nKeeping walkways clear\nCleaning commonly used surfaces\nHelping with laundry assigned in the care plan\nChanging bed linens as assigned\nWashing dishes and tidying the kitchen\nTaking out trash\nReporting unsafe conditions\nQuick Learner Check\nIs the HHA expected to do heavy professional cleaning?\nWhy should the HHA ask before moving personal items?\nName two home maintenance tasks that may be assigned.\nSuggested Answers\nNo. The HHA usually performs light housekeeping tasks assigned in the care plan.\nThe home belongs to the client, and asking shows respect for privacy, dignity, and choice.\nExamples include laundry, dishes, trash removal, light cleaning, bed linens, clearing walkways, and reporting hazards.\nRemember\n\nThe HHA’s goal is not to “take over” the home. The goal is to support safety, comfort, and independence.\n\nCanvas source: https://hic.instructure.com/courses/287/pages/hha-202-topic-1-the-hha-role-in-home-maintenance?module_item_id=3105"
        },
        {
          "title": "HHA 202 Topic 2: Housekeeping Responsibilities",
          "durationMinutes": 17,
          "content": "HHA 202 Topic 2: Housekeeping Responsibilities\nHHA 202 Topic 2: Housekeeping Responsibilities\nHHA 202 Topic 2: Housekeeping Responsibilities\n\nLight housekeeping tasks help create a clean, healthy, and safe living environment for the client.\n\nCommon Housekeeping Tasks\nDusting surfaces used by the client\nVacuuming, sweeping, and mopping assigned areas\nDoing laundry and folding clothes\nWashing dishes and keeping the kitchen tidy\nTaking out garbage to reduce odors and pests\nChanging bed linens regularly to support hygiene\nWhy Simple Tasks Matter\n\nSimple tasks can make a large difference. A clean floor can reduce slips and falls. A tidy kitchen can reduce food contamination. Fresh linens can support comfort, hygiene, and skin health.\n\nWork Safely\n\nUse safe body mechanics, avoid rushing, and use cleaning products only as directed. If a task seems unsafe, too heavy, or outside the care plan, stop and contact the supervisor.\n\nRespect the Client’s Home\n\nDo not throw away items without permission unless agency policy or safety rules require action. Ask the client where they prefer items to be placed.\n\nQuick Learner Check\nName three light housekeeping responsibilities.\nHow can a clean floor help the client?\nWhat should the HHA do if a cleaning task seems unsafe or outside the care plan?\nSuggested Answers\nExamples include dusting, vacuuming, sweeping, mopping, laundry, dishes, trash removal, and changing linens.\nIt can reduce slips, trips, and falls.\nStop and contact the supervisor for direction.\nRemember\n\nSmall housekeeping tasks can have a big effect on comfort and safety.\n\nCanvas source: https://hic.instructure.com/courses/287/pages/hha-202-topic-2-housekeeping-responsibilities?module_item_id=3106"
        },
        {
          "title": "HHA 202 Topic 3: Working With the Care Plan",
          "durationMinutes": 17,
          "content": "HHA 202 Topic 3: Working With the Care Plan\nHHA 202 Topic 3: Working With the Care Plan\nHHA 202 Topic 3: Working With the Care Plan\n\nThe care plan tells the HHA which household tasks are assigned and how often they should be done.\n\nAlways Check the Care Plan\n\nBefore doing housekeeping, check the care plan. The plan identifies which tasks are part of the visit, how often they should be completed, and any safety instructions or client preferences.\n\nDo Not Add Unapproved Tasks\n\nClients or family members may ask for extra cleaning. If the task is not in the care plan, the HHA should not simply add it. Politely explain that tasks must follow the care plan and contact the supervisor if needed.\n\nEncourage Independence\n\nThe HHA should encourage the client to do as much as they can safely do. This helps maintain strength, confidence, dignity, and independence.\n\nExample\n\nMrs. Lopez cannot mop because of arthritis, but she enjoys folding her laundry. The HHA can mop the floor while encouraging Mrs. Lopez to fold laundry at her own pace. This provides needed help without taking away the client’s independence.\n\nQuick Learner Check\nWhy should the HHA check the care plan before housekeeping?\nWhat should the HHA do if asked to perform a task not listed in the care plan?\nHow does encouraging independence help the client?\nSuggested Answers\nThe care plan explains what tasks are assigned, how often to do them, and what safety or preference instructions apply.\nPolitely explain that the aide must follow the care plan and report the request to the supervisor.\nIt helps maintain dignity, confidence, strength, routine, and control over daily life.\nRemember\n\nFollow the care plan, but do not forget the person. Let the client safely participate whenever possible.\n\nCanvas source: https://hic.instructure.com/courses/287/pages/hha-202-topic-3-working-with-the-care-plan?module_item_id=3107"
        },
        {
          "title": "HHA 202 Topic 4: Communicating About Household Tasks",
          "durationMinutes": 17,
          "content": "HHA 202 Topic 4: Communicating About Household Tasks\nHHA 202 Topic 4: Communicating About Household Tasks\nHHA 202 Topic 4: Communicating About Household Tasks\n\nHousekeeping should be done with the client, not around the client as if they are invisible.\n\nAsk About Preferences\n\nWhen possible, ask the client about timing and preferences. This helps the client feel involved in their care and respected in their own home.\n\nRespectful Questions\nWould you like me to wash these clothes today or tomorrow?\nDo you prefer your bed linens changed once or twice a week?\nWhere would you like this item placed?\nWould you like to fold these towels while I mop the floor?\nExplain Safety Concerns Kindly\n\nIf you notice a hazard, speak respectfully. Instead of saying, “This room is dangerous,” you might say, “I noticed this cord is in the walkway. Would it be okay if I move it to help prevent a fall?”\n\nWhen the Client Refuses\n\nClients have choices. If the client refuses a task that affects safety or health, document and report according to agency policy. Do not argue or force the issue.\n\nQuick Learner Check\nWhy should the HHA ask about household preferences?\nGive one respectful question about a housekeeping task.\nWhat should the HHA do if the client refuses a safety-related task?\nSuggested Answers\nIt respects the client’s choices and helps them remain involved in their own home.\nExample: “Would you like me to wash these clothes today or tomorrow?”\nDo not argue. Document and report according to agency policy.\nRemember\n\nRespectful communication turns housekeeping into supportive care.\n\nCanvas source: https://hic.instructure.com/courses/287/pages/hha-202-topic-4-communicating-about-household-tasks?module_item_id=3108"
        },
        {
          "title": "HHA 202 Topic 5: Laundry and Bed Linens",
          "durationMinutes": 17,
          "content": "HHA 202 Topic 5: Laundry and Bed Linens\nHHA 202 Topic 5: Laundry and Bed Linens\nHHA 202 Topic 5: Laundry and Bed Linens\n\nClean clothing and linens support comfort, hygiene, dignity, and skin health.\n\nLaundry Tasks\n\nLaundry may include sorting, washing, drying, folding, and putting away the client’s clothing and linens according to the care plan. Always respect the client’s preferences for clothing, detergent, folding, and storage when possible.\n\nSafety With Laundry\nUse safe body mechanics when carrying laundry.\nDo not overload baskets or machines.\nKeep laundry areas dry to prevent slips.\nFollow label instructions when needed.\nUse gloves or agency precautions for soiled items.\nReport broken machines, leaks, or unsafe laundry areas.\nChanging Bed Linens\n\nChanging bed linens regularly helps maintain hygiene and comfort. If the client spends a lot of time in bed, clean and smooth linens can also help reduce skin irritation.\n\nSupport Independence\n\nIf the client can safely fold towels, sort socks, or choose clothing, allow them to participate. Even small tasks can help the client feel useful and independent.\n\nQuick Learner Check\nWhy are clean linens important?\nName two laundry safety tips.\nHow can the client participate in laundry tasks?\nSuggested Answers\nThey support hygiene, comfort, dignity, and may help reduce skin irritation.\nExamples include using safe body mechanics, not overloading baskets, keeping floors dry, wearing gloves for soiled items, and reporting unsafe equipment.\nThe client may fold clothing, sort items, choose clothing, or direct where items should be stored if safe.\nRemember\n\nLaundry is not just a chore. It supports comfort, dignity, and a clean living space.\n\nCanvas source: https://hic.instructure.com/courses/287/pages/hha-202-topic-5-laundry-and-bed-linens?module_item_id=3109"
        },
        {
          "title": "HHA 202 Topic 6: Kitchen, Dishes, Garbage, and Food Safety",
          "durationMinutes": 17,
          "content": "HHA 202 Topic 6: Kitchen, Dishes, Garbage, and Food Safety\nHHA 202 Topic 6: Kitchen, Dishes, Garbage, and Food Safety\nHHA 202 Topic 6: Kitchen, Dishes, Garbage, and Food Safety\n\nA clean kitchen helps prevent odors, pests, and food-related illness.\n\nKitchen Tasks\nWash dishes and utensils.\nWipe counters and commonly used surfaces.\nKeep food preparation areas tidy.\nTake out garbage as assigned.\nCheck for spoiled food if the care plan allows.\nReport refrigerator, sink, pest, or odor concerns.\nFood Safety Concerns\n\nSpoiled food can make the client sick. If you notice expired food, bad odors, mold, or unsafe storage, follow agency policy. Ask the client before discarding food unless policy directs otherwise, and report concerns.\n\nGarbage Removal\n\nGarbage should be removed as assigned to prevent odors and pests. Use gloves if needed, tie bags securely, and avoid lifting bags that are too heavy or leaking.\n\nRespect the Client’s Choices\n\nFood can be personal and cultural. Be respectful when discussing kitchen cleanliness or spoiled food. Explain safety concerns calmly and involve the client in decisions whenever possible.\n\nQuick Learner Check\nWhy is kitchen cleanliness important?\nWhat should the HHA do if spoiled food is found?\nWhy should garbage be removed regularly?\nSuggested Answers\nIt helps prevent food contamination, odors, pests, and illness.\nFollow agency policy, ask the client before discarding when appropriate, and report concerns.\nTo reduce bad odors, pests, leaks, and health risks.\nRemember\n\nA tidy kitchen protects health and helps the home feel more comfortable.\n\nCanvas source: https://hic.instructure.com/courses/287/pages/hha-202-topic-6-kitchen-dishes-garbage-and-food-safety?module_item_id=3110"
        },
        {
          "title": "HHA 202 Topic 7: Identifying Home Safety Risks",
          "durationMinutes": 17,
          "content": "HHA 202 Topic 7: Identifying Home Safety Risks\nHHA 202 Topic 7: Identifying Home Safety Risks\nHHA 202 Topic 7: Identifying Home Safety Risks\n\nA safe home environment protects clients from injuries, infections, and health risks.\n\nThe HHA’s Safety Role\n\nMany home care clients are older adults or people with disabilities. They may be more vulnerable to falls, burns, infections, and other accidents. The HHA observes carefully, removes simple hazards when allowed, and reports concerns that need attention.\n\nCommon Home Safety Risks\nCluttered walkways\nLoose rugs\nElectrical cords across walking paths\nPoor lighting in hallways or staircases\nWet or slippery floors\nSpoiled food\nImproper storage of cleaning supplies\nImproper storage of medications\nItems placed too high or too low for safe reach\nSimple Safety Actions\n\nThe HHA may be able to move a cord out of a walkway, wipe a spill, clear clutter from a path, or remind the client about expired food. Larger concerns should be reported to the supervisor.\n\nExample\n\nMr. Green uses a walker and has many small rugs in the living room. If he almost trips, the HHA can politely suggest removing the rugs or using non-slip mats and report the concern according to policy.\n\nQuick Learner Check\nName three common home safety risks.\nWhat should the HHA do with hazards that cannot be corrected safely?\nWhy are loose rugs risky for a client who uses a walker?\nSuggested Answers\nExamples include clutter, loose rugs, cords, poor lighting, wet floors, spoiled food, and unsafe storage of supplies or medications.\nReport them to the supervisor according to agency policy.\nThey can catch the walker or the client’s feet and cause a trip or fall.\nRemember\n\nSafety starts with noticing small hazards before they become injuries.\n\nCanvas source: https://hic.instructure.com/courses/287/pages/hha-202-topic-7-identifying-home-safety-risks?module_item_id=3111"
        },
        {
          "title": "HHA 202 Topic 8: Infection Control and Safe Cleaning",
          "durationMinutes": 17,
          "content": "HHA 202 Topic 8: Infection Control and Safe Cleaning\nHHA 202 Topic 8: Infection Control and Safe Cleaning\nHHA 202 Topic 8: Infection Control and Safe Cleaning\n\nCleanliness helps reduce germs and lower infection risk in the home.\n\nWhy Cleanliness Matters\n\nKeeping the environment clean helps protect the client, HHA, family members, and visitors. Germs can spread through hands, surfaces, bathrooms, laundry, dishes, and contaminated items.\n\nBasic Infection-Control Practices\nWash hands regularly.\nWear gloves when contact with body fluids or soiled items is possible.\nWipe and disinfect high-touch surfaces as assigned.\nKeep bathrooms clean according to the care plan.\nHandle soiled laundry carefully.\nAvoid spreading germs from one area to another.\nSafe Cleaning Products\n\nUse cleaning products only as approved by the care plan and agency policy. Avoid strong chemicals unless approved. Never mix cleaning products, especially bleach and ammonia, because dangerous fumes can result.\n\nReport Concerns\n\nReport mold, pests, strong odors, lack of running water, sewage problems, unsafe chemical storage, or any condition that may increase infection risk.\n\nQuick Learner Check\nHow does cleaning help infection control?\nWhy should cleaning products not be mixed?\nName two infection-control practices for housekeeping.\nSuggested Answers\nCleaning removes or reduces germs on hands, surfaces, laundry, dishes, and bathrooms.\nMixing products can create dangerous fumes or unsafe chemical reactions.\nExamples include handwashing, gloves for soiled items, disinfecting high-touch surfaces, bathroom cleaning, and careful laundry handling.\nRemember\n\nClean safely. The wrong chemical use can create a new hazard.\n\nCanvas source: https://hic.instructure.com/courses/287/pages/hha-202-topic-8-infection-control-and-safe-cleaning?module_item_id=3112"
        },
        {
          "title": "HHA 202 Topic 9: Fire, Electrical, and Emergency Safety",
          "durationMinutes": 17,
          "content": "HHA 202 Topic 9: Fire, Electrical, and Emergency Safety\nHHA 202 Topic 9: Fire, Electrical, and Emergency Safety\nHHA 202 Topic 9: Fire, Electrical, and Emergency Safety\n\nHome maintenance includes watching for fire, electrical, and emergency-preparedness concerns.\n\nFire Safety Awareness\nKnow where smoke alarms are located.\nKnow where fire extinguishers are located if present.\nMake sure emergency exits are clear.\nReport blocked exits or nonworking smoke alarms.\nKeep flammable items away from heat sources.\nElectrical Safety\n\nWatch for overloaded outlets, frayed cords, cords under rugs, warm outlet covers, or cords placed across walkways. These concerns can cause fire, shock, or falls and should be reported.\n\nEmergency Contacts\n\nEmergency contact numbers should be visible and accessible according to the care plan. The HHA should know who to call in an emergency and how to reach the supervisor.\n\nClient Participation\n\nEncourage clients not to overload outlets and to keep exits clear. If the client refuses a safety change, report according to agency policy.\n\nQuick Learner Check\nWhy should exits be kept clear?\nName two electrical hazards.\nWhat should the HHA do if a smoke alarm does not work?\nSuggested Answers\nClear exits allow the client, HHA, and emergency responders to move safely during an emergency.\nExamples include overloaded outlets, frayed cords, cords across walkways, cords under rugs, and warm outlet covers.\nReport it according to agency policy and supervisor instructions.\nRemember\n\nA safe home must be ready for everyday living and unexpected emergencies.\n\nCanvas source: https://hic.instructure.com/courses/287/pages/hha-202-topic-9-fire-electrical-and-emergency-safety?module_item_id=3113"
        },
        {
          "title": "HHA 202 Topic 10: Learning Summary and Practice Scenarios",
          "durationMinutes": 17,
          "content": "HHA 202 Topic 10: Learning Summary and Practice Scenarios\nHHA 202 Topic 10: Learning Summary and Practice Scenarios\nHHA 202 Topic 10: Learning Summary and Practice Scenarios\n\nMaintenance tasks help clients live more comfortably, safely, and independently at home.\n\nLearning Summary\nHHAs may be responsible for basic housekeeping such as cleaning, laundry, dishes, trash removal, and changing linens.\nAlways follow the care plan and agency policy.\nEncourage clients to do tasks they can safely manage.\nA safe home reduces the risk of falls, illness, infection, and other accidents.\nWatch for hazards such as clutter, loose rugs, cords, poor lighting, spoiled food, and unsafe storage.\nInfection control and emergency preparedness are important parts of maintaining a safe home.\nScenario 1\n\nMrs. Lopez cannot mop because of arthritis but enjoys folding laundry. A supportive HHA mops the floor while encouraging her to fold towels at her own pace. This supports both safety and independence.\n\nScenario 2\n\nMr. Green uses a walker and has small rugs in the living room. The HHA notices he almost trips. The aide respectfully suggests removing the rugs or using non-slip mats and reports the concern according to policy.\n\nScenario 3\n\nA client asks the HHA to deep clean the garage. The task is not in the care plan. The HHA politely explains that tasks must follow the care plan and contacts the supervisor for direction.\n\nKey Skill for Success\n\nThe best HHAs notice safety concerns, communicate respectfully, support the client’s choices, and follow the care plan without guessing or overstepping.\n\nQuick Learner Check\nWhat are three main ideas from this module?\nHow did the HHA support Mrs. Lopez’s independence?\nWhat should the HHA do when asked to deep clean an area not listed in the care plan?\nSuggested Answers\nExamples include follow the care plan, complete light housekeeping, reduce safety hazards, support independence, use infection control, and report concerns.\nThe HHA did the task Mrs. Lopez could not safely do while encouraging her to do a task she could manage.\nPolitely explain that tasks must follow the care plan and contact the supervisor.\nRemember\n\nA well-maintained home supports safety, health, dignity, and independence.\n\nCanvas source: https://hic.instructure.com/courses/287/pages/hha-202-topic-10-learning-summary-and-practice-scenarios?module_item_id=3114"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "HHA 203 - Dietary Duties for Home Care (4 hours)",
      "lessons": [
        {
          "title": "HHA 203: Dietary Duties for Home Care Overview",
          "durationMinutes": 17,
          "content": "HHA 203: Dietary Duties for Home Care Overview\nHHA 203: Dietary Duties for Home Care Overview\nDietary Duties in the Home Setting\n\nDietary duties help clients stay nourished, hydrated, safe, and independent. The HHA follows the care plan, respects preferences, prevents foodborne illness, and reports nutrition concerns promptly.\n\nLesson Objectives\nExplain the HHA role in dietary duties for home care.\nIdentify basic nutrition, hydration, and meal planning principles.\nFollow special diets and swallowing precautions exactly as assigned.\nUse safe food handling, storage, and kitchen cleanliness practices.\nAssist with meals while respecting independence, culture, dignity, and choice.\nObserve and report appetite, intake, weight, swallowing, and food safety concerns.\nWhy Dietary Duties Matter\n\nFood and fluids support energy, healing, skin health, strength, mood, medication routines, and quality of life. Many clients in home care may have diabetes, heart disease, high blood pressure, swallowing problems, poor appetite, limited income, memory loss, or physical difficulty preparing meals.\n\nThe HHA does not prescribe diets or give medical nutrition advice. The HHA follows the care plan, prepares and serves assigned meals, encourages safe intake, observes changes, and reports concerns to the supervisor.\n\nCore Responsibilities\nWash hands and keep food preparation areas clean.\nPrepare meals and snacks according to the care plan.\nFollow special diet, fluid, texture, and swallowing instructions exactly.\nEncourage the client to do what they can safely do.\nRespect food preferences, culture, religion, and routines.\nDocument intake or concerns when assigned and report changes promptly.\nQuick Learner Check\nWhat is the HHA role in dietary duties?\nCan the HHA prescribe or change a client’s diet?\nName one dietary concern the HHA should report.\nSuggested Answers\nThe HHA follows the care plan, prepares and serves assigned meals, uses safe food handling, supports independence, observes intake, and reports concerns.\nNo. Diet orders and changes come from the care team. The HHA follows instructions and reports concerns.\nReport poor appetite, low fluid intake, choking, coughing, swallowing difficulty, vomiting, diarrhea, weight change, spoiled food, unsafe kitchen conditions, or refusal to follow a required diet.\nRemember\n\nDietary duties are health care duties. Clean hands, safe food, correct diet, and good observation all protect the client.\n\nSources for Instructor Review\nUSDA MyPlate\nLinks to an external site.\nFoodSafety.gov: 4 Steps to Food Safety\nLinks to an external site.\nCDC: Food Safety for Older Adults\nLinks to an external site.\nNational Institute on Aging: Healthy Eating as You Age\nLinks to an external site.\n\nCanvas source: https://hic.instructure.com/courses/287/pages/hha-203-dietary-duties-for-home-care-overview?module_item_id=3163"
        },
        {
          "title": "HHA 203 Topic 1: HHA Role in Dietary Duties",
          "durationMinutes": 17,
          "content": "HHA 203 Topic 1: HHA Role in Dietary Duties\nHHA 203 Topic 1: HHA Role in Dietary Duties\nThe HHA Role in Meals and Nutrition\n\nThe HHA supports nutrition by following the care plan, preparing safe meals, encouraging independence, and reporting changes.\n\nWhat the HHA May Do\nPlan simple meals or snacks if assigned and allowed by the care plan.\nShop for groceries or help make a grocery list if assigned.\nPrepare, heat, serve, and store food safely.\nAssist the client with eating when assigned.\nEncourage fluids or food according to the care plan.\nClean dishes, surfaces, and food preparation areas.\nRecord intake, appetite, or concerns if required by agency policy.\nWhat the HHA Does Not Do\nDo not create a special diet or change diet instructions.\nDo not tell a client to stop a prescribed diet.\nDo not force food or fluids.\nDo not ignore choking, coughing, vomiting, diarrhea, or signs of dehydration.\nDo not serve unsafe, spoiled, expired, or improperly stored food.\nDo not use personal food preferences to judge the client’s choices.\nWorking With the Care Plan\n\nBefore preparing meals, review the care plan for diet type, food allergies, fluid limits, texture changes, swallowing precautions, food likes and dislikes, diabetes instructions, sodium limits, or other special directions. When instructions are unclear, ask the supervisor before guessing.\n\nQuick Learner Check\nWhat should the HHA check before preparing food?\nWhy should the aide avoid changing a diet order?\nWhat should the aide do if diet instructions are unclear?\nSuggested Answers\nCheck the care plan for diet type, allergies, fluid limits, texture, swallowing precautions, preferences, and special instructions.\nChanging a diet order can harm the client and is outside the HHA role.\nAsk the supervisor or nurse for clarification before preparing or serving food.\nRemember\n\nWhen food instructions are unclear, pause and ask. Guessing can put the client at risk.\n\nCanvas source: https://hic.instructure.com/courses/287/pages/hha-203-topic-1-hha-role-in-dietary-duties?module_item_id=3164"
        },
        {
          "title": "HHA 203 Topic 2: Nutrition Basics and MyPlate",
          "durationMinutes": 17,
          "content": "HHA 203 Topic 2: Nutrition Basics and MyPlate\nHHA 203 Topic 2: Nutrition Basics and MyPlate\nNutrition Basics\n\nBalanced meals help support strength, healing, energy, digestion, skin health, and independence.\n\nBasic Food Groups\n\nA balanced meal usually includes a variety of foods. USDA MyPlate encourages fruits, vegetables, grains, protein foods, and dairy or fortified alternatives. The exact meal plan may change based on the client’s health needs and care plan.\n\nFood Groups and Examples\nVegetables: leafy greens, carrots, peppers, broccoli, squash, beans, and other vegetables.\nFruits: apples, berries, oranges, bananas, peaches, melon, or canned fruit packed in juice when appropriate.\nGrains: rice, oatmeal, pasta, bread, tortillas, cereal, and whole grains when allowed.\nProtein: fish, poultry, eggs, beans, lentils, tofu, nuts, peanut butter, and lean meats as allowed.\nDairy or alternatives: milk, yogurt, cheese, fortified soy milk, or other approved alternatives.\nHHA Focus\n\nThe HHA does not need to teach advanced nutrition. The main focus is to follow the care plan, offer balanced choices when allowed, prepare food safely, and report problems such as poor appetite, weight loss, or difficulty eating.\n\nQuick Learner Check\nName three basic food groups.\nShould every client eat the same diet?\nWhat should the HHA report if noticed during meals?\nSuggested Answers\nExamples include fruits, vegetables, grains, protein foods, and dairy or fortified alternatives.\nNo. Diets vary based on health conditions, preferences, allergies, culture, swallowing ability, and the care plan.\nReport poor appetite, difficulty chewing or swallowing, coughing, weight change, refusal to eat, nausea, vomiting, diarrhea, or food safety concerns.\nRemember\n\nBalanced meals are helpful, but the care plan always guides what the HHA prepares and serves.\n\nCanvas source: https://hic.instructure.com/courses/287/pages/hha-203-topic-2-nutrition-basics-and-myplate?module_item_id=3165"
        },
        {
          "title": "HHA 203 Topic 3: Special Diets and Care Plan Instructions",
          "durationMinutes": 17,
          "content": "HHA 203 Topic 3: Special Diets and Care Plan Instructions\nHHA 203 Topic 3: Special Diets and Care Plan Instructions\nSpecial Diets and Care Plan Instructions\n\nSome clients need special diets for medical reasons. The HHA must follow these instructions exactly and report concerns.\n\nCommon Special Diet Instructions\nDiabetic or carbohydrate-controlled diet: may require meal timing and careful food choices.\nLow-sodium diet: may limit salt, processed foods, canned soups, deli meats, and salty snacks.\nHeart-healthy diet: may focus on lean protein, vegetables, fruits, whole grains, and limited saturated fat.\nRenal or kidney diet: may restrict certain fluids, sodium, potassium, phosphorus, or protein as ordered.\nTexture-modified diet: may require chopped, ground, pureed, soft, or thickened foods or liquids.\nAllergy restrictions: require strict avoidance of certain foods or ingredients.\nDo Not Guess\n\nSpecial diets can be very specific. If a client asks for food that is not allowed, stay respectful. Explain that you must follow the care plan and report the request to the supervisor. Do not argue, shame, or secretly change the diet.\n\nWatch for Problems\nClient refuses required diet repeatedly.\nClient does not understand diet instructions.\nFood in the home does not match the diet plan.\nFamily brings foods that may conflict with the plan.\nClient has symptoms such as dizziness, confusion, swelling, vomiting, diarrhea, or blood sugar concerns.\nQuick Learner Check\nWhy must special diet instructions be followed exactly?\nWhat should the HHA do if the client requests food that is not allowed?\nName one common special diet.\nSuggested Answers\nSpecial diets protect health and may be ordered for diabetes, heart disease, kidney disease, swallowing problems, allergies, or other conditions.\nStay respectful, explain that care must follow the plan, and report the request or concern to the supervisor.\nExamples include diabetic, low-sodium, heart-healthy, renal, texture-modified, allergy-restricted, or fluid-restricted diets.\nRemember\n\nThe HHA can support a special diet, but cannot change it.\n\nCanvas source: https://hic.instructure.com/courses/287/pages/hha-203-topic-3-special-diets-and-care-plan-instructions?module_item_id=3166"
        },
        {
          "title": "HHA 203 Topic 4: Hydration and Fluid Needs",
          "durationMinutes": 17,
          "content": "HHA 203 Topic 4: Hydration and Fluid Needs\nHHA 203 Topic 4: Hydration and Fluid Needs\nHydration and Fluid Needs\n\nFluids help the body work properly. Some clients need encouragement to drink, while others have fluid limits that must be followed.\n\nWhy Hydration Matters\n\nWater and other fluids help with body temperature, digestion, skin health, circulation, kidney function, and medication routines. Older adults may not always feel thirsty, and illness or medication can increase dehydration risk.\n\nSigns to Report\nVery dark urine, little urine, or strong urine odor.\nDry mouth, cracked lips, dizziness, weakness, confusion, or headache.\nConstipation or sudden change in toileting pattern.\nFever, vomiting, diarrhea, or sweating that may increase fluid loss.\nSwelling, shortness of breath, or sudden weight gain in clients with fluid restrictions or heart/kidney concerns.\nFluid Restrictions\n\nSome clients are told to limit fluids because of heart, kidney, or other medical conditions. If the care plan lists a fluid restriction, do not encourage extra fluids beyond the plan. Track intake if assigned and ask the supervisor if you are unsure what counts as fluid.\n\nQuick Learner Check\nName two possible signs of dehydration.\nShould all clients be encouraged to drink unlimited fluids?\nWhat should the HHA do if a client has a fluid restriction?\nSuggested Answers\nPossible signs include dark urine, little urine, dry mouth, cracked lips, dizziness, weakness, confusion, headache, constipation, vomiting, diarrhea, or fever.\nNo. Some clients have fluid restrictions. The HHA must follow the care plan.\nFollow the care plan, track intake if assigned, and ask the supervisor if instructions are unclear.\nRemember\n\nHydration is important, but more fluid is not safe for every client. Follow the care plan.\n\nCanvas source: https://hic.instructure.com/courses/287/pages/hha-203-topic-4-hydration-and-fluid-needs?module_item_id=3167"
        },
        {
          "title": "HHA 203 Topic 5: Meal Planning, Grocery Shopping, and Budgeting",
          "durationMinutes": 17,
          "content": "HHA 203 Topic 5: Meal Planning, Grocery Shopping, and Budgeting\nHHA 203 Topic 5: Meal Planning, Grocery Shopping, and Budgeting\nMeal Planning and Grocery Shopping\n\nPlanning helps the client have safe, nourishing foods available while respecting budget, culture, preferences, and the care plan.\n\nPlanning Before Shopping\nReview the care plan for diet restrictions, allergies, texture needs, and food preferences.\nCheck what food is already in the home before making a list.\nLook for expired, spoiled, or unsafe foods and report concerns according to policy.\nPlan simple meals that the client likes and can safely eat.\nConsider the client’s budget, transportation, storage space, and cooking ability.\nEncourage the client to participate in choices whenever possible.\nShopping Safely\nSelect cold and frozen foods near the end of shopping.\nKeep raw meat, poultry, seafood, and eggs separate from ready-to-eat foods.\nCheck dates and packaging for damage.\nGo directly home with perishable foods when possible.\nPut cold foods away promptly.\nRespect and Independence\n\nFood choices are personal. The HHA should not criticize cultural foods, religious practices, or favorite meals. Instead, work within the care plan and report any safety or diet conflicts to the supervisor.\n\nQuick Learner Check\nWhat should be checked before making a grocery list?\nWhy should raw meat be kept separate from other foods?\nHow can the aide support independence during meal planning?\nSuggested Answers\nCheck the care plan, food already in the home, expiration dates, storage space, budget, preferences, and special diet needs.\nRaw meat can spread germs to ready-to-eat foods and cause foodborne illness.\nAsk the client what they prefer, offer choices, and let the client participate as much as safely possible.\nRemember\n\nMeal planning should support nutrition, safety, dignity, and choice.\n\nCanvas source: https://hic.instructure.com/courses/287/pages/hha-203-topic-5-meal-planning-grocery-shopping-and-budgeting?module_item_id=3168"
        },
        {
          "title": "HHA 203 Topic 6: Food Safety Basics",
          "durationMinutes": 17,
          "content": "HHA 203 Topic 6: Food Safety Basics\nHHA 203 Topic 6: Food Safety Basics\nFood Safety Basics\n\nFood safety prevents illness. Older adults and people with health problems may become very sick from unsafe food.\n\nThe Four Basic Steps\nClean: Wash hands, utensils, counters, and cutting boards.\nSeparate: Keep raw meat, poultry, seafood, and eggs away from ready-to-eat foods.\nCook: Cook foods to safe temperatures as instructed by food safety guidance and agency policy.\nChill: Refrigerate perishable foods promptly and keep cold foods cold.\nHand Hygiene\n\nWash hands before preparing food, before assisting with eating, after using the bathroom, after handling raw meat or eggs, after touching garbage, after coughing or sneezing, and after removing gloves. Gloves do not replace handwashing.\n\nHigh-Risk Foods\n\nOlder adults and people with weakened immune systems may need to avoid certain high-risk foods such as unpasteurized milk or juice, undercooked meats or eggs, raw seafood, or foods held at unsafe temperatures. Follow the care plan and agency food safety guidance.\n\nQuick Learner Check\nWhat are the four basic food safety steps?\nDo gloves replace handwashing?\nWhy are older adults at higher risk from unsafe food?\nSuggested Answers\nClean, separate, cook, and chill.\nNo. Hands should be washed before putting on gloves and after removing them when food safety requires it.\nOlder adults and people with illness may have weaker immune defenses, so foodborne illness can be more serious.\nRemember\n\nFood that looks fine can still carry germs. Safe habits matter every time.\n\nCanvas source: https://hic.instructure.com/courses/287/pages/hha-203-topic-6-food-safety-basics?module_item_id=3169"
        },
        {
          "title": "HHA 203 Topic 7: Food Storage, Leftovers, and Kitchen Cleanliness",
          "durationMinutes": 17,
          "content": "HHA 203 Topic 7: Food Storage, Leftovers, and Kitchen Cleanliness\nHHA 203 Topic 7: Food Storage, Leftovers, and Kitchen Cleanliness\nStorage and Kitchen Cleanliness\n\nSafe storage and a clean kitchen help prevent germs, pests, spoilage, and foodborne illness.\n\nSafe Storage Habits\nRefrigerate perishable foods promptly.\nKeep refrigerator and freezer temperatures in a safe range according to agency guidance.\nCover and label leftovers if required by agency policy.\nUse older safe foods first and discard spoiled or unsafe foods according to policy.\nKeep raw meat, poultry, seafood, and eggs away from foods that will not be cooked.\nStore cleaning supplies separately from food.\nLeftovers\n\nLeftovers can be helpful for clients, but they must be stored and reheated safely. Do not serve food that smells bad, looks spoiled, has mold, has been left out too long, or has uncertain safety. When in doubt, report and follow agency policy.\n\nKitchen Cleanliness\nWash dishes, utensils, cutting boards, and counters after use.\nClean spills promptly to prevent falls and pests.\nTake out trash as assigned.\nReport pest problems, no running water, broken refrigerator, unsafe stove, or clutter that affects food safety.\nQuick Learner Check\nWhy should raw meat be stored away from ready-to-eat foods?\nWhat should the HHA do with food that may be spoiled?\nName one kitchen condition to report.\nSuggested Answers\nRaw meat can leak juices and spread germs that cause foodborne illness.\nDo not serve it. Follow agency policy for discarding or reporting unsafe food.\nReport pests, broken refrigerator, unsafe stove, no running water, spoiled food, clutter, garbage buildup, or unsafe storage.\nRemember\n\nA clean kitchen is part of safe care.\n\nCanvas source: https://hic.instructure.com/courses/287/pages/hha-203-topic-7-food-storage-leftovers-and-kitchen-cleanliness?module_item_id=3170"
        },
        {
          "title": "HHA 203 Topic 8: Preparing and Serving Meals Safely",
          "durationMinutes": 17,
          "content": "HHA 203 Topic 8: Preparing and Serving Meals Safely\nHHA 203 Topic 8: Preparing and Serving Meals Safely\nPreparing and Serving Meals\n\nMeal preparation should protect safety, follow the diet plan, and make eating pleasant and dignified.\n\nBefore Preparing the Meal\nWash hands and clean the work area.\nReview the care plan for diet, texture, allergies, and fluid instructions.\nGather safe ingredients and clean equipment.\nAsk the client about preferences when choices are allowed.\nCheck that the client is alert and positioned safely for eating.\nServing the Meal\nServe food at a safe temperature to prevent burns or illness.\nCut food or open containers only if the client needs help.\nPlace needed items within reach.\nProvide adaptive utensils, plates, cups, or straws only as assigned.\nEncourage the client to do as much as possible independently.\nStay nearby if supervision is required by the care plan.\nAfter the Meal\n\nObserve how much the client ate or drank if assigned. Clean the area, store leftovers safely, wash dishes, and report concerns such as poor appetite, coughing, choking, nausea, vomiting, or refusal.\n\nQuick Learner Check\nWhat should be checked before meal preparation?\nWhy should food temperature be checked before serving?\nWhat should the HHA encourage during meals?\nSuggested Answers\nCheck the care plan, diet instructions, allergies, texture needs, fluid instructions, safe ingredients, and client preferences when allowed.\nFood that is too hot can burn the client, and food held at unsafe temperatures can cause illness.\nEncourage the client to do as much as safely possible to maintain dignity and independence.\nRemember\n\nMeal service is not just putting food on a plate. It includes safety, dignity, independence, and observation.\n\nCanvas source: https://hic.instructure.com/courses/287/pages/hha-203-topic-8-preparing-and-serving-meals-safely?module_item_id=3171"
        },
        {
          "title": "HHA 203 Topic 9: Feeding Assistance and Swallowing Safety",
          "durationMinutes": 17,
          "content": "HHA 203 Topic 9: Feeding Assistance and Swallowing Safety\nHHA 203 Topic 9: Feeding Assistance and Swallowing Safety\nFeeding Assistance and Swallowing Safety\n\nClients who need help eating may also be at risk for choking or aspiration. Follow the care plan exactly.\n\nBefore Assisting With Eating\nWash hands and help the client wash hands if needed.\nMake sure the client is awake and alert enough to eat safely.\nPosition the client upright as instructed.\nCheck dentures, glasses, hearing aids, and adaptive equipment if used.\nConfirm food texture, liquid thickness, and swallowing precautions in the care plan.\nDuring Feeding Assistance\nOffer small bites and allow time to chew and swallow.\nDo not rush the client.\nWatch for coughing, choking, wet voice, drooling, pocketing food in the cheek, repeated throat clearing, or trouble breathing.\nStop feeding and report immediately if swallowing problems occur.\nNever force food or fluids.\nAspiration Risk\n\nAspiration means food, fluid, saliva, or vomit enters the airway or lungs. It can cause serious illness. If a client coughs during meals, has a wet-sounding voice, or seems to choke, follow emergency and reporting procedures.\n\nQuick Learner Check\nHow should the client usually be positioned for eating?\nName two warning signs of swallowing difficulty.\nShould the aide force food if the client refuses?\nSuggested Answers\nUsually upright, according to the care plan and swallowing instructions.\nWarning signs include coughing, choking, wet voice, drooling, pocketing food, throat clearing, trouble breathing, or food left in the mouth.\nNo. Never force food or fluids. Respect refusal and report according to policy.\nRemember\n\nSlow, upright, alert, and care-plan guided: these are key ideas for safer feeding assistance.\n\nCanvas source: https://hic.instructure.com/courses/287/pages/hha-203-topic-9-feeding-assistance-and-swallowing-safety?module_item_id=3172"
        },
        {
          "title": "HHA 203 Topic 10: Culture, Preferences, and Mealtime Dignity",
          "durationMinutes": 17,
          "content": "HHA 203 Topic 10: Culture, Preferences, and Mealtime Dignity\nHHA 203 Topic 10: Culture, Preferences, and Mealtime Dignity\nCulture, Preferences, and Mealtime Dignity\n\nFood is personal. Respecting food preferences, culture, religion, and routines helps protect dignity and trust.\n\nFood Has Meaning\n\nFood can connect to culture, religion, family, memory, comfort, celebration, and identity. A client may prefer certain foods, avoid certain ingredients, fast at certain times, or have strong routines about how meals are prepared and served.\n\nRespectful HHA Practices\nAsk what the client likes when choices are allowed.\nDo not criticize unfamiliar foods or eating customs.\nRespect religious or cultural food restrictions listed in the care plan.\nOffer privacy and avoid embarrassing the client during feeding assistance.\nLet the client choose clothing protection, seating, music, prayer, or mealtime routine when safe and allowed.\nReport conflicts between preferences and diet orders so the care team can help.\nIndependence and Choice\n\nEven when the client needs help, they should still be treated as the decision-maker whenever possible. Offer choices such as which beverage, which food first, where to sit, or whether to eat now or a little later if the care plan allows.\n\nQuick Learner Check\nWhy should the aide avoid criticizing unfamiliar foods?\nWhat should the aide do if a food preference conflicts with a special diet?\nName one way to protect dignity during meals.\nSuggested Answers\nFood may be connected to culture, religion, comfort, memory, and identity. Criticism can damage trust.\nRespect the preference, do not change the diet, and report the concern to the supervisor or care team.\nOffer choices, provide privacy, avoid rushing, use adult language, and let the client do what they can safely do.\nRemember\n\nA meal is a care moment. Respect, privacy, and choice matter as much as the food itself.\n\nCanvas source: https://hic.instructure.com/courses/287/pages/hha-203-topic-10-culture-preferences-and-mealtime-dignity?module_item_id=3173"
        },
        {
          "title": "HHA 203 Topic 11: Observing Intake and Reporting Concerns",
          "durationMinutes": 17,
          "content": "HHA 203 Topic 11: Observing Intake and Reporting Concerns\nHHA 203 Topic 11: Observing Intake and Reporting Concerns\nObservation, Intake, and Reporting\n\nThe HHA may be the first to notice nutrition, hydration, swallowing, or food safety problems in the home.\n\nWhat to Observe\nHow much the client eats and drinks if intake monitoring is assigned.\nChanges in appetite, weight, energy, mood, or meal routine.\nDifficulty chewing, swallowing, coughing, choking, or wet voice during meals.\nSigns of dehydration or fluid overload.\nNausea, vomiting, diarrhea, constipation, or abdominal pain.\nFood insecurity, lack of groceries, spoiled food, pests, or unsafe kitchen conditions.\nRefusal to follow required diet, allergies, or texture precautions.\nObjective Documentation\n\nDocument facts when assigned. Write what you saw, heard, measured, or did. For example: “Client ate half of oatmeal and drank 4 ounces of water. Coughed twice while drinking thin liquid. Supervisor notified.” This is more useful than “Client ate badly.”\n\nWhen to Report Promptly\nChoking, coughing with meals, or trouble breathing.\nRepeated refusal of food or fluids.\nVery little intake, signs of dehydration, or sudden confusion.\nVomiting, diarrhea, fever, or suspected foodborne illness.\nUnsafe food storage, spoiled food, no food in the home, or broken refrigerator.\nClient or family confusion about special diet instructions.\nQuick Learner Check\nWhy is observing intake important?\nGive one example of objective meal documentation.\nName one concern that should be reported promptly.\nSuggested Answers\nIntake changes can signal illness, dehydration, swallowing problems, depression, medication issues, food insecurity, or diet problems.\nExample: “Client ate half of sandwich and drank 6 ounces of tea,” or “Client coughed after three sips of water; supervisor notified.”\nReport choking, swallowing difficulty, poor intake, dehydration signs, vomiting, diarrhea, unsafe food, no food in the home, broken refrigerator, or confusion about diet instructions.\nRemember\n\nGood observation at meals can prevent serious problems. Report early and clearly.\n\nCanvas source: https://hic.instructure.com/courses/287/pages/hha-203-topic-11-observing-intake-and-reporting-concerns?module_item_id=3174"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "HHA 204 - Safety Factors in Home Care (4 hours)",
      "lessons": [
        {
          "title": "HHA 204: Fire Safety Overview",
          "durationMinutes": 17,
          "content": "HHA 204: Fire Safety Overview\nHHA 204: Fire Safety Overview\nFire Safety in Home Care\n\nFire safety is an important part of home care. The HHA can help reduce risk by noticing hazards, following the care plan, and knowing what to do if a fire starts.\n\nWhy Fire Safety Matters\n\nHome fires can happen quickly and can become deadly in minutes. Older adults are at higher risk because aging, illness, medication effects, poor eyesight, hearing loss, slower movement, and confusion can make it harder to notice danger or escape.\n\nThe aide cannot make every home completely safe, but the aide can help prevent fires by observing hazards, reporting concerns, and supporting safe daily habits.\n\nThe HHA Role in Fire Prevention\nKnow the emergency number and the home address.\nLook for fire hazards during care tasks.\nFollow agency policy for reporting unsafe conditions.\nEncourage working smoke alarms and clear exits.\nKeep pathways clear when possible.\nDo not ignore smoke, burning smells, warm outlets, damaged cords, or unsafe oxygen use.\nCall emergency services when there is fire, smoke, or immediate danger.\nQuick Learner Check\nWhy are older adults at higher risk during a fire?\nWhat should the HHA do when a fire hazard is noticed?\nWhy is fire safety part of home care?\nSuggested Answers\nOlder adults may have decreased hearing, smell, vision, mobility, breathing strength, or decision-making ability, which can make it harder to notice danger and escape quickly.\nThe HHA should correct simple hazards if allowed and safe, report concerns to the supervisor, and call emergency services if there is immediate danger.\nThe HHA works in the client’s home and may notice hazards before others. Prevention, reporting, and knowing emergency actions help protect the client and caregiver.\nRemember\n\nFire safety begins before an emergency. Notice hazards early, report them, and follow the care plan and agency policy.\n\nCanvas source: https://hic.instructure.com/courses/287/pages/hha-204-fire-safety-overview?module_item_id=3033"
        },
        {
          "title": "HHA 204 Topic 1: Fire Basics and Smoke Alarms",
          "durationMinutes": 17,
          "content": "HHA 204 Topic 1: Fire Basics and Smoke Alarms\nHHA 204 Topic 1: Fire Basics and Smoke Alarms\nHow Fires Start and How Smoke Alarms Help\n\nUnderstanding how fire starts helps the aide recognize hazards. Smoke alarms give early warning, especially when people are sleeping.\n\nImage: Smoke detector on a ceiling. Source: Wikimedia Commons\nLinks to an external site.\n.\n\nThe Four Parts Needed for Fire\n\nA fire needs oxygen, fuel, heat, and a rapid chemical chain reaction. Removing or controlling one part can help prevent a fire.\n\nOxygen is present in the air.\nFuel is material that can burn, such as paper, wood, draperies, upholstery, gasoline, or propane.\nHeat can come from stoves, cigarettes, wiring, fireplaces, furnaces, water heaters, or other sources.\nA chain reaction happens when oxygen, fuel, and heat combine and the fire continues to burn.\nSmoke Alarms Save Lives\n\nMost home fire deaths occur at night and are caused by smoke, toxic gas, or lack of oxygen rather than flames. The smell of smoke may not wake a sleeping person because toxic gases can make sleep deeper.\n\nInstall alarms near sleeping areas and areas where people spend time.\nPlace alarms according to manufacturer instructions.\nKeep alarms away from drafts, air vents, windows, and forced air registers.\nTest smoke alarms monthly.\nCheck batteries twice a year.\nReplace smoke alarms after about ten years or according to manufacturer instructions.\nUse strobe light or vibrating alarms for clients who are hearing impaired.\nEmergency Numbers and Address Visibility\nPost 911 or local emergency numbers in large print near every phone.\nPost the home address near phones so visitors and caregivers can report it quickly.\nMake sure the address is visible from the road.\nUse signs at driveway entrances or forks if the home is hard to find.\nQuick Learner Check\nWhat four things are needed for fire to start?\nWhy are smoke alarms important at night?\nWhere should emergency numbers and the home address be posted?\nSuggested Answers\nFire needs oxygen, fuel, heat, and a chemical chain reaction.\nSmoke and toxic gases can overcome a sleeping person before flames are seen. Smoke alarms provide early warning so people can escape.\nEmergency numbers and the home address should be posted in large print near every telephone or in a clear location caregivers can find quickly.\nRemember\n\nWorking smoke alarms and clear emergency information can save critical time during a fire.\n\nCanvas source: https://hic.instructure.com/courses/287/pages/hha-204-topic-1-fire-basics-and-smoke-alarms?module_item_id=3034"
        },
        {
          "title": "HHA 204 Topic 2: Fire Extinguishers and PASS",
          "durationMinutes": 17,
          "content": "HHA 204 Topic 2: Fire Extinguishers and PASS\nHHA 204 Topic 2: Fire Extinguishers and PASS\nUsing Extinguishers Safely\n\nA fire extinguisher may help with a very small fire, but only if it is safe to use. Escape is always more important than property.\n\nTypes and Placement\n\nA home should have accessible fire extinguishers, especially in areas such as the kitchen, laundry room, garage, and workshop. A multipurpose ABC extinguisher is commonly recommended for home use.\n\nClass A is for ordinary combustibles such as wood and paper.\nClass B is for flammable liquids such as grease and gasoline.\nClass C is for electrical fires.\nCheck the gauge regularly and make sure it reads in the green zone.\nMake sure the pin and tag are in place and the extinguisher has not been used.\nBefore Using an Extinguisher\nCall 911 first.\nMake sure the fire is small and contained.\nKeep an escape route behind you.\nStand about 6 to 8 feet away.\nDo not fight a fire if smoke is heavy, the fire is spreading, or you are unsure.\nLeave immediately if the extinguisher does not put the fire out quickly.\nPASS Method\n\nPASS is the four-step method for using many portable fire extinguishers.\n\nP - Pull the pin.\nA - Aim at the base of the fire, not the top of the flames.\nS - Squeeze the handle.\nS - Sweep side to side at the base of the fire.\nQuick Learner Check\nWhat does PASS stand for?\nWhat should be done before attempting to use an extinguisher?\nWhen should the aide stop trying to put out a fire?\nSuggested Answers\nPASS stands for Pull, Aim, Squeeze, and Sweep.\nCall 911 first, make sure the fire is small, keep an escape route behind you, and stand at a safe distance.\nStop and leave if the fire spreads, smoke becomes heavy, the extinguisher is not working quickly, or there is any doubt about safety.\nRemember\n\nCall first, keep your exit behind you, and never let a small fire trap you.\n\nCanvas source: https://hic.instructure.com/courses/287/pages/hha-204-topic-2-fire-extinguishers-and-pass?module_item_id=3035"
        },
        {
          "title": "HHA 204 Topic 3: Escape Plans and Evacuation",
          "durationMinutes": 17,
          "content": "HHA 204 Topic 3: Escape Plans and Evacuation\nHHA 204 Topic 3: Escape Plans and Evacuation\nGetting Out Safely\n\nOnce a fire starts, every second counts. A small flame can become a major fire quickly, so clients and caregivers need a planned escape route.\n\nMake and Practice an Escape Plan\nDraw a floor plan of the home.\nIdentify at least two ways out of every room when possible.\nIdentify two exits out of the home.\nChoose a meeting place away from the house, such as a tree or end of the driveway.\nPractice the plan at least twice a year.\nPractice in the dark or with reduced vision because smoke can make the home dark.\nTeach children not to hide during a fire.\nAssign someone to assist small children, older adults, or disabled persons who cannot escape alone.\nLeaving Through Smoke\nDrop low and crawl because there is less smoke and heat near the floor.\nGo to the nearest safe door or window exit.\nFeel closed doors with the back of the hand before opening.\nDo not open a hot door; use another exit.\nIf the door is cool, brace yourself and open it slowly.\nClose doors behind you to slow smoke and fire.\nOnce outside, go to the meeting place and stay there.\nNever go back inside.\nIf Trapped\nClose doors between you and the fire.\nStuff towels, blankets, or rugs at the bottom of the door to reduce smoke.\nCall 911 if there is a phone.\nOpen a window if safe and breathe air from the lower part of the window.\nSignal for help with a flashlight or light-colored cloth.\nDo not use elevators in a fire; use stairs.\nClients With Limited Mobility\n\nFor someone in a wheelchair, a ground-floor bedroom with an outside door and ramps at exits can improve escape options. For someone on bedrest, the ramp and slide method may be used only as trained and when needed to move the person away from danger.\n\nQuick Learner Check\nWhy should every room have two ways out when possible?\nWhat should you do if a closed door feels hot?\nWhy should no one go back inside after escaping?\nSuggested Answers\nA fire may block one exit, so a second route gives another way to escape.\nDo not open a hot door. Fire or dangerous heat may be on the other side, so use another exit route.\nGoing back inside can be deadly because smoke, heat, and flames spread quickly. Wait for firefighters.\nRemember\n\nEscape first. Once outside, stay outside.\n\nCanvas source: https://hic.instructure.com/courses/287/pages/hha-204-topic-3-escape-plans-and-evacuation?module_item_id=3036"
        },
        {
          "title": "HHA 204 Topic 4: Oxygen, Cooking, and Bedroom Safety",
          "durationMinutes": 17,
          "content": "HHA 204 Topic 4: Oxygen, Cooking, and Bedroom Safety\nHHA 204 Topic 4: Oxygen, Cooking, and Bedroom Safety\nHigh-Risk Areas in the Home\n\nOxygen equipment, cooking, heating pads, electric blankets, and bedrooms can create fire risks if safety steps are not followed.\n\nOxygen Safety\n\nMedical oxygen is one of the most hazardous types of home medical equipment because it supports burning and is stored under pressure.\n\nNo smoking near oxygen.\nKeep candles, hair dryers, electric razors, and other ignition sources away from oxygen in use.\nPost no smoking signs at entries when oxygen is used.\nSecure oxygen cylinders so they cannot fall, or lay them flat if directed by policy.\nKeep oil and grease away from oxygen equipment.\nCooking Safety\nNever use the oven or stove as a heater.\nDo not store paper, cloth, napkins, or flammable items in the oven.\nNever pour water on a grease fire; cover the pan with a lid and turn off the heat if safe.\nKeep towels and potholders away from burners.\nAvoid loose or dangling sleeves while cooking.\nTurn pot handles inward away from the edge of the stove.\nNever leave cooking unattended.\nKeep an ABC fire extinguisher visible and easy to reach in the kitchen.\nBedroom Safety\nDo not place anything on top of an electric blanket while it is in use.\nNever sleep while using a heating pad.\nKeep a flashlight, walking aids, eyeglasses, and a way to call for help near the bed.\nClose the bedroom door before sleeping to slow the spread of smoke and fire.\nQuick Learner Check\nWhy is oxygen equipment a fire risk?\nWhat should be done for a grease fire in a pan if it is safe?\nWhy should the bedroom door be closed before sleeping?\nSuggested Answers\nOxygen supports burning and can make fire spread faster. Oxygen cylinders are also under pressure and must be handled safely.\nDo not use water. Leave the pan on the stove, cover it with a lid, turn off the heat if safe, and call for help if needed.\nA closed bedroom door can slow the spread of smoke and fire, giving more time to wake up and escape.\nRemember\n\nOxygen, cooking, and heat-producing items require extra attention because small mistakes can become dangerous quickly.\n\nCanvas source: https://hic.instructure.com/courses/287/pages/hha-204-topic-4-oxygen-cooking-and-bedroom-safety?module_item_id=3037"
        },
        {
          "title": "HHA 204 Topic 5: Electrical and Appliance Safety",
          "durationMinutes": 17,
          "content": "HHA 204 Topic 5: Electrical and Appliance Safety\nHHA 204 Topic 5: Electrical and Appliance Safety\nPreventing Electrical Fires\n\nOutdated wiring, overloaded circuits, damaged cords, and unsafe appliance use can cause shocks or fires.\n\nElectrical Warning Signs\nWarm outlet or switch cover plate.\nSmoke or unusual odor from an appliance.\nFrayed, cracked, or damaged cords.\nExposed wiring from outlets or switches.\nFrequent tripped breakers or blown fuses.\nSparks or buzzing from outlets or appliances.\nOutlet, Cord, and Extension Cord Safety\nTurn off or unplug cords if an outlet or switch cover feels warm and report it.\nDo not remove the grounding prong from a three-prong plug.\nDo not cover electrical cords with rugs or carpet.\nDo not attach cords to walls or baseboards with nails or staples.\nReplace frayed or cracked cords immediately.\nUse extension cords only temporarily.\nDo not run extension cords through walls, floors, windows, ceilings, or doors.\nDo not overload extension cords or piggyback cords.\nUse UL-listed power strips with built-in circuit breakers.\nAppliance and Light Safety\nUnplug appliances when not in use when appropriate.\nInsert plugs fully before turning appliances on.\nDo not leave appliances on overnight.\nDo not repair appliances yourself.\nKeep appliances away from sinks and hot surfaces.\nUnplug appliances that smoke or smell unusual and have them inspected.\nUse correct wattage bulbs; use no more than 60 watts if the correct wattage is unknown.\nAvoid halogen lamps near curtains or combustible materials.\nClean dryer vent hoses twice a year because lint can catch fire.\nConsider automatic shutoff irons for clients who are forgetful.\nQuick Learner Check\nWhat should an aide do if an outlet cover feels warm?\nWhy should cords not be placed under rugs?\nWhy are dryer vents a fire concern?\nSuggested Answers\nTurn the switch off or unplug cords from the outlet if safe, report the hazard, and have the wiring checked by a qualified person.\nRugs can hide damage, trap heat, and become fuel for a fire.\nLint builds up in dryer vents and can ignite from heat, so vents should be inspected and cleaned regularly.\nRemember\n\nWarm outlets, damaged cords, overloaded power, and smoking appliances are warning signs. Report them promptly.\n\nCanvas source: https://hic.instructure.com/courses/287/pages/hha-204-topic-5-electrical-and-appliance-safety?module_item_id=3038"
        },
        {
          "title": "HHA 204 Topic 6: Gas, Space Heaters, Fireplaces, and Flammables",
          "durationMinutes": 17,
          "content": "HHA 204 Topic 6: Gas, Space Heaters, Fireplaces, and Flammables\nHHA 204 Topic 6: Gas, Space Heaters, Fireplaces, and Flammables\nHeat and Fuel Hazards\n\nGas, propane, space heaters, fireplaces, and flammable liquids can be useful, but they must be handled with caution.\n\nGas and Propane Safety\n\nNatural gas is lighter than air and rises. Propane is heavier than air and settles near the floor. Both usually have an odor added that smells like rotten eggs so leaks can be detected.\n\nKnow where the main shutoff valve is located if this is part of the care plan or household safety instructions.\nDo not store or use portable propane tanks inside the home.\nIf gas is smelled or heard, do not light matches, smoke, turn on electrical switches, or use the phone inside.\nOpen doors or windows to the outside if safe.\nEvacuate everyone and call the utility company or emergency services from a neighbor’s phone or outside location.\nDo not return until the utility or emergency personnel says it is safe.\nSpace Heater Safety\nDo not use space heaters in high-traffic areas such as hallways.\nNever leave a space heater on when sleeping or when no one is home.\nKeep bedding, drapes, rugs, furniture, and flammable liquids at least three feet away.\nUse heaters with safety features such as automatic shutoff when available.\nGas and kerosene heaters need ventilation and may require carbon monoxide detectors.\nNever refuel a heater while it is running.\nFireplaces and Wood Stoves\nUse seasoned wood to reduce creosote buildup.\nHave the stove pipe or chimney cleaned yearly.\nDo not overload stoves or fireplaces with wood.\nKeep towels, drapes, newspapers, and other combustibles away.\nUse a fireplace screen.\nPut ashes and embers in a metal container outside on a fireproof surface.\nKeep tree branches at least ten feet away from the chimney or stovepipe.\nFlammable Materials\nStore kerosene, gasoline, paint thinner, and similar materials in clearly marked sealed containers.\nStore oily supplies in metal containers.\nKeep flammable liquids and supplies away from sunlight and heat sources.\nLet hot equipment such as lawnmowers cool before refueling.\nRecycle newspapers and magazines so they do not build up as fuel for a fire.\nQuick Learner Check\nWhat should be avoided if gas is smelled or heard?\nHow far should flammable materials be kept from space heaters?\nWhy should ashes be placed in a metal container outside?\nSuggested Answers\nDo not smoke, light matches, use electrical switches, or use a phone inside because sparks can ignite gas.\nKeep flammable materials at least three feet away from space heaters.\nAshes and embers can stay hot and may ignite nearby materials. A metal container on a fireproof surface reduces this risk.\nRemember\n\nFuel plus heat can become fire. Keep heat sources clear, ventilated, and supervised.\n\nCanvas source: https://hic.instructure.com/courses/287/pages/hha-204-topic-6-gas-space-heaters-fireplaces-and-flammables?module_item_id=3039"
        },
        {
          "title": "HHA 204 Topic 7: Smoking, Grills, and Final Fire Safety Habits",
          "durationMinutes": 17,
          "content": "HHA 204 Topic 7: Smoking, Grills, and Final Fire Safety Habits\nHHA 204 Topic 7: Smoking, Grills, and Final Fire Safety Habits\nPreventing Common Deadly Fire Hazards\n\nSmoking remains a leading cause of deadly home fires. Outdoor grills and charcoal also create serious risks if used indoors or near flammable materials.\n\nSmoking Safety\nDo not allow a confused client or client with dementia to smoke without supervision.\nNever leave smoking materials unattended.\nNever allow smoking in bed or while lying down.\nBefore bed, check rugs and chair cushions for dropped ashes.\nIf a cushion or chair has been burned, move it outside away from the house and call the fire department.\nUse safe ashtrays and soak ashes with water before disposal.\nDo not store matches or lighters in sunlight or near heat.\nTeach children that matches and lighters are not toys.\nGrill and Charcoal Safety\nNever use hibachis, charcoal grills, or barbecue equipment indoors.\nBurning charcoal gives off dangerous carbon monoxide.\nUse solid firestarter made for charcoal instead of unsafe liquids.\nKeep grills away from porch ceilings, walls, shrubs, and other flammable materials.\nFinal Fire Safety Habits for HHAs\nKeep smoke alarms working.\nKeep fire extinguishers accessible and checked.\nKnow emergency numbers and the home address.\nKeep exits and pathways clear.\nPractice escape plans.\nCall the fire department without delay when there is a fire, smoke, gas leak, or immediate danger.\nReport unsafe home conditions according to agency policy.\nQuick Learner Check\nWhy is smoking in bed dangerous?\nWhy should charcoal grills never be used indoors?\nWhen should the fire department be called?\nSuggested Answers\nThe person may fall asleep with a lit cigarette, causing bedding or clothing to catch fire.\nCharcoal releases carbon monoxide, which can cause deadly poisoning indoors.\nCall immediately when there is a fire, smoke, suspected gas leak, burning smell with danger, or any situation that may become life-threatening. Do not delay out of fear of bothering the fire department.\nRemember\n\nDo not wait to call for help. Fire can become life-threatening in seconds.\n\nCanvas source: https://hic.instructure.com/courses/287/pages/hha-204-topic-7-smoking-grills-and-final-fire-safety-habits?module_item_id=3040"
        },
        {
          "title": "HHA 204: Fall Prevention Overview",
          "durationMinutes": 17,
          "content": "HHA 204: Fall Prevention Overview\nHHA 204: Fall Prevention Overview\nPreventing Falls in Home Care\n\nFalls are a serious health concern for older adults. The HHA can help reduce fall risk by observing hazards, supporting safe movement, and encouraging activity within the care plan.\n\nWhy Fall Prevention Matters\n\nMore than 30 percent of people over age 65 fall each year. Most falls occur at home during everyday activities such as walking, climbing stairs, or getting in and out of bed.\n\nFalls can cause injury, hip fractures, loss of confidence, fear, depression, and reduced independence. Even when a fall does not cause injury, fear of falling may make a client stop doing activities they enjoy.\n\nActivity Is Part of Prevention\n\nFall prevention does not mean keeping the client inactive. Inactivity can cause stiff joints, muscle weakness, poor coordination, depression, and more fear. These changes can actually increase the risk for more falls.\n\nEncourage enjoyable activities allowed by the care plan.\nSupport regular exercise when ordered or approved.\nPromote strength, coordination, confidence, and independence.\nReport fear of falling or reduced activity to the supervisor.\nQuick Learner Check\nWhy can fear of falling increase future fall risk?\nWhere do many falls happen for older adults?\nWhat is the HHA role in fall prevention?\nSuggested Answers\nFear can cause the client to avoid activity. Inactivity may lead to weakness, stiff joints, poor coordination, depression, and less confidence, which can raise fall risk.\nMany falls happen at home during everyday activities such as walking, stairs, toileting, or getting in and out of bed.\nThe HHA observes hazards, follows the care plan, encourages safe activity, uses proper body mechanics, and reports risks or changes.\nRemember\n\nFall prevention means reducing hazards while still supporting safe movement and independence.\n\nCanvas source: https://hic.instructure.com/courses/287/pages/hha-204-fall-prevention-overview?module_item_id=3041"
        },
        {
          "title": "HHA 204 Topic 8: Fall Risk Factors",
          "durationMinutes": 17,
          "content": "HHA 204 Topic 8: Fall Risk Factors\nHHA 204 Topic 8: Fall Risk Factors\nWho Is at Higher Risk for Falls?\n\nKnowing common fall risk factors helps the HHA notice problems early and report them before an injury occurs.\n\nChanges With Aging\n\nBalance depends on the heart and blood vessels, muscles, nerves, eyes, and ears working together. These systems may decline with age, increasing fall risk. Older adults may also become more dependent on vision for balance, especially at night.\n\nHealth Conditions That Increase Risk\nArthritis or joint pain.\nCardiovascular disease.\nDementia or confusion.\nStroke.\nParkinson's disease.\nOsteoporosis.\nSeizures.\nWeakness, stiff joints, dizziness, poor eyesight, or difficulty walking.\nOther Risk Factors\nAlcohol use, which impairs balance.\nMedications that cause drowsiness, dizziness, weakness, or low blood pressure.\nRushing, stress, illness, or being upset.\nPoor footwear.\nPoor lighting or getting up at night without glasses.\nQuick Learner Check\nName two health conditions that can increase fall risk.\nWhy can nighttime be risky for older adults?\nWhat medication side effects can contribute to falls?\nSuggested Answers\nExamples include arthritis, cardiovascular disease, dementia, stroke, Parkinson's disease, osteoporosis, seizures, weakness, dizziness, or difficulty walking.\nOlder adults may depend more on vision for balance. At night they may be disoriented, may not wear glasses, or may not turn on enough lights.\nDrowsiness, dizziness, weakness, and changes in blood pressure can increase fall risk.\nRemember\n\nA fall risk factor is a warning sign. Observe carefully and report changes to the supervisor.\n\nCanvas source: https://hic.instructure.com/courses/287/pages/hha-204-topic-8-fall-risk-factors?module_item_id=3042"
        },
        {
          "title": "HHA 204 Topic 9: Caregiver Safety, Body Mechanics, and Footwear",
          "durationMinutes": 17,
          "content": "HHA 204 Topic 9: Caregiver Safety, Body Mechanics, and Footwear\nHHA 204 Topic 9: Caregiver Safety, Body Mechanics, and Footwear\nProtecting the Client and Yourself\n\nCaregivers can fall too. Safe body mechanics, calm pacing, and proper footwear protect both the HHA and the client.\n\nSafe Caregiver Habits\nPosition your body correctly before helping a client move.\nUse proper body mechanics.\nDo not rush your tasks or rush the client.\nMake more trips with smaller loads instead of carrying heavy or bulky items.\nDo not carry packages that block your vision.\nUse extra caution when the client is stressed, ill, upset, or unsteady.\nFootwear Matters\n\nShoes play a major role in fall prevention. Shoes should support safe walking indoors and outdoors.\n\nChoose non-skid shoes with low heels and good tread.\nAvoid smooth leather soles or worn smooth tennis shoes.\nFasten laces or Velcro securely.\nUse traction devices such as shoe chains or studded soles when walking on snow or ice if appropriate.\nUse sand, cat litter, or commercial ice melt where ice cannot be fully removed.\nCommunication During Movement\n\nBefore helping a client move, explain what you are going to do. Move at the client's pace, give clear directions, and stay close enough to assist without blocking the client's movement.\n\nQuick Learner Check\nWhy should the HHA avoid rushing the client?\nWhat type of shoes are safest for fall prevention?\nWhy should bulky items be carried in smaller loads?\nSuggested Answers\nRushing can make the client stressed, unsteady, or more likely to trip or lose balance.\nShoes should have non-skid soles, low heels, good tread, and secure laces or Velcro.\nBulky items can block vision or affect balance. Smaller loads help the caregiver walk more safely.\nRemember\n\nA calm pace, clear communication, and safe footwear help prevent falls for both the client and caregiver.\n\nCanvas source: https://hic.instructure.com/courses/287/pages/hha-204-topic-9-caregiver-safety-body-mechanics-and-footwear?module_item_id=3043"
        },
        {
          "title": "HHA 204 Topic 10: Home Hazards and Safe Rooms",
          "durationMinutes": 17,
          "content": "HHA 204 Topic 10: Home Hazards and Safe Rooms\nHHA 204 Topic 10: Home Hazards and Safe Rooms\nReducing Fall Hazards in Daily Living Areas\n\nAt least one third of falls in older adults are related to hazards in and around the home. Many hazards can be reduced with simple changes.\n\nFloor and Pathway Hazards\nRemove loose rugs and runners when possible.\nUse rubber backing, rubber matting, or double-stick tape if a rug must remain.\nKeep electrical cords along the wall and out of pathways.\nNever place cords under rugs or runners.\nKeep walkways free from fans, heaters, clutter, toys, pet items, magazines, baskets, and low stools.\nClean spills immediately.\nUse non-skid mats near sinks or wet areas.\nFurniture and Phones\nUse chairs with back support and armrests.\nAvoid low objects that blend into the carpet, such as glass coffee tables or low baskets.\nKeep telephones easy to reach to prevent rushing.\nConsider several phones or a portable phone if allowed by the care plan and household preference.\nKitchen and Storage Safety\nPlace frequently used items between hip and eye level.\nUse a reacher to avoid unnecessary bending or reaching.\nDo not climb on unstable chairs or furniture to reach high items.\nKeep the floor dry and uncluttered.\nQuick Learner Check\nWhy are loose rugs a fall hazard?\nWhere should frequently used items be stored?\nWhy should telephones be easy to reach?\nSuggested Answers\nLoose rugs can slide, curl, or catch the foot, causing the client to trip or slip.\nItems used often should be stored between hip and eye level to reduce bending, reaching, or climbing.\nRushing to answer a phone can increase fall risk, especially for a client who is unsteady.\nRemember\n\nClear pathways, stable furniture, and easy-to-reach items make daily movement safer.\n\nCanvas source: https://hic.instructure.com/courses/287/pages/hha-204-topic-10-home-hazards-and-safe-rooms?module_item_id=3044"
        },
        {
          "title": "HHA 204 Topic 11: Bedroom, Bathroom, Lighting, and Stairs",
          "durationMinutes": 17,
          "content": "HHA 204 Topic 11: Bedroom, Bathroom, Lighting, and Stairs\nHHA 204 Topic 11: Bedroom, Bathroom, Lighting, and Stairs\nHigh-Risk Areas for Falls\n\nBedrooms, bathrooms, stairs, and outdoor steps are common places for falls. The HHA should notice safety risks and report concerns.\n\nBedroom Safety\nMake sure the bed is a comfortable height and firm enough for safe transfers.\nThe bed should be stable and not slide when the client gets in or out.\nLock wheel brakes on beds with wheels.\nKeep a telephone, lamp, flashlight, glasses, cane, or walker near the bed when appropriate.\nKeep heating pad and electric blanket cords out of pathways.\nAvoid long, loose clothing that can cause tripping.\nIf the client gets dizzy when rising, encourage sitting at the edge of the bed or chair for a few minutes before standing, according to the care plan.\nBathroom Safety\nUse textured strips or appliques in tubs and showers.\nUse rubber slip-resistant mats in and outside the tub or shower.\nAvoid oil in bath water because it can increase slipping.\nUse slip-resistant grab bars inside and outside the tub or shower and next to the toilet.\nUse a shower chair or bench for someone who is unsteady, if ordered or approved.\nUse a handheld showerhead when helpful.\nA raised toilet seat with armrests may help weak or unsteady clients.\nLighting, Stairs, and Outdoor Areas\nUse adequate lighting, especially at night.\nUse the maximum wattage recommended by the fixture manufacturer.\nTouch lamps or adapters may help clients with arthritis or painful joints.\nMake sure stairs are well lit and each step is visible.\nCheck that stair carpet is securely fastened.\nDo not place loose rugs at the top or bottom of stairs.\nMark outdoor step edges with reflective tape and use traction tape when needed.\nKeep pathways and stairs clear of leaves, moss, snow, and ice.\nQuick Learner Check\nWhy are bathrooms high-risk areas for falls?\nWhat should a client do if dizzy when standing up?\nWhy should stairs be well lit?\nSuggested Answers\nBathrooms can have wet, slippery surfaces, transfers in and out of tubs or showers, and limited space for movement.\nThe client should sit at the edge of the bed or chair for a few minutes before standing, if this matches the care plan, and dizziness should be reported.\nGood lighting helps the client see each step clearly, especially the first and last step where falls often occur.\nRemember\n\nBedrooms, bathrooms, and stairs need extra attention because everyday routines often happen there.\n\nCanvas source: https://hic.instructure.com/courses/287/pages/hha-204-topic-11-bedroom-bathroom-lighting-and-stairs?module_item_id=3045"
        },
        {
          "title": "HHA 204 Topic 12: Walkers, Gait Belts, and Safe Assistance",
          "durationMinutes": 17,
          "content": "HHA 204 Topic 12: Walkers, Gait Belts, and Safe Assistance\nHHA 204 Topic 12: Walkers, Gait Belts, and Safe Assistance\nSupporting Movement Safely\n\nAssistive devices and gait belts can help support safe movement when used correctly and according to the care plan.\n\nWalker Safety\nThe client's hands must be free to grasp both walker handles.\nDo not let the client carry packages or small items by hand while using a walker.\nUse a basket or saddle bag attached to the walker when appropriate.\nAvoid heavy objects that can cause imbalance.\nReport problems with walker use, damaged equipment, or unsafe movement.\nWhat a Gait Belt Is\n\nA gait belt is a belt placed around the client's waist when the client needs help with transfers or walking. It gives the assistant a safe place to hold instead of grabbing the client's arm, clothing, or pants. Use a gait belt only when trained and when it is allowed by the care plan or agency policy.\n\nApplying and Using a Gait Belt\nPlace the belt around the waist, usually above the hips and below the ribcage.\nFasten the buckle by sliding the belt through the first slot and then the second slot.\nCheck that the belt is snug enough not to slide upward, but not painful or too tight.\nAsk the client if the belt feels okay.\nWhen walking, place your fingers under the belt for support.\nStand on the client's weaker side if there is one.\nStay close enough to help, but not so close that you block the client's steps.\nFollow training, the care plan, and agency policy for transfers and ambulation.\nIf a Fall Starts to Happen\n\nDo not try to catch the full weight of a falling client in a way that injures you. Follow agency training for controlled lowering and emergency reporting. After any fall or near fall, report it immediately and document facts according to policy.\n\nQuick Learner Check\nWhy should a client not carry items by hand while using a walker?\nWhere is a gait belt usually placed?\nHow tight should a gait belt be?\nSuggested Answers\nThe client needs both hands free to hold the walker safely. Carrying items can affect balance and grip.\nA gait belt is usually placed around the waist above the hips and below the ribcage, following training and policy.\nIt should be snug enough that it does not slide up, but not painful or too tight. Always check comfort with the client.\nRemember\n\nUse assistive devices and gait belts only as trained, and always follow the care plan and agency policy.\n\nCanvas source: https://hic.instructure.com/courses/287/pages/hha-204-topic-12-walkers-gait-belts-and-safe-assistance?module_item_id=3046"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "HHA 205 - Assistance with Self-Administration of Medications (4 hours)",
      "lessons": [
        {
          "title": "HHA 205: Medication Assistance Overview",
          "durationMinutes": 17,
          "content": "HHA 205: Medication Assistance Overview\nHHA 205: Medication Assistance Overview\nHHA 205: Medication Assistance Overview\n\nMedication assistance is serious work. The HHA helps the client stay safe by following the care plan, respecting the client’s independence, and reporting concerns promptly.\n\nLesson Objectives\n\nBy the end of this module, students should be able to explain the HHA role in assisting with self-administration of medications, identify common medication risks, describe safe assistance practices, and recognize when to report medication concerns.\n\nWhat This Module Covers\nWhy medication assistance matters in home care\nThe difference between assisting and administering medication\nHow aging can change the way medication affects the body\nSide effects, adverse reactions, and drug interactions\nMedication lists, labels, questions, storage, reminders, and refills\nSafe assistance with oral, liquid, sublingual, topical, inhaled, eye, and ear medications\nImportant Scope Reminder\n\nA Home Health Aide does not decide what medication a client should take, change the dose, set up medication unless allowed by policy, or give medication as if acting as a nurse. The HHA follows the care plan, agency policy, state rules, and supervisor directions.\n\nQuick Learner Check\nWhat does “assist with self-administration” mean?\nWhy is medication assistance considered serious work?\nWho should the HHA report medication concerns to?\nSuggested Answers\nIt means helping the client take their own medication safely, such as reminding, opening a container, steadying the client’s hand, or reading directions when allowed by the care plan.\nMedication mistakes can cause falls, illness, reactions, or hospitalization, especially for older adults taking several medications.\nThe HHA should report concerns to the supervisor or nurse according to agency policy. Emergencies require immediate help.\nRemember\n\nMedication safety begins with knowing your role, following the care plan, and reporting anything unusual.\n\nCanvas source: https://hic.instructure.com/courses/287/pages/hha-205-medication-assistance-overview?module_item_id=3058"
        },
        {
          "title": "HHA 205 Topic 1: Why Medication Assistance Matters",
          "durationMinutes": 17,
          "content": "HHA 205 Topic 1: Why Medication Assistance Matters\nHHA 205 Topic 1: Why Medication Assistance Matters\nHHA 205 Topic 1: Why Medication Assistance Matters\n\nMedications can improve health and quality of life, but when they are used incorrectly they can also cause harm.\n\nMedications in Home Care\n\nMany home care clients take more than one medication each day. Some medications are prescribed by a doctor. Others may be over-the-counter products, vitamins, minerals, herbal remedies, inhalers, creams, eye drops, or other treatments. All of these can affect the body.\n\nWhy Mistakes Happen\nThe client may take several medications at different times of day.\nThe client may see more than one doctor or use more than one pharmacy.\nThe client may have vision, hearing, memory, or hand-strength problems.\nThe client may not understand why the medication is needed.\nThe client may skip medication because of cost, side effects, or confusion.\nThe HHA’s Safety Role\n\nThe HHA is often present during daily routines, so the aide may notice missed doses, confusing schedules, expired medications, empty bottles, or changes in how the client feels. The HHA does not diagnose the problem. The HHA observes, documents when required, and reports.\n\nQuick Learner Check\nName two reasons medication mistakes can happen at home.\nWhy might an HHA notice a medication concern before others do?\nShould an HHA diagnose a medication problem?\nSuggested Answers\nExamples include many medications, complicated schedules, poor vision, memory problems, trouble opening containers, cost issues, or using several doctors/pharmacies.\nThe HHA may spend regular time with the client and may notice daily changes, missed doses, or confusion during normal care.\nNo. The HHA reports observations and concerns to the supervisor or nurse.\nRemember\n\nWhen medication routines are confusing, the HHA should slow down, follow the care plan, and report concerns instead of guessing.\n\nCanvas source: https://hic.instructure.com/courses/287/pages/hha-205-topic-1-why-medication-assistance-matters?module_item_id=3059"
        },
        {
          "title": "HHA 205 Topic 2: The HHA Role and Scope",
          "durationMinutes": 17,
          "content": "HHA 205 Topic 2: The HHA Role and Scope\nHHA 205 Topic 2: The HHA Role and Scope\nHHA 205 Topic 2: The HHA Role and Scope\n\nThe HHA supports safe self-administration but does not take over medication decisions or nursing responsibilities.\n\nAssisting Means Helping\n\nAssisting with self-administration means the client remains the person taking the medication. The aide may help with approved tasks listed in the care plan, such as reminding the client, opening a container, reading the label, or steadying the client’s hand.\n\nWhat the Client Must Be Able to Do\nIdentify the medication they are taking.\nUnderstand that it is time to take it.\nParticipate in taking the medication as directed.\nCommunicate concerns such as refusal, nausea, dizziness, or pain.\nWhat the HHA Must Not Do Without Authorization\nDo not decide which medication the client should take.\nDo not change the dose or timing.\nDo not crush, split, mix, or hide medication unless authorized and directed.\nDo not set up pill boxes unless allowed by agency policy and supervision.\nDo not give medical advice or tell the client to stop a medication.\nWhen to Ask for Help\n\nIf the client is confused, refuses medication, cannot identify the medication, has trouble swallowing, spills medication, vomits after a dose, or asks the aide to do something outside the care plan, the aide should report the situation.\n\nQuick Learner Check\nGive two examples of medication assistance an HHA may provide when allowed.\nWhat should an HHA do if the client asks the aide to change the dose?\nWhy is scope of practice important?\nSuggested Answers\nExamples include reminding the client, opening the medication container, reading directions, handing the container to the client, or steadying the client’s hand.\nThe HHA should not change the dose. The aide should explain that medication must follow the care plan and report the request to the supervisor or nurse.\nScope protects the client, the aide, and the agency by making sure medication decisions are handled by authorized professionals.\nRemember\n\nThe HHA helps the client follow the plan. The HHA does not become the prescriber, pharmacist, or nurse.\n\nCanvas source: https://hic.instructure.com/courses/287/pages/hha-205-topic-2-the-hha-role-and-scope?module_item_id=3060"
        },
        {
          "title": "HHA 205 Topic 3: Medications and Older Adults",
          "durationMinutes": 17,
          "content": "HHA 205 Topic 3: Medications and Older Adults\nHHA 205 Topic 3: Medications and Older Adults\nHHA 205 Topic 3: Medications and Older Adults\n\nOlder adults may respond to medication differently because the body changes with age.\n\nWhy Older Adults Are at Higher Risk\n\nAs people age, the body may absorb, distribute, break down, and remove medications more slowly. Changes in stomach acid, body fat, liver function, kidney function, and overall health can affect how medication works.\n\nMany Conditions, Many Medications\n\nA client may have arthritis, diabetes, high blood pressure, kidney disease, or other chronic conditions at the same time. Each condition may require medication. The more medications a person takes, the greater the chance of side effects, falls, errors, or interactions.\n\nChanges Are Not Always “Just Aging”\nConfusion, forgetfulness, or depression may be medication-related.\nWeakness, dizziness, fatigue, or falls may be connected to medication.\nVisual changes, ringing in the ears, swelling, rash, stomach problems, or bladder changes should be reported.\nQuick Learner Check\nWhy can older adults have stronger or unexpected medication effects?\nName two changes that should be reported.\nWhy should aides avoid assuming confusion is just part of aging?\nSuggested Answers\nAging can slow absorption, metabolism, and elimination of medication, and many older adults take several medications at once.\nExamples include confusion, dizziness, weakness, falls, rash, swelling, vomiting, diarrhea, constipation, blurred vision, ringing in the ears, or trouble urinating.\nConfusion may be caused by illness, medication side effects, or an adverse reaction, so it should be reported.\nRemember\n\nA new or unusual change in an older adult should be taken seriously and reported.\n\nCanvas source: https://hic.instructure.com/courses/287/pages/hha-205-topic-3-medications-and-older-adults?module_item_id=3061"
        },
        {
          "title": "HHA 205 Topic 4: Side Effects, Adverse Reactions, and Interactions",
          "durationMinutes": 17,
          "content": "HHA 205 Topic 4: Side Effects, Adverse Reactions, and Interactions\nHHA 205 Topic 4: Side Effects, Adverse Reactions, and Interactions\nHHA 205 Topic 4: Side Effects, Adverse Reactions, and Interactions\n\nA side effect is expected. An adverse reaction is new, unusual, or unexpected. Both may require reporting.\n\nSide Effects\n\nA side effect is a known response to a medication. For example, some medications may cause drowsiness. A side effect should be reported when it is severe, lasts a long time, or interferes with the client’s ability to function safely.\n\nAdverse Reactions\n\nAn adverse reaction is an unexpected or unusual response. It may appear quickly or develop slowly over days, weeks, or months. The HHA should write down what happened, when it happened, and what was observed so the report is clear.\n\nDrug and Food Interactions\n\nAn interaction happens when one substance changes the effect of another. Prescription medications, over-the-counter products, vitamins, minerals, herbal remedies, alcohol, caffeine, nicotine, and certain foods can all interact with medication.\n\nReportable Warning Signs\nDifficulty concentrating, confusion, or unusual sleepiness\nRash, swelling, fainting, tremors, stiffness, or extreme weakness\nIndigestion, constipation, diarrhea, vomiting, or appetite changes\nLoss of bladder control or difficulty urinating\nBlurred vision, double vision, hearing loss, or ringing in the ears\nQuick Learner Check\nWhat is the difference between a side effect and an adverse reaction?\nWhy can over-the-counter products still be risky?\nWhat should the HHA write down when reporting a possible reaction?\nSuggested Answers\nA side effect is a known expected response. An adverse reaction is new, unusual, or unexpected.\nThey are still drugs or active substances and can interact with prescription medications or hide symptoms.\nThe aide should note what happened, when it started, what the client said, what was seen, and any related medication routine details allowed by policy.\nRemember\n\nReport unusual changes. Do not decide on your own that a symptom is harmless.\n\nCanvas source: https://hic.instructure.com/courses/287/pages/hha-205-topic-4-side-effects-adverse-reactions-and-interactions?module_item_id=3062"
        },
        {
          "title": "HHA 205 Topic 5: Medication Lists and Questions",
          "durationMinutes": 17,
          "content": "HHA 205 Topic 5: Medication Lists and Questions\nHHA 205 Topic 5: Medication Lists and Questions\nHHA 205 Topic 5: Medication Lists and Questions\n\nAccurate medication information helps the doctor, pharmacist, nurse, client, and caregiver prevent mistakes.\n\nKeep a Complete Medication List\n\nA complete list should include prescription medications, over-the-counter medications, vitamins, minerals, nutritional supplements, herbal or natural remedies, eye or ear drops, inhalers, creams, ointments, patches, suppositories, and injections. Alcohol, caffeine, and nicotine should also be considered because they can affect health and medication response.\n\nImportant Information to Share With Health Providers\nDrug or food allergies\nSpecial diets or food restrictions\nKidney disease, liver disease, or other major health conditions\nAll doctors, pharmacies, and medications involved in the client’s care\nQuestions for the Doctor or Pharmacist\nWhat is the medication’s generic and brand name?\nWhat is the medication supposed to do?\nHow much should be taken, when, and for how long?\nShould it be taken with food, on an empty stomach, or with water?\nWhat side effects should be expected or reported immediately?\nWhat should be done if a dose is missed, refused, forgotten, or vomited?\nWhen the Medication Looks Different\n\nIf a refill looks different in color, size, shape, or markings, the client or caregiver should ask the pharmacist why before taking it.\n\nQuick Learner Check\nName three things that should be included on a medication list.\nWhy should the pharmacist be asked if a refill looks different?\nWhat should be asked if a dose is missed or vomited?\nSuggested Answers\nExamples include prescriptions, over-the-counter medicines, vitamins, herbal remedies, inhalers, eye drops, creams, patches, and supplements.\nA different appearance may be normal, but it must be verified to prevent taking the wrong medication.\nAsk the doctor or pharmacist what to do. Do not automatically double the next dose.\nRemember\n\nA complete medication list is one of the simplest tools for preventing medication problems.\n\nCanvas source: https://hic.instructure.com/courses/287/pages/hha-205-topic-5-medication-lists-and-questions?module_item_id=3063"
        },
        {
          "title": "HHA 205 Topic 6: The Five Rights and Safe Assistance",
          "durationMinutes": 17,
          "content": "HHA 205 Topic 6: The Five Rights and Safe Assistance\nHHA 205 Topic 6: The Five Rights and Safe Assistance\nHHA 205 Topic 6: The Five Rights and Safe Assistance\n\nThe five rights help prevent medication errors: right medication, right person, right dose, right route, and right time.\n\nPrepare Safely\nWash hands before assisting with medication.\nUse good lighting and reduce distractions.\nCheck the expiration date.\nNever use medication from an unlabeled container.\nCheck the label before the medication is removed and again before the container is put away.\nThe Five Rights\nRight medication: the name matches what the client is supposed to take.\nRight person: the medication belongs to this client.\nRight dose: the amount matches the label and care plan.\nRight route: the medication is taken the correct way, such as by mouth, under the tongue, on the skin, in the eye, or inhaled.\nRight time: the medication is taken at the scheduled time.\nDo Not Use If Something Seems Wrong\n\nReport and ask for guidance if the medication is expired, discolored, smells unusual, has no label, is spilled, is refused, or does not match what the client expects.\n\nDocumentation\n\nWhen the care plan or doctor requires a record, document right after the medication routine using the required system. Include the date, time, medication name, dose, and any concerns according to agency policy.\n\nQuick Learner Check\nWhat are the five rights?\nWhy should distractions be reduced?\nWhen should required medication documentation be completed?\nSuggested Answers\nRight medication, right person, right dose, right route, and right time.\nDistractions increase the chance of reading the label incorrectly, missing a step, or confusing medications.\nRight after the medication routine, using the required agency or care-plan system.\nRemember\n\nNever guess with medication. Stop, check, and report when something does not seem right.\n\nCanvas source: https://hic.instructure.com/courses/287/pages/hha-205-topic-6-the-five-rights-and-safe-assistance?module_item_id=3064"
        },
        {
          "title": "HHA 205 Topic 7: Oral, Liquid, and Sublingual Medications",
          "durationMinutes": 17,
          "content": "HHA 205 Topic 7: Oral, Liquid, and Sublingual Medications\nHHA 205 Topic 7: Oral, Liquid, and Sublingual Medications\nHHA 205 Topic 7: Oral, Liquid, and Sublingual Medications\n\nDifferent forms of medication require different safety checks and directions.\n\nOral Medications\n\nWater is usually the safest liquid to use with oral medications unless the label or health professional gives different instructions. Milk and some juices can interfere with absorption of certain medications.\n\nCrushing, Splitting, or Mixing\n\nDo not crush, split, chew, break, or mix a medication with food unless the pharmacist, nurse, doctor, care plan, and agency policy allow it. Some medications can be dangerous or ineffective if altered. If medication is mixed with food as directed, the client must eat the full amount to receive the full dose.\n\nLiquid Medications\nCheck the label to see whether the bottle should be shaken.\nMeasure at eye level using the medication cup, calibrated spoon, or device provided.\nAvoid household spoons because they are not accurate measuring tools.\nPour with the label facing upward to help keep the label clean and readable.\nSublingual Medications\n\nSublingual means the medication is placed under the tongue and absorbed through the lining of the mouth. It should dissolve as directed. It should not be chewed or swallowed unless the directions say to do so.\n\nQuick Learner Check\nWhy is water often safest for oral medication?\nWhy should household spoons be avoided for liquid medication?\nWhat does sublingual mean?\nSuggested Answers\nWater is less likely to interfere with absorption compared with some milk or juices, unless specific directions say otherwise.\nHousehold spoons vary in size and may give the wrong dose.\nSublingual means under the tongue, where the medication dissolves and is absorbed through the mouth lining.\nRemember\n\nMedication form matters. Follow the label, care plan, and supervisor directions exactly.\n\nCanvas source: https://hic.instructure.com/courses/287/pages/hha-205-topic-7-oral-liquid-and-sublingual-medications?module_item_id=3065"
        },
        {
          "title": "HHA 205 Topic 8: Topical Medications and Skin Patches",
          "durationMinutes": 17,
          "content": "HHA 205 Topic 8: Topical Medications and Skin Patches\nHHA 205 Topic 8: Topical Medications and Skin Patches\nHHA 205 Topic 8: Topical Medications and Skin Patches\n\nMedications placed on the skin can still affect the whole body and must be handled carefully.\n\nCreams and Ointments\n\nTopical medication should be applied only as directed. Some creams and ointments are applied in a thin film. Gloves protect the aide from absorbing medication through the skin and protect the client from contamination. A cotton-tipped applicator may be used for small areas when directed.\n\nSkin Patches\n\nMedication patches release medication through the skin over time. The old patch is usually removed before a new one is applied unless the doctor or care plan says otherwise. New patches are placed on approved skin areas and rotated as directed.\n\nPatch Safety Steps\nChoose skin that is clean, dry, and not hairy, oily, irritated, broken, scarred, or calloused.\nWash and dry the area before applying the new patch when directed.\nAvoid touching the medication side of the patch.\nPress the patch firmly so the edges make good contact.\nWash hands after handling the patch.\nKeep used and unused patches away from children and confused clients.\nReport Problems\n\nReport if a patch falls off, the skin becomes irritated, the client removes a patch, or there is confusion about whether an old patch is still on the body.\n\nQuick Learner Check\nWhy should gloves be worn with topical medication?\nWhy is patch rotation important?\nWhat should be reported about patches?\nSuggested Answers\nGloves protect the aide and reduce contamination for the client.\nRotation helps protect the skin and supports proper medication use as directed.\nReport if a patch falls off, irritates the skin, is missing, is duplicated, or the client removes it.\nRemember\n\nSkin medication is still medication. Handle it with the same care as pills or liquids.\n\nCanvas source: https://hic.instructure.com/courses/287/pages/hha-205-topic-8-topical-medications-and-skin-patches?module_item_id=3066"
        },
        {
          "title": "HHA 205 Topic 9: Inhalers and Nebulizers",
          "durationMinutes": 17,
          "content": "HHA 205 Topic 9: Inhalers and Nebulizers\nHHA 205 Topic 9: Inhalers and Nebulizers\nHHA 205 Topic 9: Inhalers and Nebulizers\n\nInhaled medications must reach the lungs to work correctly, so technique and timing matter.\n\nNebulizers\n\nA nebulizer turns liquid medication into a mist. The client breathes through the mouthpiece or mask until the medication is finished, often for several minutes. The HHA should follow the care plan and agency policy for any setup, cleaning, reminders, or observation.\n\nMetered-Dose Inhalers\n\nA metered-dose inhaler releases a measured mist. Proper use requires coordination: the client exhales, starts to inhale, activates the inhaler, breathes in, holds the breath briefly if able, and exhales. If more than one puff is ordered, the client waits the prescribed amount of time between puffs.\n\nSpacers or Holding Chambers\n\nA spacer or holding chamber can make inhaler use easier because the medication is released into the chamber before the client breathes it in. This helps when hand-breath coordination is difficult.\n\nWhen to Report\nThe client cannot coordinate breathing with the inhaler.\nThe client seems short of breath, wheezing, dizzy, or anxious.\nThe inhaler seems empty, damaged, missing, or used more often than ordered.\nThe client has trouble cleaning or using the device safely.\nQuick Learner Check\nWhy can inhalers be difficult for some clients?\nWhat does a spacer help with?\nWhat breathing concerns should be reported?\nSuggested Answers\nThey require hand-breath coordination and the ability to inhale deeply at the right time.\nA spacer holds the medication mist so the client can breathe it in more easily.\nReport shortness of breath, wheezing, dizziness, anxiety, inability to use the device, or use that does not match the care plan.\nRemember\n\nFor inhaled medication, the goal is not just “using the device.” The medication must be used correctly enough to reach the lungs.\n\nCanvas source: https://hic.instructure.com/courses/287/pages/hha-205-topic-9-inhalers-and-nebulizers?module_item_id=3067"
        },
        {
          "title": "HHA 205 Topic 10: Eye Drops, Eye Ointment, and Ear Drops",
          "durationMinutes": 17,
          "content": "HHA 205 Topic 10: Eye Drops, Eye Ointment, and Ear Drops\nHHA 205 Topic 10: Eye Drops, Eye Ointment, and Ear Drops\nHHA 205 Topic 10: Eye Drops, Eye Ointment, and Ear Drops\n\nDrops and ointments require clean technique, correct placement, and respect for client comfort.\n\nEye Drops\n\nFor eye drops, the goal is to get the drop into the lower eyelid pocket and keep it there long enough to work. The client may sit comfortably or lie down, tilt the head back, and look upward. After the drop is placed, the client should avoid squeezing the eye tightly because that may push the drop out.\n\nMultiple Eye Drops\n\nWhen more than one drop is ordered, there may need to be a waiting period between drops. If drops are placed too close together, the second drop may wash out the first. Follow the prescription, care plan, and supervisor directions.\n\nEye Ointment\n\nEye ointment is thicker and may be messier than drops. The applicator should not touch the eye. The client closes the eye gently after application.\n\nEar Drops\n\nCold ear drops may cause nausea or dizziness. If warming is directed, warm the bottle safely as instructed, never in a microwave or on a stove. Check whether the drops should be shaken. The client tilts the head, the prescribed drops are placed, and the position is held as directed.\n\nReport Concerns\nPain, burning, swelling, redness, drainage, dizziness, nausea, or trouble seeing/hearing\nContaminated dropper tip or applicator\nThe client cannot cooperate safely with the process\nMedication directions are unclear\nQuick Learner Check\nWhy should the eye not be squeezed tightly after eye drops?\nWhy should ear drops never be heated in a microwave or on a stove?\nWhat should be done if the dropper touches the eye or another surface?\nSuggested Answers\nSqueezing can push the medication out of the eye before it can work.\nIt can make the drops too hot and burn the ear canal.\nReport it and follow agency policy because the medication or applicator may be contaminated.\nRemember\n\nClean technique protects the client. If directions are unclear, stop and ask.\n\nCanvas source: https://hic.instructure.com/courses/287/pages/hha-205-topic-10-eye-drops-eye-ointment-and-ear-drops?module_item_id=3068"
        },
        {
          "title": "HHA 205 Topic 11: Storage, Refills, Reminders, and Reporting",
          "durationMinutes": 17,
          "content": "HHA 205 Topic 11: Storage, Refills, Reminders, and Reporting\nHHA 205 Topic 11: Storage, Refills, Reminders, and Reporting\nHHA 205 Topic 11: Storage, Refills, Reminders, and Reporting\n\nMedication safety continues after the dose: storage, refills, reminders, and reporting all matter.\n\nSafe Storage\nFollow the storage directions on the medication label.\nKeep medication tightly closed in a cool, dry place unless the label says otherwise.\nAvoid window sills, cars, bathrooms, kitchen sinks, heat, light, and moisture.\nDo not automatically refrigerate medication unless the label says to.\nStore creams and ointments separately from toothpaste or pills to avoid confusion.\nKeep medication out of reach of children and people who may be confused.\nRefills and Underuse\n\nSome clients take less medication than prescribed or delay refills because of cost, transportation, confusion, or side effects. Underuse can be dangerous. The HHA should report empty bottles, skipped doses, expired medication, financial concerns, or repeated missed refills.\n\nReminder Systems\n\nAlarms, labeled containers, pharmacy delivery, and medication reminder devices can support some clients. Clients with dementia may need direct supervision because memory and judgment can be unpredictable. The HHA should follow the care plan and report if the reminder system is not working.\n\nWhen the Client Needs More Help\nThe client cannot open containers or read labels.\nThe client is too ill, confused, or forgetful to take medication safely.\nThe client cannot identify the medication.\nThe schedule is too complicated.\nThe client uses several doctors, pharmacies, over-the-counter drugs, or herbal products.\nThe client refuses, vomits, spills, misses, or takes extra doses.\nQuick Learner Check\nWhere should medication generally be stored?\nWhy might underuse of medication happen?\nWhy may a reminder system not be enough for a client with dementia?\nSuggested Answers\nGenerally in a cool, dry place, tightly closed, away from heat, light, moisture, children, and confused clients unless the label gives different directions.\nIt may happen because of cost, transportation problems, confusion, side effects, expired medication, or missed refills.\nDementia affects memory and judgment, so the client may not respond safely or consistently to an alarm.\nRemember\n\nMedication concerns should never be ignored. Report early so the care team can prevent harm.\n\nCanvas source: https://hic.instructure.com/courses/287/pages/hha-205-topic-11-storage-refills-reminders-and-reporting?module_item_id=3069"
        }
      ]
    }
